gory:Male actors from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:People from Rye, New York]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christopher_Atkins"}
{"title_page": "R179 (New York City Subway car)", "text_new": "{{short description|Class of New York City Subway car}}\n{{redirect|R179|the imprint for a pharmaceutical|Tizanidine|the road|Route 179}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox Train\n| background =\n| name = R179\n| image = File:MTA NYC Subway A train arriving at Broad Channel.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = An R179 train on the [[A (New York City Subway service)|A]] at [[Broad Channel station|Broad Channel]]\n| interiorimage = MTA NYC Subway Bombardier Transportation R179 3015 interior.jpg\n| interiorcaption = Interior of an R179 car\n| service = 2017\u2013present\n| manufacturer =  [[Bombardier Transportation]]\n| factory =Bombardier's Plattsburgh facility\n| family = [[New Technology Train|NTT (new technology train)]]\n| refurbishment =\n| replaced = {{unbulleted list|Possibly all remaining [[R32 (New York City Subway car)|R32s]]|All remaining [[R42 (New York City Subway car)|R42s]]}}\n| formation = {{unbulleted list|47 four-car sets (two B cars)|26 five-car sets (three B cars)}}\n| fleetnumbers =  {{unbulleted list|'''Five-car sets:''' 3010-3049, 3238-3327|'''Four-car sets:''' 3050\u20133237}} \n| operator =  [[New York City Subway]]\n| depots = {{NYCS const|depot}}\n| lines = {{NYCS const|car}}\n| yearconstruction = 2016\u20132019 \n| yearservice = November 19, 2017<br>(4-car sets)<br>February 10, 2019<br>(5-car sets)\n| yearscrapped =\n| numberconstruction =\n| numberbuilt = 318\n| numberservice = 318\n| numberscrapped =\n| carbody = Stainless steel with fiberglass ends and rear bonnets\n| trainlength = 4-car train: {{convert|240.84|ft|m}}<br>5-car train: {{convert|301.05|ft|m}}<br>8-car train: {{convert|481.68|ft|m}}<br>10-car train: {{convert|602.1|ft|m}}\n| carlength =  {{convert|60.21|ft|m}}\n| width = 9.77 ft (2,978 mm)\n| height = 12.13 ft (3,697 mm)\n| floorheight ={{convert|3.76|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n| platformheight ={{convert|3.76|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n| entrylevelorstep ={{convert|3.76|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n| art-sections =\n| doors = 8 sets of 50 inch wide side doors per car\n| maxspeed = {{convert|55|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}\n| weight = 85,200 lb (38,600 kg)\n| capacity = 54 seating 198 standing (A car)<br>56 seating 202 standing (B car)\n| acceleration =  {{convert|2.5|mph/s|m/s2|abbr=on}}\n| deceleration =  {{convert|3.0|mph/s|m/s2|abbr=on}} <br>(full service),<br> {{convert|3.2|mph/s|m/s2|abbr=on}}<br> (emergency)\n| traction = Bombardier MITRAC IGBT-VVVF AC traction motors, model: TM1301SP <ref>[https://scontent-lga3-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/35392381_1943904555661486_6991157772255494144_o.jpg?_nc_cat=0&oh=5d7533d8e57856e6e06cb38760fe1379&oe=5BB8367F R179 Traction Motor Build Plate]</ref>\n| engine =\n| poweroutput ={{convert|147.5|hp|kW|1|abbr=on}} per motor axle \n| transmission =\n| aux = \n| powersupply = \n| gauge =  {{RailGauge|sg|allk=on}}\n| electricsystem   = 600 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]] [[Third rail]]\n| collectionmethod = [[Contact shoe]]\n| brakes = \n| safety = [[Dead man's switch]], [[train stop]]}}\n\nThe '''R179''' is a class of 318 [[New Technology Train|new technology (NTT)]] [[New York City Subway]] cars being built by [[Bombardier Transportation]] for the [[B Division (New York City Subway)|B Division]]. The cars replaced all remaining [[R42 (New York City Subway car)|R42s]] and are expected to replace some, if not all, remaining [[R32 (New York City Subway car)|R32s]].\n\nOriginally, the R179 order was supposed to contain 208 cars that were each {{convert|75|ft|m}} long. In the 2010\u20132014 Capital Program, the order was changed to 290 cars that were {{convert|60|ft|m}} long, similar to the car lengths of the [[R143 (New York City Subway car)|R143]] and [[R160 (New York City Subway car)|R160]] orders, with options for up to 130 more cars. The majority of the R179s were supposed to be in {{convert|300|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} five-car sets because the R179s would be replacing the 75-foot-long [[R44 (New York City Subway car)|R44s]], which were arranged in 300-foot-long four-car sets. A minority of the R179s were to be arranged in {{convert|240|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} four-car sets. In 2011, the order was reduced to 300 60-foot-long cars with no additional option orders. Because of the R44s' earlier than planned retirement and the R32s and R42s assigned to services utilizing eight-car trains at the time, the setup was reversed, with the majority of the R179s being arranged in four-car sets.\n\nThe $599 million contract for the R179s' construction was awarded to Bombardier in 2012. At the time, the first R179 train was set to be delivered in December 2014 and the last train would be delivered in July 2017. Because of manufacturing defects during the construction process, the timeline for delivery was pushed back two years, and the cost of the contract rose to $735 million. The first R179 cars were delivered in September 2016, and the first test train of eight cars was placed in service in November 2017. The test train passed its 30-day in-service test in December 2017, which allowed the remaining R179s to be gradually placed in service. All cars were expected to be delivered by early 2019. However, starting in December 2018, several cars had to be withdrawn from service due to defects, and in January 2019, deliveries were temporarily halted while these defects were being fixed. In January 2020, the R179s were experiencing door problems, leading to the entire fleet being pulled from revenue service for a short period.\n\nIn January 2018, sixteen more cars were added to the order as part of a settlement so that there would be 24 five-car sets instead of the 8 originally projected and 49 four-car sets instead of the original 65. In January 2019, two more cars were added to the order as a part of a settlement for further damages. All cars were delivered by December 2019, and had entered service by March 2020.\n\n==Description==\nThe R179s are numbered 3010-3327. Cars numbered 3010-3049 & 3238-3327 are configured into five-car sets, which are assigned to the [[A (New York City Subway service)|A]] and  based out of [[Pitkin Yard]]. Cars numbered 3050-3237 are configured into four-car sets, which are split between the [[J/Z (New York City Subway service)|J and Z]] (based out of [[East New York Yard]]) and the [[C (New York City Subway service)|C]] (based out of [[207th Street Yard]]).\n\n===Features===\n[[File:From the J Train 05 - R179.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The FIND screen of the R179]]\nThe R179 cars are equipped with updated control systems, [[HVAC]] and public address systems. They are visually very similar to the [[R160 (New York City Subway car)|R160s]], but the two car types are not interoperable with each other due to electrical incompatibilities between them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/160523_1030_Transit.pdf|title=Transit & Bus Committee Meeting May 2016|date=May 2016|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe R179s, like the R160s, employ an advanced alternative to electronic strip maps called the [[New Technology Train#FIND displays|\"Flexible Information and Notice Display\"]] (\"FIND\"), which are manufactured by Axion Technologies Ltd. This includes an [[LCD]] screen displaying the route, route information, and advertisements, as well as a dynamic red, yellow, and green LED strip map that displays the next ten stations, plus five consecutive \"further stops\" to riders.<ref>https://www.nycsubway.org/perl/show?149991</ref> There are three of these in every car. The display updates the stations at every stop, also giving the number of stops to each station listed. This allows for instant route or line changes with the correct information, which includes, but is not limited to, omitting certain stops (displayed as \"Will not stop\" in red). However, the LCD displays on the R179s that show the route are slightly larger than those on the R160s. Additionally, if the FIND has gone blank, the R179 FIND displays \"Route change: this map is not in use\", as opposed to the R160 FIND, which displays \"Listen to train crew for announcement.\"<ref name=\"Metro-NYCS-NTT-Dec2006\">{{cite news|url=http://www.metro-magazine.com/rail/article/210993/new-york-city-bringing-rail-into-the-21st-century|title=New York City Bringing Rail Into the 21st Century|date=December 6, 2006|work=[[Metro Magazine]]|last1=Seaton|first1=Charles|accessdate=January 27, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"MTA-CapitalOversight-Jan2016\">{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/160125_1345_CPOC.pdf|title=MTA Capital Program Oversight Meeting January 2016|date=January 2016|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=January 23, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129071849/http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/160125_1345_CPOC.pdf|archivedate=January 29, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes-NYCSPromiseInfo-Nov20052\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/30/nyregion/30car.html|title=New Subway Cars Promise All Kinds of Information|last=Chan|first=Sewell|date=November 30, 2005|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|authorlink=Sewell Chan|accessdate=October 27, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nycsubway.org/perl/show?149990|title=Showing Image 149990|website=www.nycsubway.org|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> In addition, the R179s utilize the older door closing chimes used on the R142s and R142As, as opposed to the newer door chimes used on the R143s, R160s and R188s. [[Communication-based train control]] (CBTC) equipment will be installed in all R179s that are already on MTA property.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/181022_1000_Transit.pdf|title=New York City Transit and Bus Committee Meeting October 2018|date=October 19, 2018|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|page=188-189|access-date=October 20, 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe R179s are equipped with looped stanchions in the interiors of trains to provide passengers on crowded trains with a greater amount of pole surface area to grab on to. This feature was previously tested on R160A set 9798-9802 and has been implemented on other trains as a part of a plan to fix the subway's [[2017 New York City transit crisis|2017 state of emergency]].<ref>{{Cite AV media|url=https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/10/NYC_Subway_R160_9800_Interior_with_Double_Stanchions.jpg|title=NYC Subway R160 9800 Interior with Double Stanchions|author=Gh9449|publisher=[[Wikimedia Commons]]|date=October 27, 2015|accessdate=May 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe R179s utilize a newer version of HVAC systems, which are noticeably quieter on the outside of the train, compared to previous generations of New Technology Trains. The R179s also have larger picture windows resulting in a tighter cab for the conductors and train operators, since slightly more space was required to accommodate the HVACs.\n\n\n===Recorded announcements===\nThe R179s are the sixth New York City Subway cars to feature recorded announcements. All passenger cars built after the R179s also use this feature.\nCurrent recorded announcements are by:\n* Kathleen Campion: announcements for  the '''[[J/Z (New York City Subway service)|J/Z]]'''. \n*Catherine Cowdery: announcements for the '''[[A (New York City Subway service)|A]]''', '''[[C (New York City Subway service)|C]]'''.\n* Charlie Pellett: announcements to warn passengers of the closing doors, last stop announcements, and current transfer and connection announcements at select stations; formerly provided safety/delay announcements (2006\u20132017).\n* Velina Mitchell: current safety and delay announcements (since 2018). She also recorded the stop announcement for transfer announcements at selected stations referencing the M14-SBS bus route.\n\n==History==\n===Contract plans===\nThe R179 contract originally consisted of 208 {{convert|75|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} cars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/budget/pdf/2008-2013%20Capital%20Plan.pdf|title=MTA Capital Program 2008\u20132013 February 2008|date=February 2008|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 12, 2016}}</ref> Later, in the 2010-2014 Capital Program, the proposed order was expanded to 420 cars (340 for the New York City Subway and 80 for the Staten Island Railway).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nysenate.gov/sites/default/files/articles/attachments/proposed0909.pdf|title=Proposed MTA Capital Program 2010\u20132014|date=September 23, 2009|website=nysenate.gov|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 8, 2016}}</ref> This consisted of 290 base order cars (250 arranged in 5-car sets and the remaining 40 arranged in 4-car sets), with two option orders. The first option called for 50 cars arranged in 5-car sets. There was also a second option for 80 additional cars, which would have supplied cars for the [[Second Avenue Subway]] Phase I service. The proposed MTA 2010-2014 Capital Program pointed towards an order of {{convert|60|ft|m|2|adj=on}} cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/pdf/CP/ProposedProgram.pdf#page=40|title=Proposed Capital Program 2010\u20132014|date=August 2009|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|website=mta.info|page=36|accessdate=September 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe official RFP was issued on June 3, 2010. Bids were due by the following August 13, and in April 2011 the contract was expected to be awarded for $637.8 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/110421_1345_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Meeting April 2011|date=April 21, 2011|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref> However, there were delays with negotiation problems, and the projected cost went up to $748 million in October 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/111024_1415_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Meeting October 2011|date=October 24, 2011|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref> In November 2011, the order was altered to a base order of 300 cars (260 arranged in 4-car sets and the remaining 40 arranged in 5-car sets), with no options.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/111114_1345_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Meeting November 2011|date=November 14, 2011|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe contract was finally awarded to [[Bombardier Transportation]] on March 24, 2012, for $599 million, below the projected cost.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/120423_1400_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Meeting April 2012|date=April 23, 2012|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/docs/r_179_staff_summary_March_2012.pdf|title=R179 Staff Summary March 2012|date=March 2012|website=mta.info|publisher=New York City Transit|access-date=September 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.governor.ny.gov/press/032812MTA-Investment |title=Governor Cuomo Announces $600 Million MTA Investment in Upstate Manufacturing &#124; Governor Andrew M. Cuomo |publisher=Governor.ny.gov |date=March 28, 2012 |accessdate=February 21, 2014}}</ref> The joint venture Alskaw Inc., made up of the companies [[Kawasaki Heavy Industries Rolling Stock Company|Kawasaki]] and [[Alstom]], which built the [[R160 (New York City Subway car)|R160A/B]] cars, protested the award of the contract to Bombardier immediately after the MTA Board approved the contract.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/120521_1400_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Meeting May 2012|date=May 21, 2012|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref> However, the protest was denied, and Bombardier signed the contract on June 4, 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/120625_1400_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Meeting June 2012|date=June 27, 2012|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"bombardier press release 20120406\"/>\n\nA 2012 news report from the ''[[New York Daily News]]'' indicated that a high-ranking MTA official had been in talks with car builder Bombardier Transportation, Inc. for a job.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/mta-exec-mario-guerra-hit-ethics-seeking-job-subway-car-maker-article-1.1052494 |title=MTA exec Mario Guerra hit on ethics over seeking job with subway-car maker |publisher=NY Daily News |date=March 28, 2012 |accessdate=February 21, 2014}}</ref> This prompted an ethics investigation but has since been resolved.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bombardier.com/en/transportation/media-centre/press-releases/details?docID=0901260d80212faa |title=News - Media Centre |publisher=Bombardier |date= |accessdate=February 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe R179s were originally intended to replace all the [[R44 (New York City Subway car)|R44s]], but due to structural integrity issues found on [[New York City Transit]]'s R44s in late 2009, those cars' retirement was facilitated by an [[option (finance)|option order]] of R160s. Additionally, the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] later dropped the plan to order R179s for the [[Staten Island Railway]], instead opting to overhaul some [[R46 (New York City Subway car)|R46s]] to replace the existing R44s there (which has also since been cancelled).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/nyct/procure/addenda/R34211add3.pdf|title=R34211 Notice -Of- Addendum Addendum #3|date=August 11, 2016|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=August 15, 2016}}</ref> The R179s were then intended to retire all remaining [[R42 (New York City Subway car)|R42s]] (50 cars) and [[R32 (New York City Subway car)|R32s]] (222 cars).<ref name=\"Pix11-NewR179s-2016\">{{Cite web|url=http://pix11.com/2016/09/08/new-r179-subway-cars-arrives-in-nyc/|title=New R179 subway cars arrive in NYC|date=September 9, 2016|website=New York's PIX11 / WPIX-TV|access-date=September 9, 2016}}</ref> Some R32s were expected to be retained due to delays in the delivery of the R179s and potential need of extra rolling stock to provide additional service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/news-c-subway/2015/12/11/detailed-study-system%E2%80%99s-longest-subway-line-identifies-opportunities|title=Detailed Study of System\u2019s Longest Subway Line Identifies Opportunities to Improve Service|website=www.mta.info|access-date=July 19, 2016}}</ref> As a result, the MTA planned to spend another $49.2 million to refurbish and maintain 132 to 164 R32 cars through 2018 and then 110 R32 cars through 2019, before finally replacing the remaining cars with the [[R211 (New York City Subway car)|R211As]]. In addition, the MTA anticipated to have most, if not all R179s delivered before the since-canceled [[14th Street Tunnel shutdown|full shutdown of the 14th Street Tunnel]] in April 2019.<ref name=\"v222\">{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/budget/july2015/MTA_2016_Prelim_Budget_Financial_Plan2016-2019_Vol2.pdf|title=MTA 2016 Preliminary Budget Financial Plan 2016-2019 Volume 2 |page=V-222|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref> However, by January 2020, the MTA planned to replace all remaining R32s with the R179s.<ref>{{Citation|title=MTA Board - 01/21/2020 Live Webcast|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y3AOsVFVOoo|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10|time=8:01:40}}</ref>\n\n===Manufacturing issues===\nIn a timeline set in October 2012, the first test train was scheduled to arrive on December 22, 2014, the first production unit was scheduled to arrive on July 27, 2015, and the entire order was to be completed on January 30, 2017.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/121029_1400_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Meeting October 2012|date=October 29, 2012|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 11, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160205142707/http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/121029_1400_CPOC.pdf|archivedate=February 5, 2016}}</ref> After some delays in starting production, a non-operational mockup was built in late November 2013. Delivery of the first 10-car test train was now scheduled for the third quarter of 2014,<ref name=\"bombardier press release 20120406\">{{cite web|url=http://us.bombardier.com/us/press_release_04062012.htm |title=Bombardier in the USA&nbsp;\u2013 Media Center |publisher=Us.bombardier.com |date= |accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> though delivery of the production cars was still scheduled to begin July 2015 and continue through January 2017. However, as NYCTA's and Bombardier's inspectors found cracks due to welding issues in the prototype train's chassis, the entire lot was rejected, and the delivery schedule was pushed back by two years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting: July 2014|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/140728_1200_CPOC.pdf#page=30|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|website=mta.info|accessdate=September 9, 2016|page=30|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801140126/http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/140728_1200_CPOC.pdf#page=30|archivedate=August 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/mta-encounters-delay-replacing-trains-article-1.1883555 | title=Riders on C train will have to wait longer for new Subway cars | work=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]] | date=July 29, 2014 | accessdate=September 30, 2014 | author=Donohue, Pete}}</ref>\n\nThe delays in delivery have increased the cost of the cars from $599 million to $735 million; these additional costs add to the costs required to maintain older cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://secondavenuesagas.com/2015/08/14/as-bombardier-struggles-r179-delay-to-cost-mta-50-million/|title=As Bombardier struggles, R179 delay to cost MTA $50 million|date=August 14, 2015|publisher=Second Avenue Sagas|website=secondavenuesagas.com|last=Kabak|first=Benjamin|accessdate=August 11, 2016}}</ref> In addition, because of the 2-year delay in producing the R179s, Bombardier was banned from bidding on the [[R211 (New York City Subway car)|R211]] contract, which would replace other older B Division rolling stock.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://montrealgazette.com/business/local-business/bombardier-shut-out-of-n-y-subway-contract-because-of-poor-performance-report|title=Bombardier shut out of N.Y. subway contract because of 'poor performance'|date=August 30, 2017|work=Montreal Gazette|access-date=August 31, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Delivery and continued issues===\n[[File:First R179 Delivered to MTA.jpg|thumb|R179 car 3014 being delivered on September 6, 2016]]\n[[File:NYC Subway Bombardier R179 at Rockaway BLVD.jpg|thumb|R179 testing at [[Rockaway Boulevard station]] on October 28, 2016]]\nBombardier built the cars in its [[Plattsburgh, New York]], facility.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.governor.ny.gov/news/governor-cuomo-announces-600-million-mta-investment-upstate-manufacturing|title=Governor Cuomo Announces $600 Million MTA Investment in Upstate Manufacturing|date=September 29, 2014|access-date=September 12, 2016}}</ref> The first five-car set of R179s (3010-3014) was delivered to the [[New York City Transit Authority]] between September 6 and 8, 2016. The next five cars (3015-3019) were delayed and were delivered between November 15 and 17, 2016, forming a complete pilot ten-car train for acceptance testing and evaluation.<ref name=\"AMNY-R179Arrive-Sep62016\">{{cite news|last1=Barone|first1=Vincent|title=New MTA subway cars to arrive for testing, will replace oldest fleet|url=http://www.amny.com/transit/new-mta-subway-cars-to-arrive-for-testing-will-replace-oldest-fleet-1.12276227|accessdate=September 8, 2016|work=[[AM New York]]|date=September 6, 2016}}</ref> The first four-car set of R179s (3050-3053) was delivered between December 21 and 22, 2016. The next four cars (3054-3057) were delivered in January 2017, forming a complete eight-car train for acceptance testing and evaluation. \n\nA delivery plan from January 2017 anticipated a rate of one car per day starting from November 2017, in an effort to have all cars on property by July 2018.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/170123_1345_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting: January 2017|last=|first=|date=January 23, 2017|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|pages=33, 34|accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref> However, additional delays have occurred, and by October 2018, deliveries were not expected to be completed until March 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/181022_1330_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting 10/22/2018|date=October 19, 2018|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|page=116|access-date=October 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/180122_1400_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting January 2018|last=|first=|date=|website=web.mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=January 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/07/nyregion/mta-subway-nyc.html|title=How Can the M.T.A. Rescue the Subway When It Struggles to Deliver Basics?|last=|first=|date=May 7, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 7, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \nDue to continuing delays in the production of the R179s, the order was increased by 16 additional B-cars on January 22, 2018. The order then consisted of 316 cars (120 arranged in 5-car sets and 196 arranged in 4-car sets).<ref>{{Cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j9zfldErD4Q&t=24m39s|author=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting|date=January 22, 2018|accessdate=January 19, 2018|time=24:36}}</ref><ref name=MTA-CPOC-Jan2019/>{{rp|19}} On January 22, 2019, another settlement increased the order by 2 additional B-cars.<ref>{{Cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cKNSPq8j164|author=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting|date=January 22, 2019|accessdate=January 22, 2019|time=31:04}}</ref> As of July 2019, deliveries were not expected to be completed until November 2019.<ref>http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/190722_1430_CPOC.pdf page 86</ref>\n\nThe four-car R179 sets were placed into revenue service on the [[J/Z (New York City Subway service)|J]] on November 19, 2017 for in-service acceptance testing after slightly over a year of successful non-revenue service tests.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://pix11.com/2017/11/25/14-months-after-delivery-new-subway-cars-enter-mtas-final-testing-stage-with-riders-on-j-line/|title=14 months after delivery, new subway cars enter MTA\u2019s final testing stage with riders on J Line|date=November 25, 2017|work=New York's PIX11 / WPIX-TV|access-date=November 26, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> During the first two weeks of the testing period, the MTA identified three major issues in the train, which have since been fixed.<ref>\n{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/mta-newest-fleet-2m-subway-cars-face-crippling-mishap-article-1.3688782|title=MTA's newest fleet of $2M subway cars face third crippling mishap|work=NY Daily News|access-date=December 12, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://secondavenuesagas.com/2017/12/10/testing-woes-plague-bombardiers-faulty-r179-cars/|title=Testing woes plague Bombardier's faulty R179 cars - Second Ave. Sagas|date=December 10, 2017|work=Second Ave. Sagas|access-date=December 12, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ny.curbed.com/2017/12/11/16761874/mta-nyc-subway-r179-train-problems|title=MTA\u2019s new fleet of subway cars plagued by mishaps|work=Curbed NY|access-date=December 12, 2017}}</ref> After successful completion, the four-car R179 sets officially entered revenue service on December 27, 2017, a month later than originally planned.<ref name=\"CPOC-Jan2018\">{{Cite web|author=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting|date=January 22, 2018|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/180122_1400_CPOC.pdf|accessdate=January 19, 2018|page=46}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=BombardierRail|number=951812524340645889|title=We\u2019re pleased to report that our R179 cars for #NewYorkCityTransit have successfully completed their extensive on-site qualification testing and 30-day in-service demonstration test and are starting to enter regular passenger service. #Plattsburgh #NewYork|date=January 12, 2018|access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> The pilot five-car R179 sets underwent specification modifications at Bombardier's [[Bath, New York|Kanona]] Facility in summer 2018 and were re-delivered for further testing.<ref name=CPOC-Jan2018/> After two years of modifications, the train was placed into service on the [[A (New York City Subway service)|A]] for a 30-day in-service test on February 10, 2019. The train completed the test on March 11, 2019 and entered regular service the next day.<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://twitter.com/BombardierRail/status/1105505014737485825 | title=Completion of 30-day revenue service test for the 10-car train | work=Bombardier Rail | date=March 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBy the start of December 2018, some trains had to be taken out of service due to manufacturing defects such as doors, propulsion, and air compressors issues.<ref>{{cite web | last=Rivoli | first=Dan | title=NYC Transit's new subway cars suffering on the tracks, dozens pulled from rails | website=New York Daily News | date=January 9, 2019 | url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/ny-metro-r179-mta-train-car-20190108-story.html | access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref> The next month, the MTA revealed that 162 cars had been delivered, of which 128 (comprising sixteen 8-car trains) had been placed in service.<ref name=\"MTA-CPOC-Jan2019\">{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/190122_1400_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting|date=January 2019|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|access-date=January 18, 2019}}</ref>{{rp|18}} In early January 2019, NYCTA President Andy Byford ordered more newer R179 cars to be removed from passenger service and the temporary suspension of the delivery of further cars until Bombardier corrected all defects found within them.<ref>{{cite web | last=Bloomberg | first=BNN | title=NYC transit chief slams Bombardier, halts deliveries: 'You have to hold their hands' | website=BNN | date=January 24, 2019 | url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/nyc-transit-chief-slams-bombardier-halts-deliveries-you-have-to-hold-their-hands-1.1203566 | access-date=January 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | publisher=Midwest Communications Inc. | title=Exclusive: NYC Transit stops Bombardier deliveries until problems fixed | website=WSAU | date=January 24, 2019 | url=https://wsau.com/news/articles/2019/jan/24/nyc-transit-to-stop-taking-new-train-cars-from-bombardier-until-existing-cars-fixed/ | access-date=January 27, 2019}}</ref> The issues have since been resolved, and deliveries recommenced in early February 2019.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/r-bombardier-resumes-deliveries-of-subway-cars-to-new-york-city-2019-1|title=Bombardier resumes deliveries of subway cars to New York City|last=Reuters|last2=Jan 28|first2=2019|website=Business Insider|language=en-US|access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref>'' On May 10, 2019, it was found that there is a welding defect on the collision pillars of the R179, but not all trains on property at the time were pulled from service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/2AvSagas/status/1126976002222170113|title=Bombardier screwed up the rolling stock again. There's a welding defect in the R179 collision pillars. Byford has attestations from Bombardier and NYCT's independent engineering assessment that the trains are safe and within NYCT standards. Byford: \"There are no safety risks.\"|last=Sagas|first=Second Ave|date=2019-05-10|website=@2AvSagas|language=en|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref> \n\nBy December 30, 2019, all 318 cars had been delivered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/BombardierRail/photos/a.902865919774651/2806951702699387/?type=3|title=Bombardier Transportation|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> Even after all cars had been delivered, an audit by Comptroller [[Scott Stringer]] found that only 18 of the original 300 cars had been delivered within the contract's deadline.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/new-york/new-york-city/mta-spent-600m-300-subway-cars-got-18-time-audit|title=MTA Spent $600M For 300 Subway Cars, Got 18 On Time: Audit|last=Culliton|first=Kathleen|date=December 9, 2019|website=New York City, NY Patch|access-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref> Additionally, in early January 2020, all cars in revenue were taken out of passenger service following two incidents involving R179 cars with defective door parts on the C train.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/nyc-transit/transcript-new-york-city-transit-president-andy-byford-issues-update-r179|title=Transcript: New York City Transit President Andy Byford Issues Updated on R179 Suwbay Cars|last=|first=|date=January 9, 2020|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/ny-mta-train-cars-pulled-from-service-r179-subway-20200109-k2biix5b2fdrdde5iev47vmi2q-story.html|title=Out with the new, in with the old as MTA puts 55-year-old cars on A, C, J and Z lines after contractor\u2019s latest train screw up|last=Guse|first=Clayton|website=nydailynews.com|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> The January incidents raised concerns that train doors could malfunction while the trains were in service, and that doors could potentially open up when the train was in motion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/08/nyregion/mta-pulls-subway-cars.html|title=Subway Pulls 300 Cars Over Fears Doors Would Open Between Stops|last=Goldbaum|first=Christina|date=2020-01-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-10|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Due to this incident and prior issues, the R179s became known as \"[[Lemon (automobile)|lemons]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/mta-pulls-nearly-300-brand-new-subway-cars-for-safety-reasons/2256699/|title=MTA Pulls Nearly 300 Brand New Subway Cars Over Door Problems|last=Siff|first=Andrew|date=January 8, 2020|website=NBC New York|access-date=January 8, 2020}}</ref> Aside from the door issues, the [[Transport Workers Union of America]] has complained about problems with operating the R179, such as stiff windows, slippery controls, and other design flaws.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/01/10/mta-workers-say-busted-doors-arent-the-only-problem-with-new-lemon-trains/|title=MTA workers say busted doors aren\u2019t the only problem with new \u2018lemon\u2019 trains|last=Barone|first=Vincent|last2=Meyer|first2=David|date=2020-01-10|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref> The R179s were repaired and the fleet re-entered service on January 24, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/nyc-transit/mta-returns-r179-subway-cars-service|title=MTA {{!}} Press Release {{!}} NYC Transit {{!}} MTA Returns R179 Subway Cars to Service|website=www.mta.info|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[New Technology Train]] - a list of all such trains on the New York City Subway.\n* [[R143 (New York City Subway car)]] - a similar car built by Kawasaki Railcar Corp. of Kobe, Japan\n* [[R160 (New York City Subway car)]] - a similar car built by Alstom and Kawasaki Railcar Corp.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|R179 (New York City Subway car)}}\n*{{NYCS const|thejoekorner|B}}\n*[http://www.nycsubway.org/wiki/New_Technology_Trains_-_B_Division nycsubway.org: New Technology Trains - B Division]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120505034246/http://www.pcac.org/nyctrc/meetings-and-minutes/minutes-102009 MTA Committee Meeting Discussing the R179]\n*[http://www.mta.info/mta/news/books/docs/r_179_staff_summary_March_2012.pdf Staff Summary]\n{{NYCS rolling stock}}\n\n[[Category:New York City Subway rolling stock|R179]]\n[[Category:Train-related introductions in 2016]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Class of New York City Subway car}}\n{{redirect|R179|the imprint for a pharmaceutical|Tizanidine|the road|Route 179}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox Train\n| background =\n| name = R179\n| image = File:MTA NYC Subway A train arriving at Broad Channel.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = An R179 train on the [[A (New York City Subway service)|A]] at [[Broad Channel station|Broad Channel]]\n| interiorimage = MTA NYC Subway Bombardier Transportation R179 3015 interior.jpg\n| interiorcaption = Interior of an R179 car\n| service = 2017\u2013present\n| manufacturer =  [[Bombardier Transportation]]\n| factory =Bombardier's Plattsburgh facility\n| family = [[New Technology Train|NTT (new technology train)]]\n| refurbishment =\n| replaced = {{unbulleted list|Possibly all remaining [[R32 (New York City Subway car)|R32s]]|All remaining [[R42 (New York City Subway car)|R42s]]}}\n| formation = {{unbulleted list|47 four-car sets (two B cars)|26 five-car sets (three B cars)}}\n| fleetnumbers =  {{unbulleted list|'''Five-car sets:''' 3010-3049, 3238-3327|'''Four-car sets:''' 3050\u20133237}} \n| operator =  [[New York City Subway]]\n| depots = {{NYCS const|depot}}\n| lines = {{NYCS const|car}}\n| yearconstruction = 2016\u20132019 \n| yearservice = November 19, 2017<br>(4-car sets)<br>February 10, 2019<br>(5-car sets)\n| yearscrapped =\n| numberconstruction =\n| numberbuilt = 318\n| numberservice = 318\n| numberscrapped =\n| carbody = Stainless steel with fiberglass ends and rear bonnets\n| trainlength = 4-car train: {{convert|240.84|ft|m}}<br>5-car train: {{convert|301.05|ft|m}}<br>8-car train: {{convert|481.68|ft|m}}<br>10-car train: {{convert|602.1|ft|m}}\n| carlength =  {{convert|60.21|ft|m}}\n| width = 9.77 ft (2,978 mm)\n| height = 12.13 ft (3,697 mm)\n| floorheight ={{convert|3.76|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n| platformheight ={{convert|3.76|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n| entrylevelorstep ={{convert|3.76|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n| art-sections =\n| doors = 8 sets of 50 inch wide side doors per car\n| maxspeed = {{convert|55|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}\n| weight = 85,200 lb (38,600 kg)\n| capacity = 54 seating 198 standing (A car)<br>56 seating 202 standing (B car)\n| acceleration =  {{convert|2.5|mph/s|m/s2|abbr=on}}\n| deceleration =  {{convert|3.0|mph/s|m/s2|abbr=on}} <br>(full service),<br> {{convert|3.2|mph/s|m/s2|abbr=on}}<br> (emergency)\n| traction = Bombardier MITRAC IGBT-VVVF AC traction motors, model: TM1301SP <ref>[https://scontent-lga3-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/35392381_1943904555661486_6991157772255494144_o.jpg?_nc_cat=0&oh=5d7533d8e57856e6e06cb38760fe1379&oe=5BB8367F R179 Traction Motor Build Plate]</ref>\n| engine =\n| poweroutput ={{convert|147.5|hp|kW|1|abbr=on}} per motor axle \n| transmission =\n| aux = \n| powersupply = \n| gauge =  {{RailGauge|sg|allk=on}}\n| electricsystem   = 600 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]] [[Third rail]]\n| collectionmethod = [[Contact shoe]]\n| brakes = \n| safety = [[Dead man's switch]], [[train stop]]}}\n\nThe '''R179''' is a class of 318 [[New Technology Train|new technology (NTT)]] [[New York City Subway]] cars being built by [[Bombardier Transportation]] for the [[B Division (New York City Subway)|B Division]]. The cars replaced all remaining [[R42 (New York City Subway car)|R42s]] and are expected to replace some, if not all, remaining [[R32 (New York City Subway car)|R32s]].\n\nOriginally, the R179 order was supposed to contain 208 cars that were each {{convert|75|ft|m}} long. In the 2010\u20132014 Capital Program, the order was changed to 290 cars that were {{convert|60|ft|m}} long, similar to the car lengths of the [[R143 (New York City Subway car)|R143]] and [[R160 (New York City Subway car)|R160]] orders, with options for up to 130 more cars. The majority of the R179s were supposed to be in {{convert|300|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} five-car sets because the R179s would be replacing the 75-foot-long [[R44 (New York City Subway car)|R44s]], which were arranged in 300-foot-long four-car sets. A minority of the R179s were to be arranged in {{convert|240|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} four-car sets. In 2011, the order was reduced to 300 60-foot-long cars with no additional option orders. Because of the R44s' earlier than planned retirement and the R32s and R42s assigned to services utilizing eight-car trains at the time, the setup was reversed, with the majority of the R179s being arranged in four-car sets.\n\nThe $599 million contract for the R179s' construction was awarded to Bombardier in 2012. At the time, the first R179 train was set to be delivered in December 2014 and the last train would be delivered in July 2017. Because of manufacturing defects during the construction process, the timeline for delivery was pushed back two years, and the cost of the contract rose to $735 million. The first R179 cars were delivered in September 2016, and the first test train of eight cars was placed in service in November 2017. The test train passed its 30-day in-service test in December 2017, which allowed the remaining R179s to be gradually placed in service. All cars were expected to be delivered by early 2019. However, starting in December 2018, several cars had to be withdrawn from service due to defects, and in January 2019, deliveries were temporarily halted while these defects were being fixed. In January 2020, the R179s were experiencing door problems, leading to the entire fleet being pulled from revenue service for a short period.\n\nIn January 2018, sixteen more cars were added to the order as part of a settlement so that there would be 24 five-car sets instead of the 8 originally projected and 49 four-car sets instead of the original 65. In January 2019, two more cars were added to the order as a part of a settlement for further damages. All cars were delivered by December 2019, and had entered service by March 2020.\n\n==Description==\nThe R179s are numbered 3010-3327. Cars numbered 3010-3049 & 3238-3327 are configured into five-car sets, which are assigned to the [[A (New York City Subway service)|A]] and  based out of [[Pitkin Yard]]. Cars numbered 3050-3237 are configured into four-car sets, which are split between the [[J/Z (New York City Subway service)|J and Z]] (based out of [[East New York Yard]]) and the [[C (New York City Subway service)|C]] (based out of [[207th Street Yard]]).\n\n===Features===\n[[File:From the J Train 05 - R179.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The FIND screen of the R179]]\nThe R179 cars are equipped with updated control systems, [[HVAC]] and public address systems. They are visually very similar to the [[R160 (New York City Subway car)|R160s]], but the two car types are not interoperable with each other due to electrical incompatibilities between them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/160523_1030_Transit.pdf|title=Transit & Bus Committee Meeting May 2016|date=May 2016|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe R179s, like the R160s, employ an advanced alternative to electronic strip maps called the [[New Technology Train#FIND displays|\"Flexible Information and Notice Display\"]] (\"FIND\"), which are manufactured by Axion Technologies Ltd. This includes an [[LCD]] screen displaying the route, route information, and advertisements, as well as a dynamic red, yellow, and green LED strip map that displays the next ten stations, plus five consecutive \"further stops\" to riders.<ref>https://www.nycsubway.org/perl/show?149991</ref> There are three of these in every car. The display updates the stations at every stop, also giving the number of stops to each station listed. This allows for instant route or line changes with the correct information, which includes, but is not limited to, omitting certain stops (displayed as \"Will not stop\" in red). However, the LCD displays on the R179s that show the route are slightly larger than those on the R160s. Additionally, if the FIND has gone blank, the R179 FIND displays \"Route change: this map is not in use\", as opposed to the R160 FIND, which displays \"Listen to train crew for announcement.\"<ref name=\"Metro-NYCS-NTT-Dec2006\">{{cite news|url=http://www.metro-magazine.com/rail/article/210993/new-york-city-bringing-rail-into-the-21st-century|title=New York City Bringing Rail Into the 21st Century|date=December 6, 2006|work=[[Metro Magazine]]|last1=Seaton|first1=Charles|accessdate=January 27, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"MTA-CapitalOversight-Jan2016\">{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/160125_1345_CPOC.pdf|title=MTA Capital Program Oversight Meeting January 2016|date=January 2016|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=January 23, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129071849/http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/160125_1345_CPOC.pdf|archivedate=January 29, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes-NYCSPromiseInfo-Nov20052\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/30/nyregion/30car.html|title=New Subway Cars Promise All Kinds of Information|last=Chan|first=Sewell|date=November 30, 2005|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|authorlink=Sewell Chan|accessdate=October 27, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nycsubway.org/perl/show?149990|title=Showing Image 149990|website=www.nycsubway.org|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> In addition, the R179s utilize the older door closing chimes used on the R142s and R142As, as opposed to the newer door chimes used on the R143s, R160s and R188s. [[Communication-based train control]] (CBTC) equipment will be installed in all R179s that are already on MTA property.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/181022_1000_Transit.pdf|title=New York City Transit and Bus Committee Meeting October 2018|date=October 19, 2018|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|page=188-189|access-date=October 20, 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe R179s are equipped with looped stanchions in the interiors of trains to provide passengers on crowded trains with a greater amount of pole surface area to grab on to. This feature was previously tested on R160A set 9798-9802 and has been implemented on other trains as a part of a plan to fix the subway's [[2017 New York City transit crisis|2017 state of emergency]].<ref>{{Cite AV media|url=https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/10/NYC_Subway_R160_9800_Interior_with_Double_Stanchions.jpg|title=NYC Subway R160 9800 Interior with Double Stanchions|author=Gh9449|publisher=[[Wikimedia Commons]]|date=October 27, 2015|accessdate=May 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe R179s utilize a newer version of HVAC systems, which are noticeably quieter on the outside of the train, compared to previous generations of New Technology Trains. The R179s also have larger picture windows resulting in a tighter cab for the conductors and train operators, since slightly more space was required to accommodate the HVACs.\n\n\n===Recorded announcements===\nThe R179s are the sixth New York City Subway cars to feature recorded announcements. All passenger cars built after the R179s also use this feature.\nCurrent recorded announcements are by:\n* Kathleen Campion: announcements for  the '''[[J/Z (New York City Subway service)|J/Z]]'''. Except The announcements recorded The Next Stop is, This is and The Next and Last Stop is.\n*Catherine Cowdery: announcements for the '''[[A (New York City Subway service)|A]]''', '''[[C (New York City Subway service)|C]]'''.\n* Charlie Pellett: announcements to warn passengers of the closing doors, last stop announcements, and current transfer and connection announcements at select stations; formerly provided safety/delay announcements (2006\u20132017).\n* Velina Mitchell: current safety and delay announcements (since 2018). She also recorded the stop announcement for transfer announcements at selected stations referencing the M14-SBS bus route.\n\n==History==\n===Contract plans===\nThe R179 contract originally consisted of 208 {{convert|75|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} cars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/budget/pdf/2008-2013%20Capital%20Plan.pdf|title=MTA Capital Program 2008\u20132013 February 2008|date=February 2008|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 12, 2016}}</ref> Later, in the 2010-2014 Capital Program, the proposed order was expanded to 420 cars (340 for the New York City Subway and 80 for the Staten Island Railway).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nysenate.gov/sites/default/files/articles/attachments/proposed0909.pdf|title=Proposed MTA Capital Program 2010\u20132014|date=September 23, 2009|website=nysenate.gov|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 8, 2016}}</ref> This consisted of 290 base order cars (250 arranged in 5-car sets and the remaining 40 arranged in 4-car sets), with two option orders. The first option called for 50 cars arranged in 5-car sets. There was also a second option for 80 additional cars, which would have supplied cars for the [[Second Avenue Subway]] Phase I service. The proposed MTA 2010-2014 Capital Program pointed towards an order of {{convert|60|ft|m|2|adj=on}} cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/pdf/CP/ProposedProgram.pdf#page=40|title=Proposed Capital Program 2010\u20132014|date=August 2009|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|website=mta.info|page=36|accessdate=September 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe official RFP was issued on June 3, 2010. Bids were due by the following August 13, and in April 2011 the contract was expected to be awarded for $637.8 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/110421_1345_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Meeting April 2011|date=April 21, 2011|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref> However, there were delays with negotiation problems, and the projected cost went up to $748 million in October 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/111024_1415_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Meeting October 2011|date=October 24, 2011|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref> In November 2011, the order was altered to a base order of 300 cars (260 arranged in 4-car sets and the remaining 40 arranged in 5-car sets), with no options.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/111114_1345_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Meeting November 2011|date=November 14, 2011|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe contract was finally awarded to [[Bombardier Transportation]] on March 24, 2012, for $599 million, below the projected cost.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/120423_1400_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Meeting April 2012|date=April 23, 2012|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/docs/r_179_staff_summary_March_2012.pdf|title=R179 Staff Summary March 2012|date=March 2012|website=mta.info|publisher=New York City Transit|access-date=September 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.governor.ny.gov/press/032812MTA-Investment |title=Governor Cuomo Announces $600 Million MTA Investment in Upstate Manufacturing &#124; Governor Andrew M. Cuomo |publisher=Governor.ny.gov |date=March 28, 2012 |accessdate=February 21, 2014}}</ref> The joint venture Alskaw Inc., made up of the companies [[Kawasaki Heavy Industries Rolling Stock Company|Kawasaki]] and [[Alstom]], which built the [[R160 (New York City Subway car)|R160A/B]] cars, protested the award of the contract to Bombardier immediately after the MTA Board approved the contract.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/120521_1400_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Meeting May 2012|date=May 21, 2012|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref> However, the protest was denied, and Bombardier signed the contract on June 4, 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/120625_1400_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Meeting June 2012|date=June 27, 2012|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"bombardier press release 20120406\"/>\n\nA 2012 news report from the ''[[New York Daily News]]'' indicated that a high-ranking MTA official had been in talks with car builder Bombardier Transportation, Inc. for a job.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/mta-exec-mario-guerra-hit-ethics-seeking-job-subway-car-maker-article-1.1052494 |title=MTA exec Mario Guerra hit on ethics over seeking job with subway-car maker |publisher=NY Daily News |date=March 28, 2012 |accessdate=February 21, 2014}}</ref> This prompted an ethics investigation but has since been resolved.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bombardier.com/en/transportation/media-centre/press-releases/details?docID=0901260d80212faa |title=News - Media Centre |publisher=Bombardier |date= |accessdate=February 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe R179s were originally intended to replace all the [[R44 (New York City Subway car)|R44s]], but due to structural integrity issues found on [[New York City Transit]]'s R44s in late 2009, those cars' retirement was facilitated by an [[option (finance)|option order]] of R160s. Additionally, the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] later dropped the plan to order R179s for the [[Staten Island Railway]], instead opting to overhaul some [[R46 (New York City Subway car)|R46s]] to replace the existing R44s there (which has also since been cancelled).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/nyct/procure/addenda/R34211add3.pdf|title=R34211 Notice -Of- Addendum Addendum #3|date=August 11, 2016|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=August 15, 2016}}</ref> The R179s were then intended to retire all remaining [[R42 (New York City Subway car)|R42s]] (50 cars) and [[R32 (New York City Subway car)|R32s]] (222 cars).<ref name=\"Pix11-NewR179s-2016\">{{Cite web|url=http://pix11.com/2016/09/08/new-r179-subway-cars-arrives-in-nyc/|title=New R179 subway cars arrive in NYC|date=September 9, 2016|website=New York's PIX11 / WPIX-TV|access-date=September 9, 2016}}</ref> Some R32s were expected to be retained due to delays in the delivery of the R179s and potential need of extra rolling stock to provide additional service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/news-c-subway/2015/12/11/detailed-study-system%E2%80%99s-longest-subway-line-identifies-opportunities|title=Detailed Study of System\u2019s Longest Subway Line Identifies Opportunities to Improve Service|website=www.mta.info|access-date=July 19, 2016}}</ref> As a result, the MTA planned to spend another $49.2 million to refurbish and maintain 132 to 164 R32 cars through 2018 and then 110 R32 cars through 2019, before finally replacing the remaining cars with the [[R211 (New York City Subway car)|R211As]]. In addition, the MTA anticipated to have most, if not all R179s delivered before the since-canceled [[14th Street Tunnel shutdown|full shutdown of the 14th Street Tunnel]] in April 2019.<ref name=\"v222\">{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/budget/july2015/MTA_2016_Prelim_Budget_Financial_Plan2016-2019_Vol2.pdf|title=MTA 2016 Preliminary Budget Financial Plan 2016-2019 Volume 2 |page=V-222|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref> However, by January 2020, the MTA planned to replace all remaining R32s with the R179s.<ref>{{Citation|title=MTA Board - 01/21/2020 Live Webcast|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y3AOsVFVOoo|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10|time=8:01:40}}</ref>\n\n===Manufacturing issues===\nIn a timeline set in October 2012, the first test train was scheduled to arrive on December 22, 2014, the first production unit was scheduled to arrive on July 27, 2015, and the entire order was to be completed on January 30, 2017.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/121029_1400_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Meeting October 2012|date=October 29, 2012|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 11, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160205142707/http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/121029_1400_CPOC.pdf|archivedate=February 5, 2016}}</ref> After some delays in starting production, a non-operational mockup was built in late November 2013. Delivery of the first 10-car test train was now scheduled for the third quarter of 2014,<ref name=\"bombardier press release 20120406\">{{cite web|url=http://us.bombardier.com/us/press_release_04062012.htm |title=Bombardier in the USA&nbsp;\u2013 Media Center |publisher=Us.bombardier.com |date= |accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> though delivery of the production cars was still scheduled to begin July 2015 and continue through January 2017. However, as NYCTA's and Bombardier's inspectors found cracks due to welding issues in the prototype train's chassis, the entire lot was rejected, and the delivery schedule was pushed back by two years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting: July 2014|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/140728_1200_CPOC.pdf#page=30|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|website=mta.info|accessdate=September 9, 2016|page=30|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801140126/http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/140728_1200_CPOC.pdf#page=30|archivedate=August 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/mta-encounters-delay-replacing-trains-article-1.1883555 | title=Riders on C train will have to wait longer for new Subway cars | work=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]] | date=July 29, 2014 | accessdate=September 30, 2014 | author=Donohue, Pete}}</ref>\n\nThe delays in delivery have increased the cost of the cars from $599 million to $735 million; these additional costs add to the costs required to maintain older cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://secondavenuesagas.com/2015/08/14/as-bombardier-struggles-r179-delay-to-cost-mta-50-million/|title=As Bombardier struggles, R179 delay to cost MTA $50 million|date=August 14, 2015|publisher=Second Avenue Sagas|website=secondavenuesagas.com|last=Kabak|first=Benjamin|accessdate=August 11, 2016}}</ref> In addition, because of the 2-year delay in producing the R179s, Bombardier was banned from bidding on the [[R211 (New York City Subway car)|R211]] contract, which would replace other older B Division rolling stock.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://montrealgazette.com/business/local-business/bombardier-shut-out-of-n-y-subway-contract-because-of-poor-performance-report|title=Bombardier shut out of N.Y. subway contract because of 'poor performance'|date=August 30, 2017|work=Montreal Gazette|access-date=August 31, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Delivery and continued issues===\n[[File:First R179 Delivered to MTA.jpg|thumb|R179 car 3014 being delivered on September 6, 2016]]\n[[File:NYC Subway Bombardier R179 at Rockaway BLVD.jpg|thumb|R179 testing at [[Rockaway Boulevard station]] on October 28, 2016]]\nBombardier built the cars in its [[Plattsburgh, New York]], facility.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.governor.ny.gov/news/governor-cuomo-announces-600-million-mta-investment-upstate-manufacturing|title=Governor Cuomo Announces $600 Million MTA Investment in Upstate Manufacturing|date=September 29, 2014|access-date=September 12, 2016}}</ref> The first five-car set of R179s (3010-3014) was delivered to the [[New York City Transit Authority]] between September 6 and 8, 2016. The next five cars (3015-3019) were delayed and were delivered between November 15 and 17, 2016, forming a complete pilot ten-car train for acceptance testing and evaluation.<ref name=\"AMNY-R179Arrive-Sep62016\">{{cite news|last1=Barone|first1=Vincent|title=New MTA subway cars to arrive for testing, will replace oldest fleet|url=http://www.amny.com/transit/new-mta-subway-cars-to-arrive-for-testing-will-replace-oldest-fleet-1.12276227|accessdate=September 8, 2016|work=[[AM New York]]|date=September 6, 2016}}</ref> The first four-car set of R179s (3050-3053) was delivered between December 21 and 22, 2016. The next four cars (3054-3057) were delivered in January 2017, forming a complete eight-car train for acceptance testing and evaluation. \n\nA delivery plan from January 2017 anticipated a rate of one car per day starting from November 2017, in an effort to have all cars on property by July 2018.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/170123_1345_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting: January 2017|last=|first=|date=January 23, 2017|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|pages=33, 34|accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref> However, additional delays have occurred, and by October 2018, deliveries were not expected to be completed until March 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/181022_1330_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting 10/22/2018|date=October 19, 2018|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|page=116|access-date=October 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/180122_1400_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting January 2018|last=|first=|date=|website=web.mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=January 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/07/nyregion/mta-subway-nyc.html|title=How Can the M.T.A. Rescue the Subway When It Struggles to Deliver Basics?|last=|first=|date=May 7, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 7, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \nDue to continuing delays in the production of the R179s, the order was increased by 16 additional B-cars on January 22, 2018. The order then consisted of 316 cars (120 arranged in 5-car sets and 196 arranged in 4-car sets).<ref>{{Cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j9zfldErD4Q&t=24m39s|author=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting|date=January 22, 2018|accessdate=January 19, 2018|time=24:36}}</ref><ref name=MTA-CPOC-Jan2019/>{{rp|19}} On January 22, 2019, another settlement increased the order by 2 additional B-cars.<ref>{{Cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cKNSPq8j164|author=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting|date=January 22, 2019|accessdate=January 22, 2019|time=31:04}}</ref> As of July 2019, deliveries were not expected to be completed until November 2019.<ref>http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/190722_1430_CPOC.pdf page 86</ref>\n\nThe four-car R179 sets were placed into revenue service on the [[J/Z (New York City Subway service)|J]] on November 19, 2017 for in-service acceptance testing after slightly over a year of successful non-revenue service tests.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://pix11.com/2017/11/25/14-months-after-delivery-new-subway-cars-enter-mtas-final-testing-stage-with-riders-on-j-line/|title=14 months after delivery, new subway cars enter MTA\u2019s final testing stage with riders on J Line|date=November 25, 2017|work=New York's PIX11 / WPIX-TV|access-date=November 26, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> During the first two weeks of the testing period, the MTA identified three major issues in the train, which have since been fixed.<ref>\n{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/mta-newest-fleet-2m-subway-cars-face-crippling-mishap-article-1.3688782|title=MTA's newest fleet of $2M subway cars face third crippling mishap|work=NY Daily News|access-date=December 12, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://secondavenuesagas.com/2017/12/10/testing-woes-plague-bombardiers-faulty-r179-cars/|title=Testing woes plague Bombardier's faulty R179 cars - Second Ave. Sagas|date=December 10, 2017|work=Second Ave. Sagas|access-date=December 12, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ny.curbed.com/2017/12/11/16761874/mta-nyc-subway-r179-train-problems|title=MTA\u2019s new fleet of subway cars plagued by mishaps|work=Curbed NY|access-date=December 12, 2017}}</ref> After successful completion, the four-car R179 sets officially entered revenue service on December 27, 2017, a month later than originally planned.<ref name=\"CPOC-Jan2018\">{{Cite web|author=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting|date=January 22, 2018|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/180122_1400_CPOC.pdf|accessdate=January 19, 2018|page=46}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=BombardierRail|number=951812524340645889|title=We\u2019re pleased to report that our R179 cars for #NewYorkCityTransit have successfully completed their extensive on-site qualification testing and 30-day in-service demonstration test and are starting to enter regular passenger service. #Plattsburgh #NewYork|date=January 12, 2018|access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> The pilot five-car R179 sets underwent specification modifications at Bombardier's [[Bath, New York|Kanona]] Facility in summer 2018 and were re-delivered for further testing.<ref name=CPOC-Jan2018/> After two years of modifications, the train was placed into service on the [[A (New York City Subway service)|A]] for a 30-day in-service test on February 10, 2019. The train completed the test on March 11, 2019 and entered regular service the next day.<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://twitter.com/BombardierRail/status/1105505014737485825 | title=Completion of 30-day revenue service test for the 10-car train | work=Bombardier Rail | date=March 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBy the start of December 2018, some trains had to be taken out of service due to manufacturing defects such as doors, propulsion, and air compressors issues.<ref>{{cite web | last=Rivoli | first=Dan | title=NYC Transit's new subway cars suffering on the tracks, dozens pulled from rails | website=New York Daily News | date=January 9, 2019 | url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/ny-metro-r179-mta-train-car-20190108-story.html | access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref> The next month, the MTA revealed that 162 cars had been delivered, of which 128 (comprising sixteen 8-car trains) had been placed in service.<ref name=\"MTA-CPOC-Jan2019\">{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/190122_1400_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting|date=January 2019|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|access-date=January 18, 2019}}</ref>{{rp|18}} In early January 2019, NYCTA President Andy Byford ordered more newer R179 cars to be removed from passenger service and the temporary suspension of the delivery of further cars until Bombardier corrected all defects found within them.<ref>{{cite web | last=Bloomberg | first=BNN | title=NYC transit chief slams Bombardier, halts deliveries: 'You have to hold their hands' | website=BNN | date=January 24, 2019 | url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/nyc-transit-chief-slams-bombardier-halts-deliveries-you-have-to-hold-their-hands-1.1203566 | access-date=January 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | publisher=Midwest Communications Inc. | title=Exclusive: NYC Transit stops Bombardier deliveries until problems fixed | website=WSAU | date=January 24, 2019 | url=https://wsau.com/news/articles/2019/jan/24/nyc-transit-to-stop-taking-new-train-cars-from-bombardier-until-existing-cars-fixed/ | access-date=January 27, 2019}}</ref> The issues have since been resolved, and deliveries recommenced in early February 2019.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/r-bombardier-resumes-deliveries-of-subway-cars-to-new-york-city-2019-1|title=Bombardier resumes deliveries of subway cars to New York City|last=Reuters|last2=Jan 28|first2=2019|website=Business Insider|language=en-US|access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref>'' On May 10, 2019, it was found that there is a welding defect on the collision pillars of the R179, but not all trains on property at the time were pulled from service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/2AvSagas/status/1126976002222170113|title=Bombardier screwed up the rolling stock again. There's a welding defect in the R179 collision pillars. Byford has attestations from Bombardier and NYCT's independent engineering assessment that the trains are safe and within NYCT standards. Byford: \"There are no safety risks.\"|last=Sagas|first=Second Ave|date=2019-05-10|website=@2AvSagas|language=en|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref> \n\nBy December 30, 2019, all 318 cars had been delivered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/BombardierRail/photos/a.902865919774651/2806951702699387/?type=3|title=Bombardier Transportation|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> Even after all cars had been delivered, an audit by Comptroller [[Scott Stringer]] found that only 18 of the original 300 cars had been delivered within the contract's deadline.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/new-york/new-york-city/mta-spent-600m-300-subway-cars-got-18-time-audit|title=MTA Spent $600M For 300 Subway Cars, Got 18 On Time: Audit|last=Culliton|first=Kathleen|date=December 9, 2019|website=New York City, NY Patch|access-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref> Additionally, in early January 2020, all cars in revenue were taken out of passenger service following two incidents involving R179 cars with defective door parts on the C train.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/nyc-transit/transcript-new-york-city-transit-president-andy-byford-issues-update-r179|title=Transcript: New York City Transit President Andy Byford Issues Updated on R179 Suwbay Cars|last=|first=|date=January 9, 2020|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/ny-mta-train-cars-pulled-from-service-r179-subway-20200109-k2biix5b2fdrdde5iev47vmi2q-story.html|title=Out with the new, in with the old as MTA puts 55-year-old cars on A, C, J and Z lines after contractor\u2019s latest train screw up|last=Guse|first=Clayton|website=nydailynews.com|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> The January incidents raised concerns that train doors could malfunction while the trains were in service, and that doors could potentially open up when the train was in motion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/08/nyregion/mta-pulls-subway-cars.html|title=Subway Pulls 300 Cars Over Fears Doors Would Open Between Stops|last=Goldbaum|first=Christina|date=2020-01-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-10|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Due to this incident and prior issues, the R179s became known as \"[[Lemon (automobile)|lemons]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/mta-pulls-nearly-300-brand-new-subway-cars-for-safety-reasons/2256699/|title=MTA Pulls Nearly 300 Brand New Subway Cars Over Door Problems|last=Siff|first=Andrew|date=January 8, 2020|website=NBC New York|access-date=January 8, 2020}}</ref> Aside from the door issues, the [[Transport Workers Union of America]] has complained about problems with operating the R179, such as stiff windows, slippery controls, and other design flaws.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/01/10/mta-workers-say-busted-doors-arent-the-only-problem-with-new-lemon-trains/|title=MTA workers say busted doors aren\u2019t the only problem with new \u2018lemon\u2019 trains|last=Barone|first=Vincent|last2=Meyer|first2=David|date=2020-01-10|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref> The R179s were repaired and the fleet re-entered service on January 24, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/nyc-transit/mta-returns-r179-subway-cars-service|title=MTA {{!}} Press Release {{!}} NYC Transit {{!}} MTA Returns R179 Subway Cars to Service|website=www.mta.info|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[New Technology Train]] - a list of all such trains on the New York City Subway.\n* [[R143 (New York City Subway car)]] - a similar car built by Kawasaki Railcar Corp. of Kobe, Japan\n* [[R160 (New York City Subway car)]] - a similar car built by Alstom and Kawasaki Railcar Corp.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|R179 (New York City Subway car)}}\n*{{NYCS const|thejoekorner|B}}\n*[http://www.nycsubway.org/wiki/New_Technology_Trains_-_B_Division nycsubway.org: New Technology Trains - B Division]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120505034246/http://www.pcac.org/nyctrc/meetings-and-minutes/minutes-102009 MTA Committee Meeting Discussing the R179]\n*[http://www.mta.info/mta/news/books/docs/r_179_staff_summary_March_2012.pdf Staff Summary]\n{{NYCS rolling stock}}\n\n[[Category:New York City Subway rolling stock|R179]]\n[[Category:Train-related introductions in 2016]]\n", "name_user": "Williamwang363", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRecorded announcements", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R179_(New_York_City_Subway_car)"}
{"title_page": "Daniel Biss", "text_new": "{{short description|American mathematician and politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name              = Daniel Biss\n| image             = File:Daniel Biss 2012 (cropped).jpg\n| state_senate      = Illinois\n| district          = 9th\n| term_start        = January 8, 2013\n| term_end          = January 6, 2019\n| predecessor       = [[Jeffrey Schoenberg]]\n| successor         = [[Laura Fine]]\n| state_house1      = Illinois\n| district1         = 17th\n| term_start1       = May 2011\n| term_end1         = January 8, 2013\n| predecessor1      = [[Elizabeth Coulson]]\n| successor1        = [[Laura Fine]]\n| birth_name        = Daniel K\u00e1lm\u00e1n Biss\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1977|8|27}}\n| birth_place       = [[Akron, Ohio|Akron]], [[Ohio]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date        = \n| death_place       = \n| party             = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse            = Karin Steinbrueck\n| children          = 2\n| education         = [[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]]) <br> [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] ([[Master of Arts|M.A.]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]])\n| profession        = [[Mathematician]]\n| website           = {{url|danielbiss.com|Official website}}\n{{Infobox scientist | embed = yes\n| fields            = [[Algebraic topology]]\n| workplaces        = [[University of Chicago]]\n| thesis_title      = The Homotopy Type of the Matroid Grassmannian\n| thesis_url        = https://annals.math.princeton.edu/wp-content/uploads/annals-v158-n3-p04.pdf\n| thesis_year       = 2002\n| doctoral_advisor  = [[Michael J. Hopkins|Michael  Hopkins]]\n| doctoral_students = \n}}\n| signature         = BissSig.png\n}}\n\n'''Daniel K\u00e1lm\u00e1n Biss'''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.harvard.edu/gazette/1998/05.28/HoopesPrizesAwa.html | title=Hoopes Prizes Awarded to Undergraduates and Thesis Advisers | work=Harvard Gazette | date=28 May 1998 | accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref> (born August 27, 1977)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://math.mit.edu/~gracelyo/18904/BissCoveringSpaceArticle.pdf | title=A Generalized Approach to the Fundamental Group | publisher=Mathematical Association of America | work=The American Mathematical Monthly | date=October 2000 | accessdate=2 June 2016 | author=Biss, Daniel K.}}</ref> is an American mathematician and politician who was the member of the [[Illinois Senate]] for the 9th district from January 2013 until January 2019. The district includes Chicago's northern suburbs, including [[Evanston, Illinois|Evanston]], [[Glencoe, Illinois|Glencoe]], [[Glenview, Illinois|Glenview]], [[Morton Grove, Illinois|Morton Grove]], [[Northbrook, Illinois|Northbrook]], [[Northfield, Illinois|Northfield]], [[Skokie, Illinois|Skokie]], [[Wilmette, Illinois|Wilmette]], and [[Winnetka, Illinois|Winnetka]]. Biss first ran for office in 2008 and was a member of the [[Illinois House of Representatives]] from 2011 to 2013. He was also a candidate in the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] primary for [[Governor of Illinois]] in the [[Illinois gubernatorial election, 2018|2018 election]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/politics/ct-daniel-biss-illinois-governor-race-met-0320-20170319-story.html|title=State Sen. Daniel Biss announces Democratic bid for governor}}</ref>\n\nPrior to pursuing a political career, Biss was an Assistant Professor of Mathematics at the [[University of Chicago]] from 2002 to 2008.\n\n== Personal life and education ==\nBiss was born into a Jewish [[Israelis|Israeli]] family<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/BDS-THREAT/Jewish-candidate-for-Illinois-governor-drops-running-mate-over-BDS-504506 Jewish candidate for Illinois governor drops running mate over BDS], ''Jerusalem Post'',\n September 7, 2017.</ref><ref>[[David Weigel]], [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2017/09/07/in-illinois-a-democrat-chooses-a-socialist-running-mate-then-dumps-him/ In Illinois, a Democrat chooses a socialist running mate, then dumps him], ''Washington Post'', September 7, 2017.</ref> of musicians: his brother is the noted pianist [[Jonathan Biss]], his parents are the violinists [[Paul Biss]] and [[Miriam Fried]], and his grandmother was the Russian-born cellist [[Raya Garbousova]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Jonathan Biss: A Super, Human, Musical Mission|url=https://www.sfcv.org/events-calendar/artist-spotlight/jonathan-biss-a-super-human-musical-mission|accessdate=September 5, 2013|newspaper=San Francisco Classical Voice|author=Swinkels, Niels|date=June 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jonathan Biss|url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/opera-classical/jonathan-biss|accessdate=September 5, 2013|newspaper=Time Out New York|author=Giovetti, Olivia|date=January 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBiss attended [[Bloomington North High School]] in [[Bloomington, Indiana]], and he was a finalist in the [[Westinghouse Science Talent Search]] in 1995.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bloomington youth stars in science |url=https://newspapers.library.in.gov/cgi-bin/indiana?a=d&d=JPOST19950222-01.1.3 |work=Jewish Post, Indianapolis |date=22 February 1995 |page=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=What does science have to do with the race for governor in Illinois? |url=https://www.societyforscience.org/content/ssp-blog/what-does-science-have-do-race-governor-illinois |publisher=Society for Science & the Public |date=February 21, 2018}}</ref> He\nreceived an undergraduate degree from [[Harvard University]], graduating ''[[summa cum laude]]'' in 1998, and a Ph.D. at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] in 2002, both in mathematics.<ref name=szpiro>{{cite book|title=A mathematical medley: fifty easy pieces on mathematics|author=Szpiro, George G.|authorlink= George Szpiro|pages=97\u201399|year=2010|publisher=American Mathematical Society|chapter=20: Brilliant but Fallible|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mXWr00HurmMC|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=mXWr00HurmMC&pg=PA97|isbn=9780821890646}}</ref> He won the 1999 [[Morgan Prize]] for outstanding research as an undergraduate, and was a [[Clay Mathematics Institute|Clay Research Fellow]] from 2002 to 2007.<ref>[http://www.claymath.org/fas/research_fellows/Biss Daniel Biss], [[Clay Mathematics Institute]]</ref> His doctoral advisor was [[Michael J. Hopkins]]. He was a visiting scholar at the [[Institute for Advanced Study]] in the fall of 2003.<ref>[http://www.ias.edu/people/cos/users/daniel Institute for Advanced Study: A Community of Scholars]</ref>\n\nBiss also wrote an appendix for the popular 2006 [[Young adult fiction|young adult]] novel ''[[An Abundance of Katherines]]'', by [[John Green (author)|John Green]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nir|first1=Oaz|year=2008|title=Book Review: An Abundance of Katherines|journal=Notices of the AMS|volume=55|issue=9|pages=1096\u201398|publisher=American Mathematical Society|doi=|url=http://www.ams.org/notices/200809/tx080901096p.pdf|accessdate=June 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Mathematics career ==\nPrior to full-time pursuit of a political career, Biss was an Assistant Professor of Mathematics at the [[University of Chicago]] from 2002 to 2008.<ref name=JPost>{{cite web |url=http://www.jpost.com/American-Politics/Spot-the-differences-between-the-two-Jewish-candidates-for-Illinois-governor-543636 |title= Spot the differences between the two Jewish candidates for Illinois governor |work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |date=February 26, 2018 |accessdate=March 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt least four of the mathematics papers that Biss published in academic journals were later discovered to contain major errors. Mathematician Nikolai Mn\u00ebv published a report in 2007 that there was a \"serious flaw\" in two of Biss's works published in ''[[Annals of Mathematics]]'' and ''[[Advances in Mathematics]]'' in 2003, saying \"unfortunately this simple mistake destroys the main theorems of both papers\".<ref>{{cite arxiv |eprint=0709.1291|last1=Mnev|first1=N|title=On D.K. Biss' papers \"The homotopy type of the matroid Grassmannian\" and \"Oriented matroids, complex manifolds, and a combinatorial model for BU\"|class=math.CO|year=2007}}</ref> In 2008 and 2009, Biss acknowledged the flaw and published [[erratum]] reports for the two papers, thanking Mn\u00ebv for drawing his attention to the error.<ref name=szpiro/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Biss|first=Daniel K.|date=July 2009|title=Erratum to 'The homotopy type of the matroid Grassmannian'|url=http://annals.math.princeton.edu/wp-content/uploads/annals-v170-n1-p15-p.pdf|journal=[[Annals of Mathematics]]|series=2nd|volume=170-1|page=493|doi=10.4007/annals.2009.170.493|pmid=|accessdate=May 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first=Daniel |last=Biss |title=Erratum to 'Oriented matroids, complex manifolds, and a combinatorial model for BU' [Adv. Math. 179 (2) (2003) 250\u2013290] |journal=[[Advances in Mathematics]] |volume=221 |issue=2 |page=681 |date=June 1, 2009 |doi=10.1016/j.aim.2008.12.012 }}</ref> He and a co-author, [[Benson Farb]], also acknowledged in 2009 that there was a \"fatal error\" in a paper they had published in ''[[Inventiones Mathematicae]]'' in 2006, thanking mathematicians Masatoshi Sato and Tom Church for helping to explain the problem.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Erratum to {{'}}''Kg'' is not finitely generated' |first1=Daniel K. |last=Biss |first2=Benson |last2=Farb |journal=[[Inventiones Mathematicae]] |volume=178 |issue=1 |page=229 |date=October 2009 |doi=10.1007/s00222-009-0202-x |arxiv=math/0405386 |bibcode=2009InMat.178..229B }}</ref> Another of his papers published in ''[[Topology and its Applications]]'' was formally retracted by the publisher in 2017, fifteen years after its 2002 publication, with the journal saying \"This article has been retracted at the request of the Editors-in-Chief after receiving a complaint about anomalies in this paper. The editors solicited further independent reviews which indicated that the definitions in the paper are ambiguous and most results are false. The author was contacted and does not dispute these findings.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Retraction notice to 'The topological fundamental group and generalized covering spaces' [Topol. Appl. 124 (3) (2002) 355\u2013371] |journal=[[Topology and its Applications]] |date=15 February 2017 |volume=217 |page=116 |doi=10.1016/j.topol.2016.12.016 |last1=Biss |first1=Daniel K. }}</ref> The journal said they had identified twelve specific errors in the paper, but clarified that they had concluded that the paper's findings were merely inaccurate, not fraudulent.<ref name=Pi>{{cite newspaper |url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/news/are-gov-hopeful-bisss-claims-of-math-prowess-pi-in-the-sky/ |title=Are gov hopeful Biss's claims of math prowess pi in the sky? |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=September 29, 2017 |access-date=March 26, 2018 |first=Tina |last=Sfondeles}}</ref><ref name=Watch1>{{cite web |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2017/02/13/journal-retracts-paper-state-senator-former-mathematician/ |title=Journal retracts paper by state senator (and former mathematician) |date=February 13, 2017 |work=[[Retraction Watch]] |access-date=March 26, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Watch2>{{cite web |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2017/02/23/false-results-retracted-paper-senator-inaccurate-not-fraudulent-say-editors/ |title='False' results in retracted paper by senator are inaccurate, not fraudulent, say editors |work=[[Retraction Watch]] |date=February 23, 2017 |access-date=March 26, 2018}}</ref> When contacted by the journal, Biss had responded saying \"Thank you for writing. I am no longer in mathematics and so don't feel equipped to fully evaluate these claims. I certainly do not dispute them. If you would like to publish a retraction to that effect, that would seem to me to be an appropriate approach.\"<ref name=Pi/><ref name=Watch2/>\n\nWhen the 2017 retraction and the previously identified errors were reported by the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' in September 2017, his campaign blamed operatives for the perceived front-runner for the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] candidate for governor of Illinois, [[J. B. Pritzker]], for raising it as a political issue. They said \"Whether it was training at MIT or the University of Chicago, Daniel has had dozens of academic papers reviewed by his peers and published. In a few cases, further research has found that the case posited in the original article didn't stand up, and he revised his findings.\"<ref name=Pi/> They referred to the raising of the issue as \"silly opposition research\".<ref name=Pi/>\n\n== Illinois House of Representatives ==\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\n*Appropriations \u2013 Elementary & Secondary Education\n*Personnel & Pensions\n*Consumer Protection\n*Small Business Empowerment & Workforce Development\n*International Trade & Commerce \n*Bio-Technology\n*Appropriations \u2013 Higher Education<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilga.gov/house//Rep.asp?MemberID=1778 |title=Representative Daniel Biss (D) |publisher=www.ilga.gov |date= |accessdate={{date|2011-02-22}}}}</ref>\n\n=== Tenure ===\n{{expand section | date = April 2020}}\n\n== Illinois Senate ==\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\n{{expand section | date = April 2020}}\n\n=== Tenure ===\n{{expand section | date = April 2020}}\n\n== Political views ==\n[[File:Stop Brett Kavanaugh Rally Downtown Chicago Illinois (43406990865).jpg|thumb|right|Biss at a rally against the appointment of [[Brett Kavanaugh]] to the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] in 2018]]\nAccording to his responses in a 2008 \"[[Political Courage Test]]\", Daniel Biss supports carbon emissions limits and is [[pro-choice]] (supporting legal access to abortion services). He also supports allowing Illinois high school graduates to pay in-state tuition at public universities regardless of immigration status, as well as state funding to raise the salaries of teachers.<ref name=PCT2008>{{cite web | url = http://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/101726/daniel-biss/ | title = Daniel Biss' Issue Positions | work = [[Project Vote Smart]] | year = 2008 | publisher = One Common Ground | location = Philipsburg, Montana }}</ref> He received a 7% rating by the [[National Rifle Association|NRA]] in 2010.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://votesmart.org/candidate/101726/daniel-biss?categoryId=37&type=R | title = Daniel K. Biss' Political Summary on Issue: Guns | work = [[Project Vote Smart]] | accessdate = November 25, 2015 | publisher = One Common Ground | location = Philipsburg, Montana }}</ref> Biss has expressed support of [[labor union]]s<ref>{{cite news release | url = http://danielbiss.com/releases/Kickoff%20Press%20Release_091409.pdf | title = Biss Kicks Off Campaign With 150 Strong | date = September 14, 2009 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140221021013/http://danielbiss.com/releases/Kickoff%20Press%20Release_091409.pdf | archivedate=February 21, 2014 | publisher = Daniel Biss for State Representative | location = [[Evanston, Illinois]] }}</ref> and he received a $20,000 campaign contribution from [[AFSCME]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.journalstandard.com/x1696634795/Wage-increases-slow-but-not-campaign-contributions | title = Wage increases slow, but not campaign contributions | work = [[Journal Standard]] | edition = online | location = Freeport, Illinois | date = November 9, 2011 | agency = Illinois Statehouse News | accessdate = November 25, 2015 }}</ref> Biss also supports legalizing marijuana in Illinois.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://capitolfax.com/2017/03/29/where-do-the-candidates-stand-on-marijuana/|title=Capitol Fax.com - Your Illinois News Radar \u00bb Where do the candidates stand on marijuana?|website=capitolfax.com|access-date=2017-04-03}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Biss cosponsored SB&nbsp;1, a bill that aimed to limit the annual growth of retirement annuities within state employee's pension plans in an attempt to reduce debts in the state retirement system.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://votesmart.org/bill/16386/46516/amends-state-employee-pension-plans |title=SB&nbsp;1 \u2013 Amends State Employee Pension Plans \u2013 Key Vote | work = [[Project Vote Smart]] | publisher = One Common Ground | location = Philipsburg, Montana |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref> In May 2015, the Illinois Supreme Court found the law unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/politics/ct-illinois-pension-law-court-ruling-20150508-story.html |title=Illinois Supreme Court rules landmark pension law unconstitutional |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=8 May 2015 |last1=Pearson |first1=Rick |last2=Geiger |first2=Kim |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref> In rejecting the constitutionality of SB&nbsp;1, the Illinois Supreme Court stated: \"These modifications to pension benefits unquestionably diminish the value of the retirement annuities the members\u2026were promised when they joined the pension system. Accordingly, based on the plain language of the Act, these annuity-reducing provisions contravene the pension protection clause's absolute prohibition against diminishment of pension benefits and exceed the General Assembly\u2019s authority,\" the ruling states.<ref>http://chicago.suntimes.com/politics/pension-reforms-illinois-supreme-court/</ref> Biss later said that his work on SB&nbsp;1 was an error, saying \"I decided this was the least bad of the bad options. I allowed myself to think we couldn't do better.\" Biss later expressed support for funding higher pension payments if necessary by instituting a tax system with a graduated income tax and a tax on financial transactions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20180202/BLOGS02/180209967/illinois-governor-candidate-dan-biss-on-taxes-amazon-hq2-lasalle|title=Biss' populist play: Tax LaSalle Street and rethink Amazon HQ2|work=Crain's Chicago Business|access-date=2018-03-05}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Biss sponsored SB&nbsp;1424, a bill proposing a system of matching state funds for small-donor political contributions<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ilga.gov/legislation/BillStatus.asp?GA=100&DocTypeID=SB&DocNum=1424&GAID=14&SessionID=91&LegID=103770|title=Illinois General Assembly \u2013 Bill Status for SB1424|website=www.ilga.gov|access-date=2017-03-20}}</ref>  and SB&nbsp;780, a bill proposing to elect a number of statewide offices by [[Instant-runoff voting|ranked-choice ballot]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ilga.gov/legislation/BillStatus.asp?GA=100&DocTypeID=SB&DocNum=780&GAID=14&SessionID=91&LegID=102091|title=Illinois General Assembly \u2013 Bill Status for SB0780|website=www.ilga.gov|access-date=2017-03-20}}</ref> He also co-sponsored SB&nbsp;1933, a bill by State Sen. Andy Manar to allow for automatic voter registration when applying for an Illinois driver's license.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ilga.gov/legislation/BillStatus.asp?GA=100&DocTypeID=SB&DocNum=1933&GAID=14&SessionID=91&LegID=105253|title=Illinois General Assembly \u2013 Bill Status for SB1933|website=www.ilga.gov|access-date=2017-03-20}}</ref>\n\nBiss supports [[universal health care]] and advocates specifically for a state-level [[single-payer healthcare]] system.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Rich|title=Biss, Pawar respond *** Pritzker outlines Medicaid buy-in idea|url=https://capitolfax.com/2017/08/01/pritzker-outlines-medicaid-buy-in-idea/|accessdate=12 August 2017|work=capitolfax.com|date=1 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The truth about single-payer|url=https://www.danielbiss.com/single-payer/|website=Daniel Biss for Governor|accessdate=12 August 2017|date=5 August 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, Biss voted to reinforce the [[Affordable Care Act]] in Illinois by prohibiting insurance companies from discriminating against customers with [[pre-existing conditions]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dugyala|first1=Rishika|title=Biss joins fight to prevent denial of pre-existing conditions in Illinois|url=https://dailynorthwestern.com/2017/06/14/city/biss-joins-fight-to-prevent-denial-of-pre-existing-conditions-in-illinois/|accessdate=12 August 2017|work=The Daily Northwestern|date=14 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Campaigns ==\nBiss ran for a seat in the Illinois State House of Representatives in 2008, losing to [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Elizabeth Coulson]]. Starting in 2009, he then worked as a policy adviser to [[Pat Quinn (politician)|Pat Quinn]], the Democratic governor of Illinois.<ref name=JPost/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lai|first1=Jonathan|title=Ex-prof elected state rep|url=https://www.chicagomaroon.com/article/2010/11/12/ex-prof-elected-state-rep/|accessdate=28 May 2019|work=The Chicago Maroon|date=12 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Daniel Biss' Biography|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/101726/daniel-biss|website=Vote Smart: Facts Matter|accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Biss For Illinois 2017 campaign logo.png|thumb|Biss 2018 gubernatorial campaign logo.]]\nOn November 10, 2011, Biss announced his intent to run for the Illinois Senate seat held by retiring Senator [[Jeffrey Schoenberg]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=State Rep. Biss to seek Schoenberg's state Senate seat |first=Patrick |last=Svitek |date=November 10, 2011 |publisher=The Daily Northwestern |url=http://www.dailynorthwestern.com/city/state-rep-biss-to-seek-schoenberg-s-senate-seat-1.2669291 }}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He won the election on November 6, 2012, receiving over 66% of the vote,<ref name=chang>{{cite news | first = Chi-an | last = Chang | date = November 7, 2012 | title = Biss Wins 9th State Senate District Race | publisher = [[Patch Media]] | url = http://patch.com/illinois/winnetka/9th-state-senate-district-results-biss-vs-farkas | accessdate = 2016-09-26}}</ref> and was sworn in on January 8, 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.journal-topics.com/articles/biss-fine-take-oath-one-day-early/|title=Biss Fine Take Oath One Day Early|last=Robb|first=Tom|date=2013-01-09|website=Journal & Topics|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>\n\nBiss announced a run for [[Illinois Comptroller]] in the [[Illinois Comptroller special election, 2016|2016 special election]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pearson|first1=Rick|title=City Clerk Mendoza gets major union backing in state comptroller bid|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/politics/ct-susana-mendoza-comptroller-endorsement-met0924-20150923-story.html|accessdate=3 October 2015|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=22 September 2015}}</ref> but dropped out and endorsed opponent [[Susana Mendoza]].<ref>{{cite news release | url = http://www.danielbiss.com/comptroller-1 | first = Daniel | last = Biss | title = Comptroller Campaign Update | work = Biss for Illinois | location = [[Evanston, Illinois]] | accessdate = 2015-11-25 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151125205006/http://www.danielbiss.com/comptroller-1 | archive-date = 2015-11-25 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, 2017, Biss announced his candidacy for the Democratic nomination for [[Governor of Illinois]] for [[Illinois gubernatorial election, 2018|the 2018 election]] on a [[Facebook Live]] video, attacking incumbent governor [[Bruce Rauner]] and Illinois House Speaker [[Mike Madigan]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pearson|first1=Rick|title=State Sen. Daniel Biss announces Democratic bid for governor|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/politics/ct-daniel-biss-illinois-governor-race-met-0320-20170319-story.html|accessdate=20 March 2017|work=chicagotribune.com|agency=Chicago Tribune|date=March 20, 2017}}</ref> Biss joined a growing field of Democratic contenders, including businessman [[Christopher G. Kennedy|C. G. Kennedy]] and Chicago alderman [[Ameya Pawar]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schulte|first1=Sarah|title=State Sen. Biss says he's running for Illinois governor|url=http://abc7chicago.com/politics/state-sen-biss-says-hes-running-for-illinois-governor/1809229/|accessdate=20 March 2017|work=ABC7 Chicago|date=20 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320173905/http://abc7chicago.com/politics/state-sen-biss-says-hes-running-for-illinois-governor/1809229/|archive-date=20 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBiss briefly named Chicago alderman and [[Democratic Socialists of America]] member [[Carlos Ramirez-Rosa]] as his gubernatorial running mate, but dropped him from the ticket after just six days after Ramirez-Rosa expressed some support for the [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions]] boycott movement against [[Israel]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Ryan|title=Ramirez-Rosa dumped off the Biss ticket in six days; denies flip-flop on Israel issue|url=https://www.chicagoreader.com/Bleader/archives/2017/09/07/ramirez-rosa-dumped-off-the-biss-ticket-in-six-days-denies-flip-flop-on-israel-issue|accessdate=9 October 2017|work=Chicago Reader}}</ref> Biss later announced his selection of [[Rockford, Illinois|Rockford]]-based [[Illinois House of Representatives|state representative]] [[Litesa Wallace]], a single mother and former [[social worker]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vinicky|first1=Amanda|title=Daniel Biss Replaces Ramirez-Rosa with Rep. Litesa Wallace|url=http://chicagotonight.wttw.com/2017/09/08/daniel-biss-replaces-ramirez-rosa-rep-litesa-wallace|accessdate=9 October 2017|work=Chicago Tonight {{!}} WTTW}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Biss formally announces Litesa Wallace as new running mate|url=https://capitolfax.com/2017/09/08/biss-formally-announces-litesa-wallace-as-new-running-mate/|accessdate=9 October 2017|work=capitolfax.com|date=8 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nBiss had been endorsed by many of his colleagues in the Illinois General Assembly, high-profile academics and activists including Nobel laureate [[Richard Thaler]] and presidential candidate [[Lawrence Lessig]], [[National Nurses United]], the largest organization of registered nurses in the United States, and [[Our Revolution]], the successor organization to [[Bernie Sanders]]' [[Bernie Sanders presidential campaign, 2016|2016 presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Who's on Team Biss?|url=https://www.danielbiss.com/team-biss-endorsements/|website=Daniel Biss for Governor|publisher=Biss for Illinois|accessdate=22 January 2018|date=6 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201080830/https://www.danielbiss.com/team-biss-endorsements/|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Pedersen|first1=Brendan|title=Biss Lands Major Progressive Group's Endorsement|url=https://www.nbcchicago.com/blogs/ward-room/our-revolution-illinois-endorses-sen-daniel-biss-471698764.html|accessdate=30 January 2018|work=NBC Chicago|date=30 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Our Revolution Endorses Daniel Biss for Governor of Illinois|url=https://ourrevolution.com/press/our-revolution-endorses-daniel-biss-governor-illinois/|website=Our Revolution|accessdate=16 March 2018|date=27 February 2018}}</ref> Biss received two-thirds of preferential votes from Illinois members of the progressive advocacy group [[MoveOn.org]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Payne|first1=Benjamin|title=Daniel Biss Lands MoveOn.org Endorsement For Illinois Governor|url=http://wvik.org/post/daniel-biss-lands-moveonorg-endorsement-illinois-governor#stream/0|accessdate=30 January 2018|agency=WVIK|date=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, 2018, Biss lost the Democratic primary to [[J. B. Pritzker]]. He earned  26.70% of the total vote, behind Prizker with 45.13% and ahead of [[Christopher G. Kennedy|C. G. Kennedy]] with 24.37%. \nBiss carried two counties, [[McLean County, Illinois|McLean]] and [[Champaign County, Illinois|Champaign]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Canvas, General Primary Election, March 20, 2018 |url=https://www.elections.il.gov/Downloads/ElectionInformation/VoteTotals/2018GPOfficialVote.pdf |publisher=Illinois State Board of Elections}}</ref>\n\n== Post-senate activities ==\n\nOn September 18, 2018, Biss announced in an email to supporters that he has accepted the position of executive director of the nonprofit Rust Belt Rising, which aims to train and support Democratic candidates in the [[Great Lakes region|Great Lakes states]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Meadows |first1=Jonah |title=Sen. Daniel Biss To Head Democratic Candidate Training Nonprofit |url=https://patch.com/illinois/evanston/sen-daniel-biss-head-democratic-candidate-training-nonprofit |accessdate=19 September 2018 |work=Evanston, IL Patch |date=18 September 2018}}</ref> Biss was succeeded in the Illinois Senate by [[Laura Fine]] on January 6, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.illinoissenatedemocrats.com/caucus-news/106-senator-laura-fine-news/6860-fine-sworn-in-as-state-senator|title=Fine sworn in as State Senator|last=|first=|date=2019-01-07|website=Illinois Senate Democrats|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>\n\nOn August 15, 2019, Biss announced his endorsement of [[Elizabeth Warren]] [[Elizabeth Warren 2020 presidential campaign|for president]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DanielBiss/status/1162009805604761600|title=Endorsement of Elizabeth Warren|last=Biss|first=Daniel|date=August 15, 2019|website=[[Twitter]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 3, 2020|quote=\"A presidential candidate whose rallying cry is \"big structural change\" -- yes, please! ... I'm proud to endorse [[Elizabeth Warren]], who represents a once-in-a-generation opportunity to reform our broken system. I hope you'll join me in supporting her. [pic.twitter.com/LNGu8Bufgb Video]\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Sweet|first=Lynn|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/8/15/20808045/pete-buttigieg-chicago-elizabeth-warren-hires-illinois-director-amy-klobuchar-state-delegate-slates|title=Buttigieg\u2019s Chicago presidential outpost; Warren hires Illinois director; Klobuchar working on state delegate slates|date=August 15, 2019|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|access-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211141043/https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/8/15/20808045/pete-buttigieg-chicago-elizabeth-warren-hires-illinois-director-amy-klobuchar-state-delegate-slates|archive-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref> In January 2020, Biss was selected to be on Warren's slate of 101 potential Illinois delegates to the [[2020 Democratic National Convention]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Bill|url=https://evanstonnow.com/story/government/bill-smith/election-2020/2020-01-04/83994/ten-evanstonians-seek-to-be-democratic|title=Ten Evanstonians seek to be Democratic presidential convention delegates|date=January 4, 2020|work=Evanston Now|access-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402184805/https://evanstonnow.com/story/government/bill-smith/election-2020/2020-01-04/83994/ten-evanstonians-seek-to-be-democratic|archive-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|last=Meadows|first=Jonah|url=https://patch.com/illinois/evanston/these-9th-district-residents-are-potential-convention-delegates|title=These 9th district residents are potential convention delegates|date=January 31, 2020|work=[[Patch Media|Patch]]|access-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224025514/https://patch.com/illinois/evanston/these-9th-district-residents-are-potential-convention-delegates|archive-date=February 24, 2020}}</ref> but Warren suspended her campaign on March 5, before [[2020 Illinois Democratic primary|the presidential primary in Illinois]] on March 17.<ref>{{cite news|last=Goldmacher|first=Shane|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/05/us/politics/elizabeth-warren-drops-out.html|title=Elizabeth Warren, once a front-runner, drops out of presidential race|date=March 5, 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328220831/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/05/us/politics/elizabeth-warren-drops-out.html|archive-date=March 28, 2020|last2=Herndon|first2=Astead|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ [[Illinois House of Representatives]], 17th district: Results, 2008\u20132010<ref name=\"results\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cookcountyclerk.com/elections/results/Pages/default.aspx |title=Election Results |accessdate=July 8, 2013 |publisher=Cook County Board of Elections }}</ref>\n!| Year\n!\n!| Democratic\n!| Votes\n!| Pct\n!\n!| Republican\n!| Votes\n!| Pct\n|-\n| [[Illinois House of Representatives elections, 2008|2008]]\n|\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} |Daniel Biss\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" |25,959\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} |48.52%\n|\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} |'''[[Elizabeth Coulson]]'''\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |'''27,540'''\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} |'''51.48%'''\n|-\n| [[Illinois House of Representatives elections, 2010|2010]]\n|\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | '''Daniel Biss'''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" | '''23,134'''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | '''54.78%'''\n|\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | Hamilton Chang\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" | 19,096\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | 45.22%\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ [[Illinois Senate]], 9th district: Results, 2012\u20132014<ref name=\"results\"/>\n!| Year\n!\n!| Democratic\n!| Votes\n!| Pct\n!\n!| Republican\n!| Votes\n!| Pct\n|-\n| [[Illinois Senate elections, 2012|2012]]\n|\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | '''Daniel Biss'''\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" | '''68,064'''\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | '''66.63%'''\n|\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | Glenn Farkas\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" | 34,081\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | 33.37%\n|-\n| [[Illinois Senate elections, 2014|2014]]\n|\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | '''Daniel Biss'''\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" | '''55,986'''\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | '''100.00%'''\n|\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} |\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} |\n|}\n\n{{election box begin no change\n| title = Illinois gubernatorial primary results, 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=809635|title=Illinois gubernatorial primary election results (2018)|last=|first=|date=March 20, 2018|website=Our Campaigns|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403012839/https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=809635|archive-date=April 3, 2020|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate  = [[J. B. Pritzker]]\n| party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes      = 597,756\n| percentage = 45.13\n}}\n{{election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate  = [[Daniel Biss]]\n| party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes      = 353,625\n| percentage = 26.70\n}}\n{{election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate  = [[Christopher G. Kennedy|C. G. Kennedy]]\n| party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes      = 322,730\n| percentage = 24.37\n}}\n{{election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate  = Tio Hardiman\n| party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes      = 21,075\n| percentage = 1.59\n}}\n{{election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate  = Bob Daiber\n| party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes      = 15,009\n| percentage = 1.13\n}}\n{{election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate  = Robert Marshall\n| party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes      = 14,353\n| percentage = 1.08\n}}\n{{election box total no change\n| votes      = 1,324,548\n| percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{election box end}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Illinois House of Representatives elections, 2010]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://my.ilga.gov/Member/Index/2020?tab=1&chamber=S Biography, bills and committees] at the 98th Illinois General Assembly\n**By session: [http://www.ilga.gov/senate/Senator.asp?GA=98&MemberID=2020 98th], [http://www.ilga.gov/house/Rep.asp?GA=97&MemberID=1778 97th]\n*[http://senatorbiss.com/ Illinois State Senator Daniel Biss] legislative website\n*[http://www.illinoissenatedemocrats.com/index.php/sen-biss-home Senator Daniel Biss] at Illinois Senate Democrats\n*[http://danielbiss.com/ Daniel Biss for Illinois] campaign website\n{{CongLinks | votesmart = 101726 }}\n*{{MathGenealogy|67217}}\n*[http://rustbeltrising.org Rust Belt Rising], political organization that Biss is executive director of\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par | us-il-hs}}\n{{succession box\n| title  = {{nowrap|Member of the [[Illinois House of Representatives]]}} <br> from the 17th district\n| years  = May 2011 &ndash; January 8, 2013\n| before = [[Elizabeth Coulson]]\n| after  = [[Laura Fine]]\n}}\n{{s-par | us-il-sen}}\n{{succession box\n| title  = Member of the [[Illinois Senate]] <br> from the 9th district\n| years  = January 8, 2013 &ndash; January 6, 2019\n| before = [[Jeffrey Schoenberg]]\n| after  = [[Laura Fine]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Biss, Daniel}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American people of Romanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Illinois Democrats]]\n[[Category:Illinois state senators]]\n[[Category:Institute for Advanced Study visiting scholars]]\n[[Category:Jewish American politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Mathematicians from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Mathematicians from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Members of the Illinois House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Morgan Prize winners]]\n[[Category:People from Bloomington, Illinois]]\n[[Category:People from Evanston, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Akron, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Topologists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American mathematician and politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Daniel Biss\n| image        = File:Daniel Biss 2012 (cropped).jpg\n| state_senate = Illinois\n| district     = 9th\n| term_start   = January 8, 2013\n| term_end     = January 6, 2019\n| predecessor  = [[Jeffrey Schoenberg]]\n| successor    = [[Laura Fine]]\n| state_house1 = Illinois\n| district1    = 17th\n| term_start1  = May 2011\n| term_end1    = January 8, 2013\n| predecessor1 = [[Elizabeth Coulson]]\n| successor1   = Laura Fine\n| birth_name   = Daniel K\u00e1lm\u00e1n Biss\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1977|8|27}}\n| birth_place  = [[Akron, Ohio|Akron]], [[Ohio]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse       = Karin Steinbrueck\n| children     = 2\n| education    = [[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]]) <br> [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])\n| profession   = [[Mathematician]]\n| website      = {{url|danielbiss.com|Official website}}\n| signature    = BissSig.png\n}}\n\n'''Daniel K\u00e1lm\u00e1n Biss'''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.harvard.edu/gazette/1998/05.28/HoopesPrizesAwa.html | title=Hoopes Prizes Awarded to Undergraduates and Thesis Advisers | work=Harvard Gazette | date=28 May 1998 | accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref> (born August 27, 1977)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://math.mit.edu/~gracelyo/18904/BissCoveringSpaceArticle.pdf | title=A Generalized Approach to the Fundamental Group | publisher=Mathematical Association of America | work=The American Mathematical Monthly | date=October 2000 | accessdate=2 June 2016 | author=Biss, Daniel K.}}</ref> is an American mathematician and politician who was the member of the [[Illinois Senate]] for the 9th district from January 2013 until January 2019. The district includes Chicago's northern suburbs, including [[Evanston, Illinois|Evanston]], [[Glencoe, Illinois|Glencoe]], [[Glenview, Illinois|Glenview]], [[Morton Grove, Illinois|Morton Grove]], [[Northbrook, Illinois|Northbrook]], [[Northfield, Illinois|Northfield]], [[Skokie, Illinois|Skokie]], [[Wilmette, Illinois|Wilmette]], and [[Winnetka, Illinois|Winnetka]]. Biss first ran for office in 2008 and was a member of the [[Illinois House of Representatives]] from 2011 to 2013. He was also a candidate in the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] primary for [[Governor of Illinois]] in the [[Illinois gubernatorial election, 2018|2018 election]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/politics/ct-daniel-biss-illinois-governor-race-met-0320-20170319-story.html|title=State Sen. Daniel Biss announces Democratic bid for governor}}</ref>\n\nPrior to pursuing a political career, Biss was an Assistant Professor of Mathematics at the [[University of Chicago]] from 2002 to 2008.\n\n== Personal life and education ==\nBiss was born into a Jewish [[Israelis|Israeli]] family<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/BDS-THREAT/Jewish-candidate-for-Illinois-governor-drops-running-mate-over-BDS-504506 Jewish candidate for Illinois governor drops running mate over BDS], ''Jerusalem Post'',\n September 7, 2017.</ref><ref>[[David Weigel]], [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2017/09/07/in-illinois-a-democrat-chooses-a-socialist-running-mate-then-dumps-him/ In Illinois, a Democrat chooses a socialist running mate, then dumps him], ''Washington Post'', September 7, 2017.</ref> of musicians: his brother is the noted pianist [[Jonathan Biss]], his parents are the violinists [[Paul Biss]] and [[Miriam Fried]], and his grandmother was the Russian-born cellist [[Raya Garbousova]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Jonathan Biss: A Super, Human, Musical Mission|url=https://www.sfcv.org/events-calendar/artist-spotlight/jonathan-biss-a-super-human-musical-mission|accessdate=September 5, 2013|newspaper=San Francisco Classical Voice|author=Swinkels, Niels|date=June 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jonathan Biss|url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/opera-classical/jonathan-biss|accessdate=September 5, 2013|newspaper=Time Out New York|author=Giovetti, Olivia|date=January 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBiss attended [[Bloomington North High School]] in [[Bloomington, Indiana]], and he was a finalist in the [[Westinghouse Science Talent Search]] in 1995.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bloomington youth stars in science |url=https://newspapers.library.in.gov/cgi-bin/indiana?a=d&d=JPOST19950222-01.1.3 |work=Jewish Post, Indianapolis |date=22 February 1995 |page=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=What does science have to do with the race for governor in Illinois? |url=https://www.societyforscience.org/content/ssp-blog/what-does-science-have-do-race-governor-illinois |publisher=Society for Science & the Public |date=February 21, 2018}}</ref> He\nreceived an undergraduate degree from [[Harvard University]], graduating ''[[summa cum laude]]'' in 1998, and a Ph.D. at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] in 2002, both in mathematics.<ref name=szpiro>{{cite book|title=A mathematical medley: fifty easy pieces on mathematics|author=Szpiro, George G.|authorlink= George Szpiro|pages=97\u201399|year=2010|publisher=American Mathematical Society|chapter=20: Brilliant but Fallible|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mXWr00HurmMC|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=mXWr00HurmMC&pg=PA97|isbn=9780821890646}}</ref> He won the 1999 [[Morgan Prize]] for outstanding research as an undergraduate, and was a [[Clay Mathematics Institute|Clay Research Fellow]] from 2002 to 2007.<ref>[http://www.claymath.org/fas/research_fellows/Biss Daniel Biss], [[Clay Mathematics Institute]]</ref> His doctoral advisor was [[Michael J. Hopkins]]. He was a visiting scholar at the [[Institute for Advanced Study]] in the fall of 2003.<ref>[http://www.ias.edu/people/cos/users/daniel Institute for Advanced Study: A Community of Scholars]</ref>\n\nBiss also wrote an appendix for the popular 2006 [[Young adult fiction|young adult]] novel ''[[An Abundance of Katherines]]'', by [[John Green (author)|John Green]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nir|first1=Oaz|year=2008|title=Book Review: An Abundance of Katherines|journal=Notices of the AMS|volume=55|issue=9|pages=1096\u201398|publisher=American Mathematical Society|doi=|url=http://www.ams.org/notices/200809/tx080901096p.pdf|accessdate=June 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Mathematics career ==\nPrior to full-time pursuit of a political career, Biss was an Assistant Professor of Mathematics at the [[University of Chicago]] from 2002 to 2008.<ref name=JPost>{{cite web |url=http://www.jpost.com/American-Politics/Spot-the-differences-between-the-two-Jewish-candidates-for-Illinois-governor-543636 |title= Spot the differences between the two Jewish candidates for Illinois governor |work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |date=February 26, 2018 |accessdate=March 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt least four of the mathematics papers that Biss published in academic journals were later discovered to contain major errors. Mathematician Nikolai Mn\u00ebv published a report in 2007 that there was a \"serious flaw\" in two of Biss's works published in ''[[Annals of Mathematics]]'' and ''[[Advances in Mathematics]]'' in 2003, saying \"unfortunately this simple mistake destroys the main theorems of both papers\".<ref>{{cite arxiv |eprint=0709.1291|last1=Mnev|first1=N|title=On D.K. Biss' papers \"The homotopy type of the matroid Grassmannian\" and \"Oriented matroids, complex manifolds, and a combinatorial model for BU\"|class=math.CO|year=2007}}</ref> In 2008 and 2009, Biss acknowledged the flaw and published [[erratum]] reports for the two papers, thanking Mn\u00ebv for drawing his attention to the error.<ref name=szpiro/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Biss|first=Daniel K.|date=July 2009|title=Erratum to 'The homotopy type of the matroid Grassmannian'|url=http://annals.math.princeton.edu/wp-content/uploads/annals-v170-n1-p15-p.pdf|journal=[[Annals of Mathematics]]|series=2nd|volume=170-1|page=493|doi=10.4007/annals.2009.170.493|pmid=|accessdate=May 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first=Daniel |last=Biss |title=Erratum to 'Oriented matroids, complex manifolds, and a combinatorial model for BU' [Adv. Math. 179 (2) (2003) 250\u2013290] |journal=[[Advances in Mathematics]] |volume=221 |issue=2 |page=681 |date=June 1, 2009 |doi=10.1016/j.aim.2008.12.012 }}</ref> He and a co-author, [[Benson Farb]], also acknowledged in 2009 that there was a \"fatal error\" in a paper they had published in ''[[Inventiones Mathematicae]]'' in 2006, thanking mathematicians Masatoshi Sato and Tom Church for helping to explain the problem.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Erratum to {{'}}''Kg'' is not finitely generated' |first1=Daniel K. |last=Biss |first2=Benson |last2=Farb |journal=[[Inventiones Mathematicae]] |volume=178 |issue=1 |page=229 |date=October 2009 |doi=10.1007/s00222-009-0202-x |arxiv=math/0405386 |bibcode=2009InMat.178..229B }}</ref> Another of his papers published in ''[[Topology and its Applications]]'' was formally retracted by the publisher in 2017, fifteen years after its 2002 publication, with the journal saying \"This article has been retracted at the request of the Editors-in-Chief after receiving a complaint about anomalies in this paper. The editors solicited further independent reviews which indicated that the definitions in the paper are ambiguous and most results are false. The author was contacted and does not dispute these findings.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Retraction notice to 'The topological fundamental group and generalized covering spaces' [Topol. Appl. 124 (3) (2002) 355\u2013371] |journal=[[Topology and its Applications]] |date=15 February 2017 |volume=217 |page=116 |doi=10.1016/j.topol.2016.12.016 |last1=Biss |first1=Daniel K. }}</ref> The journal said they had identified twelve specific errors in the paper, but clarified that they had concluded that the paper's findings were merely inaccurate, not fraudulent.<ref name=Pi>{{cite newspaper |url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/news/are-gov-hopeful-bisss-claims-of-math-prowess-pi-in-the-sky/ |title=Are gov hopeful Biss's claims of math prowess pi in the sky? |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=September 29, 2017 |access-date=March 26, 2018 |first=Tina |last=Sfondeles}}</ref><ref name=Watch1>{{cite web |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2017/02/13/journal-retracts-paper-state-senator-former-mathematician/ |title=Journal retracts paper by state senator (and former mathematician) |date=February 13, 2017 |work=[[Retraction Watch]] |access-date=March 26, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Watch2>{{cite web |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2017/02/23/false-results-retracted-paper-senator-inaccurate-not-fraudulent-say-editors/ |title='False' results in retracted paper by senator are inaccurate, not fraudulent, say editors |work=[[Retraction Watch]] |date=February 23, 2017 |access-date=March 26, 2018}}</ref> When contacted by the journal, Biss had responded saying \"Thank you for writing. I am no longer in mathematics and so don't feel equipped to fully evaluate these claims. I certainly do not dispute them. If you would like to publish a retraction to that effect, that would seem to me to be an appropriate approach.\"<ref name=Pi/><ref name=Watch2/>\n\nWhen the 2017 retraction and the previously identified errors were reported by the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' in September 2017, his campaign blamed operatives for the perceived front-runner for the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] candidate for governor of Illinois, [[J. B. Pritzker]], for raising it as a political issue. They said \"Whether it was training at MIT or the University of Chicago, Daniel has had dozens of academic papers reviewed by his peers and published. In a few cases, further research has found that the case posited in the original article didn't stand up, and he revised his findings.\"<ref name=Pi/> They referred to the raising of the issue as \"silly opposition research\".<ref name=Pi/>\n\n== Illinois House of Representatives ==\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\n*Appropriations \u2013 Elementary & Secondary Education\n*Personnel & Pensions\n*Consumer Protection\n*Small Business Empowerment & Workforce Development\n*International Trade & Commerce \n*Bio-Technology\n*Appropriations \u2013 Higher Education<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilga.gov/house//Rep.asp?MemberID=1778 |title=Representative Daniel Biss (D) |publisher=www.ilga.gov |date= |accessdate={{date|2011-02-22}}}}</ref>\n\n=== Tenure ===\n{{expand section | date = April 2020}}\n\n== Illinois Senate ==\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\n{{expand section | date = April 2020}}\n\n=== Tenure ===\n{{expand section | date = April 2020}}\n\n== Political views ==\n[[File:Stop Brett Kavanaugh Rally Downtown Chicago Illinois (43406990865).jpg|thumb|right|Biss at a rally against the appointment of [[Brett Kavanaugh]] to the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] in 2018]]\nAccording to his responses in a 2008 \"[[Political Courage Test]]\", Daniel Biss supports carbon emissions limits and is [[pro-choice]] (supporting legal access to abortion services). He also supports allowing Illinois high school graduates to pay in-state tuition at public universities regardless of immigration status, as well as state funding to raise the salaries of teachers.<ref name=PCT2008>{{cite web | url = http://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/101726/daniel-biss/ | title = Daniel Biss' Issue Positions | work = [[Project Vote Smart]] | year = 2008 | publisher = One Common Ground | location = Philipsburg, Montana }}</ref> He received a 7% rating by the [[National Rifle Association|NRA]] in 2010.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://votesmart.org/candidate/101726/daniel-biss?categoryId=37&type=R | title = Daniel K. Biss' Political Summary on Issue: Guns | work = [[Project Vote Smart]] | accessdate = November 25, 2015 | publisher = One Common Ground | location = Philipsburg, Montana }}</ref> Biss has expressed support of [[labor union]]s<ref>{{cite news release | url = http://danielbiss.com/releases/Kickoff%20Press%20Release_091409.pdf | title = Biss Kicks Off Campaign With 150 Strong | date = September 14, 2009 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140221021013/http://danielbiss.com/releases/Kickoff%20Press%20Release_091409.pdf | archivedate=February 21, 2014 | publisher = Daniel Biss for State Representative | location = [[Evanston, Illinois]] }}</ref> and he received a $20,000 campaign contribution from [[AFSCME]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.journalstandard.com/x1696634795/Wage-increases-slow-but-not-campaign-contributions | title = Wage increases slow, but not campaign contributions | work = [[Journal Standard]] | edition = online | location = Freeport, Illinois | date = November 9, 2011 | agency = Illinois Statehouse News | accessdate = November 25, 2015 }}</ref> Biss also supports legalizing marijuana in Illinois.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://capitolfax.com/2017/03/29/where-do-the-candidates-stand-on-marijuana/|title=Capitol Fax.com - Your Illinois News Radar \u00bb Where do the candidates stand on marijuana?|website=capitolfax.com|access-date=2017-04-03}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Biss cosponsored SB&nbsp;1, a bill that aimed to limit the annual growth of retirement annuities within state employee's pension plans in an attempt to reduce debts in the state retirement system.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://votesmart.org/bill/16386/46516/amends-state-employee-pension-plans |title=SB&nbsp;1 \u2013 Amends State Employee Pension Plans \u2013 Key Vote | work = [[Project Vote Smart]] | publisher = One Common Ground | location = Philipsburg, Montana |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref> In May 2015, the Illinois Supreme Court found the law unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/politics/ct-illinois-pension-law-court-ruling-20150508-story.html |title=Illinois Supreme Court rules landmark pension law unconstitutional |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=8 May 2015 |last1=Pearson |first1=Rick |last2=Geiger |first2=Kim |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref> In rejecting the constitutionality of SB&nbsp;1, the Illinois Supreme Court stated: \"These modifications to pension benefits unquestionably diminish the value of the retirement annuities the members\u2026were promised when they joined the pension system. Accordingly, based on the plain language of the Act, these annuity-reducing provisions contravene the pension protection clause's absolute prohibition against diminishment of pension benefits and exceed the General Assembly\u2019s authority,\" the ruling states.<ref>http://chicago.suntimes.com/politics/pension-reforms-illinois-supreme-court/</ref> Biss later said that his work on SB&nbsp;1 was an error, saying \"I decided this was the least bad of the bad options. I allowed myself to think we couldn't do better.\" Biss later expressed support for funding higher pension payments if necessary by instituting a tax system with a graduated income tax and a tax on financial transactions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20180202/BLOGS02/180209967/illinois-governor-candidate-dan-biss-on-taxes-amazon-hq2-lasalle|title=Biss' populist play: Tax LaSalle Street and rethink Amazon HQ2|work=Crain's Chicago Business|access-date=2018-03-05}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Biss sponsored SB&nbsp;1424, a bill proposing a system of matching state funds for small-donor political contributions<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ilga.gov/legislation/BillStatus.asp?GA=100&DocTypeID=SB&DocNum=1424&GAID=14&SessionID=91&LegID=103770|title=Illinois General Assembly \u2013 Bill Status for SB1424|website=www.ilga.gov|access-date=2017-03-20}}</ref>  and SB&nbsp;780, a bill proposing to elect a number of statewide offices by [[Instant-runoff voting|ranked-choice ballot]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ilga.gov/legislation/BillStatus.asp?GA=100&DocTypeID=SB&DocNum=780&GAID=14&SessionID=91&LegID=102091|title=Illinois General Assembly \u2013 Bill Status for SB0780|website=www.ilga.gov|access-date=2017-03-20}}</ref> He also co-sponsored SB&nbsp;1933, a bill by State Sen. Andy Manar to allow for automatic voter registration when applying for an Illinois driver's license.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ilga.gov/legislation/BillStatus.asp?GA=100&DocTypeID=SB&DocNum=1933&GAID=14&SessionID=91&LegID=105253|title=Illinois General Assembly \u2013 Bill Status for SB1933|website=www.ilga.gov|access-date=2017-03-20}}</ref>\n\nBiss supports [[universal health care]] and advocates specifically for a state-level [[single-payer healthcare]] system.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Rich|title=Biss, Pawar respond *** Pritzker outlines Medicaid buy-in idea|url=https://capitolfax.com/2017/08/01/pritzker-outlines-medicaid-buy-in-idea/|accessdate=12 August 2017|work=capitolfax.com|date=1 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The truth about single-payer|url=https://www.danielbiss.com/single-payer/|website=Daniel Biss for Governor|accessdate=12 August 2017|date=5 August 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, Biss voted to reinforce the [[Affordable Care Act]] in Illinois by prohibiting insurance companies from discriminating against customers with [[pre-existing conditions]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dugyala|first1=Rishika|title=Biss joins fight to prevent denial of pre-existing conditions in Illinois|url=https://dailynorthwestern.com/2017/06/14/city/biss-joins-fight-to-prevent-denial-of-pre-existing-conditions-in-illinois/|accessdate=12 August 2017|work=The Daily Northwestern|date=14 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Campaigns ==\nBiss ran for a seat in the Illinois State House of Representatives in 2008, losing to [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Elizabeth Coulson]]. Starting in 2009, he then worked as a policy adviser to [[Pat Quinn (politician)|Pat Quinn]], the Democratic governor of Illinois.<ref name=JPost/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lai|first1=Jonathan|title=Ex-prof elected state rep|url=https://www.chicagomaroon.com/article/2010/11/12/ex-prof-elected-state-rep/|accessdate=28 May 2019|work=The Chicago Maroon|date=12 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Daniel Biss' Biography|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/101726/daniel-biss|website=Vote Smart: Facts Matter|accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Biss For Illinois 2017 campaign logo.png|thumb|Biss 2018 gubernatorial campaign logo.]]\nOn November 10, 2011, Biss announced his intent to run for the Illinois Senate seat held by retiring Senator [[Jeffrey Schoenberg]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=State Rep. Biss to seek Schoenberg's state Senate seat |first=Patrick |last=Svitek |date=November 10, 2011 |publisher=The Daily Northwestern |url=http://www.dailynorthwestern.com/city/state-rep-biss-to-seek-schoenberg-s-senate-seat-1.2669291 }}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He won the election on November 6, 2012, receiving over 66% of the vote,<ref name=chang>{{cite news | first = Chi-an | last = Chang | date = November 7, 2012 | title = Biss Wins 9th State Senate District Race | publisher = [[Patch Media]] | url = http://patch.com/illinois/winnetka/9th-state-senate-district-results-biss-vs-farkas | accessdate = 2016-09-26}}</ref> and was sworn in on January 8, 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.journal-topics.com/articles/biss-fine-take-oath-one-day-early/|title=Biss Fine Take Oath One Day Early|last=Robb|first=Tom|date=2013-01-09|website=Journal & Topics|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>\n\nBiss announced a run for [[Illinois Comptroller]] in the [[Illinois Comptroller special election, 2016|2016 special election]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pearson|first1=Rick|title=City Clerk Mendoza gets major union backing in state comptroller bid|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/politics/ct-susana-mendoza-comptroller-endorsement-met0924-20150923-story.html|accessdate=3 October 2015|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=22 September 2015}}</ref> but dropped out and endorsed opponent [[Susana Mendoza]].<ref>{{cite news release | url = http://www.danielbiss.com/comptroller-1 | first = Daniel | last = Biss | title = Comptroller Campaign Update | work = Biss for Illinois | location = [[Evanston, Illinois]] | accessdate = 2015-11-25 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151125205006/http://www.danielbiss.com/comptroller-1 | archive-date = 2015-11-25 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, 2017, Biss announced his candidacy for the Democratic nomination for [[Governor of Illinois]] for [[Illinois gubernatorial election, 2018|the 2018 election]] on a [[Facebook Live]] video, attacking incumbent governor [[Bruce Rauner]] and Illinois House Speaker [[Mike Madigan]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pearson|first1=Rick|title=State Sen. Daniel Biss announces Democratic bid for governor|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/politics/ct-daniel-biss-illinois-governor-race-met-0320-20170319-story.html|accessdate=20 March 2017|work=chicagotribune.com|agency=Chicago Tribune|date=March 20, 2017}}</ref> Biss joined a growing field of Democratic contenders, including businessman [[Christopher G. Kennedy|C. G. Kennedy]] and Chicago alderman [[Ameya Pawar]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schulte|first1=Sarah|title=State Sen. Biss says he's running for Illinois governor|url=http://abc7chicago.com/politics/state-sen-biss-says-hes-running-for-illinois-governor/1809229/|accessdate=20 March 2017|work=ABC7 Chicago|date=20 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320173905/http://abc7chicago.com/politics/state-sen-biss-says-hes-running-for-illinois-governor/1809229/|archive-date=20 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBiss briefly named Chicago alderman and [[Democratic Socialists of America]] member [[Carlos Ramirez-Rosa]] as his gubernatorial running mate, but dropped him from the ticket after just six days after Ramirez-Rosa expressed some support for the [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions]] boycott movement against [[Israel]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Ryan|title=Ramirez-Rosa dumped off the Biss ticket in six days; denies flip-flop on Israel issue|url=https://www.chicagoreader.com/Bleader/archives/2017/09/07/ramirez-rosa-dumped-off-the-biss-ticket-in-six-days-denies-flip-flop-on-israel-issue|accessdate=9 October 2017|work=Chicago Reader}}</ref> Biss later announced his selection of [[Rockford, Illinois|Rockford]]-based [[Illinois House of Representatives|state representative]] [[Litesa Wallace]], a single mother and former [[social worker]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vinicky|first1=Amanda|title=Daniel Biss Replaces Ramirez-Rosa with Rep. Litesa Wallace|url=http://chicagotonight.wttw.com/2017/09/08/daniel-biss-replaces-ramirez-rosa-rep-litesa-wallace|accessdate=9 October 2017|work=Chicago Tonight {{!}} WTTW}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Biss formally announces Litesa Wallace as new running mate|url=https://capitolfax.com/2017/09/08/biss-formally-announces-litesa-wallace-as-new-running-mate/|accessdate=9 October 2017|work=capitolfax.com|date=8 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nBiss had been endorsed by many of his colleagues in the Illinois General Assembly, high-profile academics and activists including Nobel laureate [[Richard Thaler]] and presidential candidate [[Lawrence Lessig]], [[National Nurses United]], the largest organization of registered nurses in the United States, and [[Our Revolution]], the successor organization to [[Bernie Sanders]]' [[Bernie Sanders presidential campaign, 2016|2016 presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Who's on Team Biss?|url=https://www.danielbiss.com/team-biss-endorsements/|website=Daniel Biss for Governor|publisher=Biss for Illinois|accessdate=22 January 2018|date=6 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201080830/https://www.danielbiss.com/team-biss-endorsements/|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Pedersen|first1=Brendan|title=Biss Lands Major Progressive Group's Endorsement|url=https://www.nbcchicago.com/blogs/ward-room/our-revolution-illinois-endorses-sen-daniel-biss-471698764.html|accessdate=30 January 2018|work=NBC Chicago|date=30 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Our Revolution Endorses Daniel Biss for Governor of Illinois|url=https://ourrevolution.com/press/our-revolution-endorses-daniel-biss-governor-illinois/|website=Our Revolution|accessdate=16 March 2018|date=27 February 2018}}</ref> Biss received two-thirds of preferential votes from Illinois members of the progressive advocacy group [[MoveOn.org]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Payne|first1=Benjamin|title=Daniel Biss Lands MoveOn.org Endorsement For Illinois Governor|url=http://wvik.org/post/daniel-biss-lands-moveonorg-endorsement-illinois-governor#stream/0|accessdate=30 January 2018|agency=WVIK|date=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, 2018, Biss lost the Democratic primary to [[J. B. Pritzker]]. He earned  26.70% of the total vote, behind Prizker with 45.13% and ahead of [[Christopher G. Kennedy|C. G. Kennedy]] with 24.37%. \nBiss carried two counties, [[McLean County, Illinois|McLean]] and [[Champaign County, Illinois|Champaign]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Canvas, General Primary Election, March 20, 2018 |url=https://www.elections.il.gov/Downloads/ElectionInformation/VoteTotals/2018GPOfficialVote.pdf |publisher=Illinois State Board of Elections}}</ref>\n\n== Post-senate activities ==\n\nOn September 18, 2018, Biss announced in an email to supporters that he has accepted the position of executive director of the nonprofit Rust Belt Rising, which aims to train and support Democratic candidates in the [[Great Lakes region|Great Lakes states]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Meadows |first1=Jonah |title=Sen. Daniel Biss To Head Democratic Candidate Training Nonprofit |url=https://patch.com/illinois/evanston/sen-daniel-biss-head-democratic-candidate-training-nonprofit |accessdate=19 September 2018 |work=Evanston, IL Patch |date=18 September 2018}}</ref> Biss was succeeded in the Illinois Senate by [[Laura Fine]] on January 6, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.illinoissenatedemocrats.com/caucus-news/106-senator-laura-fine-news/6860-fine-sworn-in-as-state-senator|title=Fine sworn in as State Senator|last=|first=|date=2019-01-07|website=Illinois Senate Democrats|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>\n\nOn August 15, 2019, Biss announced his endorsement of [[Elizabeth Warren]] [[Elizabeth Warren 2020 presidential campaign|for president]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DanielBiss/status/1162009805604761600|title=Endorsement of Elizabeth Warren|last=Biss|first=Daniel|date=August 15, 2019|website=[[Twitter]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 3, 2020|quote=\"A presidential candidate whose rallying cry is \"big structural change\" -- yes, please! ... I'm proud to endorse [[Elizabeth Warren]], who represents a once-in-a-generation opportunity to reform our broken system. I hope you'll join me in supporting her. [pic.twitter.com/LNGu8Bufgb Video]\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Sweet|first=Lynn|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/8/15/20808045/pete-buttigieg-chicago-elizabeth-warren-hires-illinois-director-amy-klobuchar-state-delegate-slates|title=Buttigieg\u2019s Chicago presidential outpost; Warren hires Illinois director; Klobuchar working on state delegate slates|date=August 15, 2019|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|access-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211141043/https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/8/15/20808045/pete-buttigieg-chicago-elizabeth-warren-hires-illinois-director-amy-klobuchar-state-delegate-slates|archive-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref> In January 2020, Biss was selected to be on Warren's slate of 101 potential Illinois delegates to the [[2020 Democratic National Convention]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Bill|url=https://evanstonnow.com/story/government/bill-smith/election-2020/2020-01-04/83994/ten-evanstonians-seek-to-be-democratic|title=Ten Evanstonians seek to be Democratic presidential convention delegates|date=January 4, 2020|work=Evanston Now|access-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402184805/https://evanstonnow.com/story/government/bill-smith/election-2020/2020-01-04/83994/ten-evanstonians-seek-to-be-democratic|archive-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|last=Meadows|first=Jonah|url=https://patch.com/illinois/evanston/these-9th-district-residents-are-potential-convention-delegates|title=These 9th district residents are potential convention delegates|date=January 31, 2020|work=[[Patch Media|Patch]]|access-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224025514/https://patch.com/illinois/evanston/these-9th-district-residents-are-potential-convention-delegates|archive-date=February 24, 2020}}</ref> but Warren suspended her campaign on March 5, before [[2020 Illinois Democratic primary|the presidential primary in Illinois]] on March 17.<ref>{{cite news|last=Goldmacher|first=Shane|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/05/us/politics/elizabeth-warren-drops-out.html|title=Elizabeth Warren, once a front-runner, drops out of presidential race|date=March 5, 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328220831/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/05/us/politics/elizabeth-warren-drops-out.html|archive-date=March 28, 2020|last2=Herndon|first2=Astead|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ [[Illinois House of Representatives]], 17th district: Results, 2008\u20132010<ref name=\"results\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cookcountyclerk.com/elections/results/Pages/default.aspx |title=Election Results |accessdate=July 8, 2013 |publisher=Cook County Board of Elections }}</ref>\n!| Year\n!\n!| Democratic\n!| Votes\n!| Pct\n!\n!| Republican\n!| Votes\n!| Pct\n|-\n| [[Illinois House of Representatives elections, 2008|2008]]\n|\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} |Daniel Biss\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" |25,959\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} |48.52%\n|\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} |'''[[Elizabeth Coulson]]'''\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |'''27,540'''\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} |'''51.48%'''\n|-\n| [[Illinois House of Representatives elections, 2010|2010]]\n|\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | '''Daniel Biss'''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" | '''23,134'''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | '''54.78%'''\n|\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | Hamilton Chang\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" | 19,096\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | 45.22%\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ [[Illinois Senate]], 9th district: Results, 2012\u20132014<ref name=\"results\"/>\n!| Year\n!\n!| Democratic\n!| Votes\n!| Pct\n!\n!| Republican\n!| Votes\n!| Pct\n|-\n| [[Illinois Senate elections, 2012|2012]]\n|\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | '''Daniel Biss'''\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" | '''68,064'''\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | '''66.63%'''\n|\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | Glenn Farkas\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" | 34,081\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | 33.37%\n|-\n| [[Illinois Senate elections, 2014|2014]]\n|\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | '''Daniel Biss'''\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" | '''55,986'''\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | '''100.00%'''\n|\