{"title_page": "Pacific Standard", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{about|the magazine|the pacific standard time|Pacific Time Zone|the production company co-founded by [[Reese Witherspoon]]|Pacific Standard (production company)}}\n{{Infobox magazine\n| image_file = \n| image_size = <!-- 220px -->\n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| editor = [[Nicholas Jackson (editor)|Nicholas Jackson]]\n| editor_title = [[Editor-in-chief]]\n| frequency = Bimonthly\n| total_circulation = 110,332<ref>[http://www.bpaww.com/Bpaww_com/ProductManagement/PDFDisplay.aspx?statement_id=81394&pk=gm23rz2vq2jmymuschqfsytf BPA Worldwide]{{dead link|date=January 2018}}</ref>\n| circulation_year = June 2011\n| category = [[Environmental policy|Environment]], solutions-driven [[journalism]], [[social issues]], [[health]], [[public policy]], [[economics]], [[social science]], [[education]]\n| company = [[The Social Justice Foundation]]\n| publisher = [[Sara Miller McCune]]\n| founded = {{Start date|2008}}\n| country = United States\n| based = [[Santa Barbara, California]]\n| language = [[American English|English]]\n| website = {{URL|https://psmag.com}}\n| issn = 1941-5672\n}}\n'''''Pacific Standard''''' was an American online [[magazine]] that reported on issues of social and [[environmental justice]]. Founded in 2008, the magazine was published in print and online for its first ten years until production of the print edition ceased in 2018 and it transitioned to an online-only format,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psmag.com/magazine/the-next-10-years-of-pacific-standard|title=The Next 10 Years of Pacific Standard|last=Jackson|first=Nicholas|website=Pacific Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref> which folded in 2019. ''Pacific Standard'' was published by [[The Social Justice Foundation]], headquartered in [[Santa Barbara, California]].\n\nOn August 7, 2019, [[Nicholas Jackson (editor)|Nicholas Jackson]], editor-in-chief, stated on Twitter that Pacific Standard was to close after its primary funder abruptly cut off all funding.<ref>{{cite tweet | user=nbj914 | number=1159185980902871041 | date=8 August 2019 | title=Today is an extremely difficult day}}</ref>\n\n== Background: Miller\u2013McCune years ==\n'''''Pacific Standard''''', formerly ''Miller\u2013McCune'' magazine, was launched in 2008 by [[Sara Miller McCune]], the founder and head of [[Sage Publications]]. It was named one of the year's \"hottest launches\" by ''MIN'' magazine<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minonline.com/features/9098.html|title=min magazine 2008: Hottest Magazine Launches|date=November 10, 2008|access-date=November 8, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228232023/http://www.minonline.com/features/9098.html|archive-date=December 28, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and received the same honor from ''[[Library Journal]]'' the following year. It also received the 2008\u20132009 [[Society of Environmental Journalists]] Award for Outstanding Explanatory Journalism and the [[Utne Reader]] Independent Press Award 2009 for science/technology coverage. In 2010, Miller McCune was named by [[Folio (magazine)|''Folio'' magazine]] to the FOLIO: 40 list of publishing innovators: \"At a time when print is becoming a secondary product for many publishers (in mindset if not revenue), Miller\u2013McCune is succeeding with long-form journalism.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.foliomag.com/2010/sarah-miller-mccune | title=Sara Miller McCune, founder, Miller McCune-Magazine}} Foliomag.com, Retrieved May 15, 2012</ref>\n\nIn 2010, the magazine launched ''Miller\u2013McCune LIVE'', a special events program to bring articles to life through comprehensive debate featuring industry leaders. The first debate, on lobbying, took place in September in Washington, D.C. The second debate was held in New York City in November with panelists [[Sree Sreenivasan]] and [[Rachel Sklar]], who dug into the effects of social media on \"real life\" and ways to humanize the Internet.\n\nIn-depth pieces include stories such as \"Native Environmentalism and the Alberta Oil Boom\", \"[[Global Warming]]: the Archaeological Frontier\", \"When [[Facebook]] Is Your Medical Record\", as well as \"Art and [[Alzheimer's]]: Another Way of Remembering\", the story of [[Hilda Goldblatt Gorenstein (Hilgos)]] and the documentary \"''[[I Remember Better When I Paint]]''\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miller-mccune.com/health/art-and-alzheimers-another-way-of-remembering-25996/|title=Miller-McCune website|accessdate=January 19, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110122192129/http://www.miller-mccune.com/health/art-and-alzheimers-another-way-of-remembering-25996/|archivedate=January 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Transition to ''Pacific Standard'' ==\nIn April 2011, editor [[John Mecklin (journalist)|John Mecklin]] announced his resignation, citing \"creative differences\" among other reasons.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/mediawire/129253/miller-mccune-editors-resignation-letter-i-will-be-a-thoughtful-guest-and-leave/ | title=Miller\u2013McCune editor's resignation letter: 'I will be a thoughtful guest and leave' | access-date=2012-05-15 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522001212/http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/mediawire/129253/miller-mccune-editors-resignation-letter-i-will-be-a-thoughtful-guest-and-leave/ | archive-date=2012-05-22 | url-status=dead }} Poynter.org, Retrieved May 15, 2012</ref> On May 17, the organization announced that Maria Streshinsky, former managing editor of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' magazine, would become the editor-in-chief of the magazine.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.psmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/streshinsky-pr.pdf |title=Miller\u2013McCune Names The Atlantic's Maria Streshinsky as Editor-in-Chief |access-date=2012-05-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525222829/http://www.psmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/streshinsky-pr.pdf |archive-date=2012-05-25 |url-status=dead |work=Pacific Standard}}</ref>\n\nOn February 17, 2012, Miller\u2013McCune announced that the magazine's name would be changed to ''Pacific Standard'' as of the May\u2013June 2012 edition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miller-mccune.com/media/announcing-our-new-name-39701/|title=Announcing Our New Name|date=February 17, 2012|access-date=2012-02-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221083326/http://www.miller-mccune.com/media/announcing-our-new-name-39701/|archive-date=2012-02-21|url-status=dead}}</ref> In a May 2012 interview, Streshinsky said that the publication's new name reflected its taking a \"western\" perspective: \"We want to tell the nationally important stories that are coming out of this side of the country, and from the edges of the Pacific.... So many of the nation's biggest shifts have come from the West, and we want to showcase that.\"<ref name=\"jr-ps\">{{cite news | last=Wihbey|first=John|url=http://journalistsresource.org/reference/research/research-chat-pacific-standard-editor-mariastreshinsky/|title=Research chat: ''Pacific Standard'' editor Maria Streshinsky}} ''Journalists Resource'', Retrieved May 15, 2012</ref>\n\nAs of January 2014, the magazine enjoyed its largest website traffic month ever. It continues to get most of its funding from Sage Publications, with much smaller amounts from subscription, newsstand, and website revenue.<ref>Sarah Laskow, [http://www.cjr.org/behind_the_news/pacific_standard_mag.php?page=all \"Meet the 6-year-old mag that just took the internet by storm\"], ''[[Columbia Journalism Review]]'', January 28, 2014.</ref> In 2014, ''Pacific Standard'' was nominated for its first-ever [[National Magazine Awards|National Magazine Award]], presented by the [[American Society of Magazine Editors]], in the category of General Excellence for Literature, Science and Politics Magazines.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.magazine.org/about-asme/pressroom/asme-press-releases/asme/national-magazine-awards-2014-finalists-announced|title=National Magazine Awards 2014 Finalists Announced|accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, digital director [[Nicholas Jackson (editor)|Nicholas Jackson]] was appointed editor-in-chief, and senior editor [[Ryan Jacobs]] was appointed deputy editor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.adweek.com/digital/rd-recap-new-hires-at-elle-com-changes-at-pacific-standard/|title=RD Recap: New Hires at Elle.com; Changes at Pacific Standard|access-date=February 10, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> They quickly brought on creative director Taylor Le<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pubexec.com/article/pacific-standard-adds-two-masthead-taylor-le-named-creative-director-ted-scheinman-joins-senior-editor/all/|title=Pacific Standard Adds Two to Masthead: Taylor Le Named Creative Director; Ted Scheinman Joins as Senior Editor|newspaper=Publishing Executive|access-date=February 10, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> and executive editor Jennifer Sahn.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foliomag.com/people-move-29/|title=People on the Move - Folio|date=August 19, 2015|newspaper=Folio|access-date=February 10, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> Jackson repositioned the magazine to tell \"stories that matter,\" focusing most heavily on social and environmental justice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://psmag.com/introducing-the-new-psmag-com-3309d91fcd6d#.kk4aoivq0|archive-date=2016-06-03|archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20160603100736/https://psmag.com/introducing%2Dthe%2Dnew%2Dpsmag%2Dcom%2D3309d91fcd6d#.kk4aoivq0|url-status=dead|title=Introducing the New PSmag.com|last=Jackson|first=Nicholas|date=April 5, 2016|newspaper=Pacific Standard|access-date=February 10, 2017}}</ref> In 2017, the magazine was honored with its second National Magazine Award.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.adweek.com/digital/mother-jones-wins-magazine-of-the-year-at-2017-ellies/|title=Mother Jones Wins Magazine of the Year at 2017 Ellies|access-date=February 10, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> Also in 2017, ''Pacific Standard''' nonprofit parent changed its name from the Miller-McCune Center for Research, Media, and Public Policy to The Social Justice Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Pacific Standard magazine now published by The Social Justice Foundation {{!}} SAGE Publications Inc| accessdate = 2018-01-27| url = https://us.sagepub.com/en-us/nam/pacificstandardmagazinepublishedbysocialjusticefoundation| date = 2017-09-06}}</ref>\n\n==Readership and topics covered==\nThe magazine was created for opinion leaders, policymakers, and concerned citizens who are interested in developing solutions to some of the world\u2019s toughest social and environmental problems. Its target readers are \"influentials\" who read ''[[The Economist]]'', ''[[The Atlantic]]'', [[Mother Jones (magazine)|''Mother Jones'']], and [[Wired (magazine)|''Wired'']], but former editor-in-chief Streshinsky differentiated ''Pacific Standard'' by focusing on the behavioral and social sciences.<ref name=\"mb-ps\">{{cite news |url=http://www.mediabistro.com/How-To-Pitch-Pacific-Standard-a10698.html|title=How to Pitch: Pacific Standard}} Mediabistro, Retrieved July 23, 2014</ref>\n\nIn an interview, Streshinsky said:\n\n<blockquote>\"... we\u2019re also committed to producing old-fashioned, well-told, deeply reported magazine journalism on subjects and characters of national interest or curiosity\u2014we just want to do it in a way that is especially steeped in the relevant research literature and intellectual context. We value great storytelling and cogent analysis as much as anyone else on the block. And we love \u201cconceptual scoops\u201d\u2014the kind of piece that can powerfully, sharply, and accurately reframe the reader\u2019s understanding of an important, complex subject.\"<ref name=\"mb-ps\"/> </blockquote>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://psmag.com/}}\n\n[[Category:American monthly magazines]]\n[[Category:American science and technology magazines]]\n[[Category:English-language magazines]]\n[[Category:Environmental magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in California]]\n[[Category:Internet properties disestablished in 2019]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{about|the magazine|the pacific standard time|Pacific Time Zone|the production company co-founded by [[Reese Witherspoon]]|Pacific Standard (production company)}}\n{{Infobox magazine\n| image_file = \n| image_size = <!-- 220px -->\n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| editor = [[Nicholas Jackson (editor)|Nicholas Jackson]]\n| editor_title = [[Editor-in-chief]]\n| frequency = Bimonthly\n| total_circulation = 110,332<ref>[http://www.bpaww.com/Bpaww_com/ProductManagement/PDFDisplay.aspx?statement_id=81394&pk=gm23rz2vq2jmymuschqfsytf BPA Worldwide]{{dead link|date=January 2018}}</ref>\n| circulation_year = June 2011\n| category = [[Environmental policy|Environment]], solutions-driven [[journalism]], [[social issues]], [[health]], [[public policy]], [[economics]], [[social science]], [[education]]\n| company = [[The Social Justice Foundation]]\n| publisher = [[Sara Miller McCune]]\n| founded = {{Start date|2008}}\n| country = United States\n| based = [[Santa Barbara, California]]\n| language = [[American English|English]]\n| website = {{URL|https://psmag.com}}\n| issn = 1941-5672\n}}\n'''''Pacific Standard''''' was an American online [[magazine]] that reported on issues of social and environmental justice. Founded in 2008, the magazine was published in print and online for its first ten years until production of the print edition ceased in 2018 and it transitioned to an online-only format,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psmag.com/magazine/the-next-10-years-of-pacific-standard|title=The Next 10 Years of Pacific Standard|last=Jackson|first=Nicholas|website=Pacific Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref> which folded in 2019. ''Pacific Standard'' was published by [[The Social Justice Foundation]], headquartered in [[Santa Barbara, California]].\n\nOn August 7, 2019, [[Nicholas Jackson (editor)|Nicholas Jackson]], editor-in-chief, stated on Twitter that Pacific Standard was to close after its primary funder abruptly cut off all funding.<ref>{{cite tweet | user=nbj914 | number=1159185980902871041 | date=8 August 2019 | title=Today is an extremely difficult day}}</ref>\n\n== Background: Miller\u2013McCune years ==\n'''''Pacific Standard''''', formerly ''Miller\u2013McCune'' magazine, was launched in 2008 by [[Sara Miller McCune]], the founder and head of [[Sage Publications]]. It was named one of the year's \"hottest launches\" by ''MIN'' magazine<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minonline.com/features/9098.html|title=min magazine 2008: Hottest Magazine Launches|date=November 10, 2008|access-date=November 8, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228232023/http://www.minonline.com/features/9098.html|archive-date=December 28, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and received the same honor from ''[[Library Journal]]'' the following year. It also received the 2008\u20132009 [[Society of Environmental Journalists]] Award for Outstanding Explanatory Journalism and the [[Utne Reader]] Independent Press Award 2009 for science/technology coverage. In 2010, Miller McCune was named by [[Folio (magazine)|''Folio'' magazine]] to the FOLIO: 40 list of publishing innovators: \"At a time when print is becoming a secondary product for many publishers (in mindset if not revenue), Miller\u2013McCune is succeeding with long-form journalism.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.foliomag.com/2010/sarah-miller-mccune | title=Sara Miller McCune, founder, Miller McCune-Magazine}} Foliomag.com, Retrieved May 15, 2012</ref>\n\nIn 2010, the magazine launched ''Miller\u2013McCune LIVE'', a special events program to bring articles to life through comprehensive debate featuring industry leaders. The first debate, on lobbying, took place in September in Washington, D.C. The second debate was held in New York City in November with panelists [[Sree Sreenivasan]] and [[Rachel Sklar]], who dug into the effects of social media on \"real life\" and ways to humanize the Internet.\n\nIn-depth pieces include stories such as \"Native Environmentalism and the Alberta Oil Boom\", \"[[Global Warming]]: the Archaeological Frontier\", \"When [[Facebook]] Is Your Medical Record\", as well as \"Art and [[Alzheimer's]]: Another Way of Remembering\", the story of [[Hilda Goldblatt Gorenstein (Hilgos)]] and the documentary \"''[[I Remember Better When I Paint]]''\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miller-mccune.com/health/art-and-alzheimers-another-way-of-remembering-25996/|title=Miller-McCune website|accessdate=January 19, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110122192129/http://www.miller-mccune.com/health/art-and-alzheimers-another-way-of-remembering-25996/|archivedate=January 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Transition to ''Pacific Standard'' ==\nIn April 2011, editor [[John Mecklin (journalist)|John Mecklin]] announced his resignation, citing \"creative differences\" among other reasons.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/mediawire/129253/miller-mccune-editors-resignation-letter-i-will-be-a-thoughtful-guest-and-leave/ | title=Miller\u2013McCune editor's resignation letter: 'I will be a thoughtful guest and leave' | access-date=2012-05-15 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522001212/http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/mediawire/129253/miller-mccune-editors-resignation-letter-i-will-be-a-thoughtful-guest-and-leave/ | archive-date=2012-05-22 | url-status=dead }} Poynter.org, Retrieved May 15, 2012</ref> On May 17, the organization announced that Maria Streshinsky, former managing editor of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' magazine, would become the editor-in-chief of the magazine.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.psmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/streshinsky-pr.pdf |title=Miller\u2013McCune Names The Atlantic's Maria Streshinsky as Editor-in-Chief |access-date=2012-05-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525222829/http://www.psmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/streshinsky-pr.pdf |archive-date=2012-05-25 |url-status=dead |work=Pacific Standard}}</ref>\n\nOn February 17, 2012, Miller\u2013McCune announced that the magazine's name would be changed to ''Pacific Standard'' as of the May\u2013June 2012 edition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miller-mccune.com/media/announcing-our-new-name-39701/|title=Announcing Our New Name|date=February 17, 2012|access-date=2012-02-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221083326/http://www.miller-mccune.com/media/announcing-our-new-name-39701/|archive-date=2012-02-21|url-status=dead}}</ref> In a May 2012 interview, Streshinsky said that the publication's new name reflected its taking a \"western\" perspective: \"We want to tell the nationally important stories that are coming out of this side of the country, and from the edges of the Pacific.... So many of the nation's biggest shifts have come from the West, and we want to showcase that.\"<ref name=\"jr-ps\">{{cite news | last=Wihbey|first=John|url=http://journalistsresource.org/reference/research/research-chat-pacific-standard-editor-mariastreshinsky/|title=Research chat: ''Pacific Standard'' editor Maria Streshinsky}} ''Journalists Resource'', Retrieved May 15, 2012</ref>\n\nAs of January 2014, the magazine enjoyed its largest website traffic month ever. It continues to get most of its funding from Sage Publications, with much smaller amounts from subscription, newsstand, and website revenue.<ref>Sarah Laskow, [http://www.cjr.org/behind_the_news/pacific_standard_mag.php?page=all \"Meet the 6-year-old mag that just took the internet by storm\"], ''[[Columbia Journalism Review]]'', January 28, 2014.</ref> In 2014, ''Pacific Standard'' was nominated for its first-ever [[National Magazine Awards|National Magazine Award]], presented by the [[American Society of Magazine Editors]], in the category of General Excellence for Literature, Science and Politics Magazines.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.magazine.org/about-asme/pressroom/asme-press-releases/asme/national-magazine-awards-2014-finalists-announced|title=National Magazine Awards 2014 Finalists Announced|accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, digital director [[Nicholas Jackson (editor)|Nicholas Jackson]] was appointed editor-in-chief, and senior editor [[Ryan Jacobs]] was appointed deputy editor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.adweek.com/digital/rd-recap-new-hires-at-elle-com-changes-at-pacific-standard/|title=RD Recap: New Hires at Elle.com; Changes at Pacific Standard|access-date=February 10, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> They quickly brought on creative director Taylor Le<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pubexec.com/article/pacific-standard-adds-two-masthead-taylor-le-named-creative-director-ted-scheinman-joins-senior-editor/all/|title=Pacific Standard Adds Two to Masthead: Taylor Le Named Creative Director; Ted Scheinman Joins as Senior Editor|newspaper=Publishing Executive|access-date=February 10, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> and executive editor Jennifer Sahn.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foliomag.com/people-move-29/|title=People on the Move - Folio|date=August 19, 2015|newspaper=Folio|access-date=February 10, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> Jackson repositioned the magazine to tell \"stories that matter,\" focusing most heavily on social and environmental justice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://psmag.com/introducing-the-new-psmag-com-3309d91fcd6d#.kk4aoivq0|archive-date=2016-06-03|archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20160603100736/https://psmag.com/introducing%2Dthe%2Dnew%2Dpsmag%2Dcom%2D3309d91fcd6d#.kk4aoivq0|url-status=dead|title=Introducing the New PSmag.com|last=Jackson|first=Nicholas|date=April 5, 2016|newspaper=Pacific Standard|access-date=February 10, 2017}}</ref> In 2017, the magazine was honored with its second National Magazine Award.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.adweek.com/digital/mother-jones-wins-magazine-of-the-year-at-2017-ellies/|title=Mother Jones Wins Magazine of the Year at 2017 Ellies|access-date=February 10, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> Also in 2017, ''Pacific Standard''' nonprofit parent changed its name from the Miller-McCune Center for Research, Media, and Public Policy to The Social Justice Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Pacific Standard magazine now published by The Social Justice Foundation {{!}} SAGE Publications Inc| accessdate = 2018-01-27| url = https://us.sagepub.com/en-us/nam/pacificstandardmagazinepublishedbysocialjusticefoundation| date = 2017-09-06}}</ref>\n\n==Readership and topics covered==\nThe magazine was created for opinion leaders, policymakers, and concerned citizens who are interested in developing solutions to some of the world\u2019s toughest social and environmental problems. Its target readers are \"influentials\" who read ''[[The Economist]]'', ''[[The Atlantic]]'', [[Mother Jones (magazine)|''Mother Jones'']], and [[Wired (magazine)|''Wired'']], but former editor-in-chief Streshinsky differentiated ''Pacific Standard'' by focusing on the behavioral and social sciences.<ref name=\"mb-ps\">{{cite news |url=http://www.mediabistro.com/How-To-Pitch-Pacific-Standard-a10698.html|title=How to Pitch: Pacific Standard}} Mediabistro, Retrieved July 23, 2014</ref>\n\nIn an interview, Streshinsky said:\n\n<blockquote>\"... we\u2019re also committed to producing old-fashioned, well-told, deeply reported magazine journalism on subjects and characters of national interest or curiosity\u2014we just want to do it in a way that is especially steeped in the relevant research literature and intellectual context. We value great storytelling and cogent analysis as much as anyone else on the block. And we love \u201cconceptual scoops\u201d\u2014the kind of piece that can powerfully, sharply, and accurately reframe the reader\u2019s understanding of an important, complex subject.\"<ref name=\"mb-ps\"/> </blockquote>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://psmag.com/}}\n\n[[Category:American monthly magazines]]\n[[Category:American science and technology magazines]]\n[[Category:English-language magazines]]\n[[Category:Environmental magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in California]]\n[[Category:Internet properties disestablished in 2019]]\n", "name_user": "Daask", "label": "safe", "comment": "linkenvironmental justiceusingFind link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pacific_Standard"}
{"title_page": "Mannomustine", "text_new": "{{Drugbox\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid =\n| IUPAC_name = (2-chloroethyl)({6-[(2-chloroethyl)amino]-2,3,4,5-tetrahydroxyhexyl})amine\n| image = Mannomustine.svg\n| width = \n| image2 =\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename = Degranol\n| Drugs.com = \n| MedlinePlus = \n| pregnancy_AU = D\n| pregnancy_US = D\n| pregnancy_category =\n| legal_status = Rx-only\n| dependency_liability =\n| routes_of_administration = [[Intramuscular injection|Intramuscular]]\n\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data-->\n| bioavailability = \n| protein_bound = \n| metabolism = [[Liver|Hepatic]]\n| elimination_half-life = \n| excretion = [[Kidney|Renal]]\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=10 | H=24 | Cl=4 | N=2 | O=4\n| molecular_weight = 378.12 g/mol\n| smiles = ClCCNC[C@@H](O)[C@@H](O)[C@H](O)[C@H](O)CNCCCl\n| StdInChI = 1S/C10H22Cl2N2O4/c11-1-3-13-5-7(15)9(17)10(18)8(16)6-14-4-2-12/h7-10,13-18H,1-6H2/t7-,8-,9-,10-/m1/s1\n| StdInChIKey = MQXVYODZCMMZEM-ZYUZMQFOSA-N\n| DrugBank = \n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = E60VWA40D2\n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEBI = \n| KEGG_Ref = {{keggcite|correct|kegg}}\n| KEGG = \n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChEMBL_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEMBL = \n| ChemSpiderID = 2298447\n| PubChem = 3033867\n| CAS_number = 576-68-1\n| CAS_supplemental = 551-74-6\n| ATC_prefix=L01\n| ATC_suffix=\n| ATC_supplemental=\n}}\n\n'''Mannomustine''' ([[International Nonproprietary Name|INN]]), also known as '''mannitol nitrogen mustard''', tradename '''Degranol''' is an old [[alkylating antineoplastic agent]] from the group of [[nitrogen mustard]]s. It was first synthesized and characterized in 1957 by Vargha et al.<ref>Vargha et al., J. Chem. Soc. 1957, 805.</ref>\n\nThe mechanism of [[antineoplastic drug|antineoplastic]] activity of mannomustine, like for all other alkylating agents, lies in its ability to [[alkyl]]ate [[DNA]] [[guanine]] [[nucleobase]]s and, thus, to prevent uncoupling of DNA strands, which is a required step for any cell to divide.\n\nMannomustine was, at the time of its creation as a drug, claimed to be considerably less toxic than [[mechlorethamine]]. For example, the LD<sub>50</sub> in rats, for intravenous mannomustine administration route, is claimed to be about 56&nbsp;mg/kg.<ref>Scherf et al., Arzneim.-Forsch. 20, 1467 (1970)</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Mannitol]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Intracellular chemotherapeutic agents}}\n\n[[Category:Alkylating antineoplastic agents]]\n[[Category:Nitrogen mustards]]\n[[Category:Chloroethyl compounds]]\n", "text_old": "{{Drugbox\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid =\n| IUPAC_name = (2-chloroethyl)({6-[(2-chloroethyl)amino]-2,3,4,5-tetrahydroxyhexyl})amine\n| image = Mannomustine.svg\n| width = \n| image2 =\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename = Degranol\n| Drugs.com = \n| MedlinePlus = \n| pregnancy_AU = D\n| pregnancy_US = D\n| pregnancy_category =\n| legal_status = Rx-only\n| dependency_liability =\n| routes_of_administration = [[Intramuscular injection|Intramuscular]]\n\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data-->\n| bioavailability = \n| protein_bound = \n| metabolism = [[Liver|Hepatic]]\n| elimination_half-life = \n| excretion = [[Kidney|Renal]]\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=10 | H=24 | Cl=4 | N=2 | O=4\n| molecular_weight = 378.12 g/mol\n| smiles = ClCCNC[C@@H](O)[C@@H](O)[C@H](O)[C@H](O)CNCCCl\n| StdInChI = 1S/C10H22Cl2N2O4/c11-1-3-13-5-7(15)9(17)10(18)8(16)6-14-4-2-12/h7-10,13-18H,1-6H2/t7-,8-,9-,10-/m1/s1\n| StdInChIKey = MQXVYODZCMMZEM-ZYUZMQFOSA-N\n| DrugBank = \n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = \n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEBI = \n| KEGG_Ref = {{keggcite|correct|kegg}}\n| KEGG = \n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChEMBL_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEMBL = \n| ChemSpiderID = 2298447\n| PubChem = 3033867\n| CAS_number = 576-68-1\n| CAS_supplemental = 551-74-6\n| ATC_prefix=L01\n| ATC_suffix=\n| ATC_supplemental=\n}}\n\n'''Mannomustine''' ([[International Nonproprietary Name|INN]]), also known as '''mannitol nitrogen mustard''', tradename '''Degranol''' is an old [[alkylating antineoplastic agent]] from the group of [[nitrogen mustard]]s. It was first synthesized and characterized in 1957 by Vargha et al.<ref>Vargha et al., J. Chem. Soc. 1957, 805.</ref>\n\nThe mechanism of [[antineoplastic drug|antineoplastic]] activity of mannomustine, like for all other alkylating agents, lies in its ability to [[alkyl]]ate [[DNA]] [[guanine]] [[nucleobase]]s and, thus, to prevent uncoupling of DNA strands, which is a required step for any cell to divide.\n\nMannomustine was, at the time of its creation as a drug, claimed to be considerably less toxic than [[mechlorethamine]]. For example, the LD<sub>50</sub> in rats, for intravenous mannomustine administration route, is claimed to be about 56&nbsp;mg/kg.<ref>Scherf et al., Arzneim.-Forsch. 20, 1467 (1970)</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Mannitol]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Intracellular chemotherapeutic agents}}\n\n[[Category:Alkylating antineoplastic agents]]\n[[Category:Nitrogen mustards]]\n[[Category:Chloroethyl compounds]]\n", "name_user": "Fswitzer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "added FDA UNII to drug box", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mannomustine"}
{"title_page": "Jesse Dayton", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2014}}\n:''For the 19th-century New York politician, see [[Jesse C. Dayton]].''\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Jesse Dayton\n| background          = solo_singer\n| image               = Jesse Dayton.JPG\n| birth_name          = \n| birth_date          = \n| birth_place         = [[Beaumont, Texas]]\n| origin              = \n| genre               =  [[Americana (music)|Americana]], [[Country music|Country]], [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| occupation          = Musician, actor, record producer\n| instrument          = Guitar, singer\n| years_active        = \n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = [[Johnny Cash]], [[Waylon Jennings]], [[Willie Nelson]]\n| website             = {{URL|http://www.jessedayton.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Jesse Dayton''' is an American, [[Austin, Texas]]-based [[Americana (music)|Americana]] artist, best known for his guitar contributions to albums by country musicians including [[Johnny Cash]], [[Waylon Jennings]], and [[Willie Nelson]].<ref name=\"indie1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indie911.com/directory/country-and-western/jesse-dayton |archive-url=https://archive.is/20060507125317/http://www.indie911.com/directory/country-and-western/jesse-dayton |url-status=dead |archive-date=2006-05-07 |title=De beste bron van informatie over indie911. Deze website is te koop! |language=nl |publisher=Indie911.com |date= |access-date=2012-03-04 }}</ref><ref name=\"westword\">{{cite web|last=Solomon|first=Jon|title=Jesse Dayton Wonders Where the Protest Songs Have Gone|url=https://www.westword.com/music/jesse-dayton-talks-bill-clinton-rob-zombie-waylon-jennings-and-nazis-10969705|website=[[Westword]]|date=November 5, 2018|accessdate=December 3, 2018}}</ref> He is also notable for his collaborations with horror film director [[Rob Zombie]], who has commissioned Dayton on multiple occasions to record music to accompany his films.<ref name=\"westword\"/>\n\n==Career==\nDayton was born in [[Beaumont, Texas]], where he was raised on the music of [[George Jones]], [[Hank Williams]], and [[Lefty Frizzell]], all the while harboring an affinity for the spirit of punk with bands like [[the Clash]].<ref name=\"indie1\"/> After touring with two rockabilly bands, the Road Kings and the Alamo Jets, Dayton ventured off into solo territory, recording his Americana-chart-topping record ''Raisin' Cain''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gray |first=Christopher |url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/AMDB/Profile?oid=oid:93829 |title=Austin Music Database |publisher=The Austin Chronicle |date= |accessdate=2012-03-04}}</ref>\n\nWith [[Lucinda Williams]] Dayton performed at [[Bill Clinton]]'s second inaugural ball.<ref name=\"westword\"/>\n\nSince then Dayton has released several different solo albums and worked with a variety of country rock artists, most notably [[Waylon Jennings]] and [[Johnny Cash]] on ''Right for the Time'' (1996)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Right-Time-Waylon-Jennings/dp/B000000NRU |title=Right for the Time: Waylon Jennings: Music |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-04}}</ref> after Jennings injured his picking thumb and required a guitar stand-in. Dayton also contributed guitarwork on albums by [[the Supersuckers]] and [[Kris Kristofferson]].<ref name=\"indie1\"/>\n\nIn 2004, horror film director [[Rob Zombie]] commissioned Jesse Dayton to record an album for the fictional characters Banjo & Sullivan from his sophomore feature ''[[The Devil's Rejects]]''.<ref name=\"westword\"/> The resulting album was a collection of tongue-in-cheek honky-tonk country entitled ''[[Banjo & Sullivan: The Ultimate Collection]]''. In Zombie's ''[[Halloween II (2009 film)|Halloween II]]'', Dayton performs as the lead singer and guitarist of the fictional psychobilly band Captain Clegg & the Night Creatures. He released an album entitled ''Rob Zombie presents Captain Clegg & The Night Creatures'' on August 28, same day as the film ''Halloween II'' premiered.<ref>[http://www.fangoriaonline.com/features/halloween/2731-halloween-ii-captain-clegg-a-the-night-creatures-cd-on-the-way.html]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090607093202/http://www.fangoriaonline.com/features/halloween/2731-halloween-ii-captain-clegg-a-the-night-creatures-cd-on-the-way.html |date=June 7, 2009 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.fangoria.com/musick/lists-of-doom/2893-exclusive-lists-of-doom-xvi-capt-cleggs-top-10-horror-films.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090620001145/http://www.fangoria.com/musick/lists-of-doom/2893-exclusive-lists-of-doom-xvi-capt-cleggs-top-10-horror-films.html |date=June 20, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 he toured with [[John Doe (musician)|John Doe]] both as the opening act and a member of Doe's backing band.<ref name=\"westword\"/> In 2015 Dayton played guitar in the band [[X (American band)|X]] on their US tour, filling in for [[Billy Zoom]] who had been diagnosed with cancer.<ref name=\"westword\"/> In 2016 he again toured with John Doe as well being the opener on the [[Supersuckers]] European and US tours.\n\nOn September 16, 2016, he released his ninth album titled ''The Revealer'' on his Hardcharger Records imprint through [[Blue \u00c9lan Records]].<ref name=\"westword\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n\n* ''Raisin' Cain'' (1995)\n* ''Tall Texas Tales'' (2000)\n* ''Hey Nashvegas'' (2001)\n* ''Country Soul Brother'' (2004)\n* ''South Austin Sessions'' (2006)\n* ''Holdin' Our Own'' (2007)\n* ''Captain Clegg and the Nightcreatures'' (2009; as Captain Clegg and the Nightcreatures)\n* ''One for the Dance Halls'' (2010)\n* ''Jesse Sings Kinky'' (2012)\n* ''The Revealer'' (2016)\n* ''The Outsider'' (2018)\n* ''On Fire in Nashville'' (2019)\n* ''Mixtape Vol. 1'' (2019)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dayton, Jesse}}\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Austin, Texas]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Texas]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Texas]]\n[[Category:Singers from Texas]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Texas]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2014}}\n:''For the 19th-century New York politician, see [[Jesse C. Dayton]].''\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Jesse Dayton\n| background          = solo_singer\n| image               = Jesse Dayton.JPG\n| birth_name          = \n| birth_date          = \n| birth_place         = [[Beaumont, Texas]]\n| origin              = \n| genre               =  [[Americana (music)|Americana]], [[Country music|Country]], [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| occupation          = Musician, actor, record producer\n| instrument          = Guitar, singer\n| years_active        = \n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = [[Johnny Cash]], [[Waylon Jennings]], [[Willie Nelson]]\n| website             = {{URL|http://www.jessedayton.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Jesse Dayton''' is an American, [[Austin, Texas]]-based [[Americana (music)|Americana]] artist, best known for his guitar contributions to albums by country musicians including [[Johnny Cash]], [[Waylon Jennings]], and [[Willie Nelson]].<ref name=\"indie1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indie911.com/directory/country-and-western/jesse-dayton |archive-url=https://archive.is/20060507125317/http://www.indie911.com/directory/country-and-western/jesse-dayton |url-status=dead |archive-date=2006-05-07 |title=De beste bron van informatie over indie911. Deze website is te koop! |language=nl |publisher=Indie911.com |date= |access-date=2012-03-04 }}</ref><ref name=\"westword\">{{cite web|last=Solomon|first=Jon|title=Jesse Dayton Wonders Where the Protest Songs Have Gone|url=https://www.westword.com/music/jesse-dayton-talks-bill-clinton-rob-zombie-waylon-jennings-and-nazis-10969705|website=[[Westword]]|date=November 5, 2018|accessdate=December 3, 2018}}</ref> He is also notable for his collaborations with horror film director [[Rob Zombie]], who has commissioned Dayton on multiple occasions to record music to accompany his films.<ref name=\"westword\"/>\n\n==Career==\nDayton was born in [[Beaumont, Texas]], where he was raised on the music of [[George Jones]], [[Hank Williams]], and [[Lefty Frizzell]], all the while harboring an affinity for the spirit of punk with bands like [[the Clash]].<ref name=\"indie1\"/> After touring with two rockabilly bands, the Road Kings and the Alamo Jets, Dayton ventured off into solo territory, recording his Americana-chart-topping record ''Raisin' Cain''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gray |first=Christopher |url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/AMDB/Profile?oid=oid:93829 |title=Austin Music Database |publisher=The Austin Chronicle |date= |accessdate=2012-03-04}}</ref>\n\nWith [[Lucinda Williams]] Dayton performed at [[Bill Clinton]]'s second inaugural ball.<ref name=\"westword\"/>\n\nSince then Dayton has released several different solo albums and worked with a variety of country rock artists, most notably [[Waylon Jennings]] and [[Johnny Cash]] on ''Right for the Time'' (1996)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Right-Time-Waylon-Jennings/dp/B000000NRU |title=Right for the Time: Waylon Jennings: Music |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-04}}</ref> after Jennings injured his picking thumb and required a guitar stand-in. Dayton also contributed guitarwork on albums by [[the Supersuckers]] and [[Kris Kristofferson]].<ref name=\"indie1\"/>\n\nIn 2004, horror film director [[Rob Zombie]] commissioned Jesse Dayton to record an album for the fictional characters Banjo & Sullivan from his sophomore feature ''[[The Devil's Rejects]]''.<ref name=\"westword\"/> The resulting album was a collection of tongue-in-cheek honky-tonk country entitled ''[[Banjo & Sullivan: The Ultimate Collection]]''. In Zombie's ''[[Halloween II (2009 film)|Halloween II]]'', Dayton performs as the lead singer and guitarist of the fictional psychobilly band Captain Clegg & the Night Creatures. He released an album entitled ''Rob Zombie presents Captain Clegg & The Night Creatures'' on August 28, same day as the film ''Halloween II'' premiered.<ref>[http://www.fangoriaonline.com/features/halloween/2731-halloween-ii-captain-clegg-a-the-night-creatures-cd-on-the-way.html]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090607093202/http://www.fangoriaonline.com/features/halloween/2731-halloween-ii-captain-clegg-a-the-night-creatures-cd-on-the-way.html |date=June 7, 2009 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.fangoria.com/musick/lists-of-doom/2893-exclusive-lists-of-doom-xvi-capt-cleggs-top-10-horror-films.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090620001145/http://www.fangoria.com/musick/lists-of-doom/2893-exclusive-lists-of-doom-xvi-capt-cleggs-top-10-horror-films.html |date=June 20, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 he toured with [[John Doe (musician)|John Doe]] both as the opening act and a member of Doe's backing band.<ref name=\"westword\"/> In 2015 Dayton played guitar in the band [[X (American band)|X]] on their US tour, filling in for [[Billy Zoom]] who had been diagnosed with cancer.<ref name=\"westword\"/> In 2016 he again toured with John Doe as well being the opener on the [[Supersuckers]] European and US tours.\n\nOn September 16, 2016, he released his ninth album titled ''The Revealer'' on his Hardcharger Records imprint through Blue \u00c9lan Records.<ref name=\"westword\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n\n* ''Raisin' Cain'' (1995)\n* ''Tall Texas Tales'' (2000)\n* ''Hey Nashvegas'' (2001)\n* ''Country Soul Brother'' (2004)\n* ''South Austin Sessions'' (2006)\n* ''Holdin' Our Own'' (2007)\n* ''Captain Clegg and the Nightcreatures'' (2009; as Captain Clegg and the Nightcreatures)\n* ''One for the Dance Halls'' (2010)\n* ''Jesse Sings Kinky'' (2012)\n* ''The Revealer'' (2016)\n* ''The Outsider'' (2018)\n* ''On Fire in Nashville'' (2019)\n* ''Mixtape Vol. 1'' (2019)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dayton, Jesse}}\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Austin, Texas]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Texas]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Texas]]\n[[Category:Singers from Texas]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Texas]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Aaronchaotix", "label": "safe", "comment": "Noted a missing page.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jesse_Dayton"}
{"title_page": "William Boyd Dalton", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish association football player}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name                = William Dalton\n|fullname            = William Boyd Dalton<ref name=\"EU Football\">{{cite web |last1=Football |first1=EU |title=EU Football |url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=4188 |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n|birth_date          = {{birth date|df=yes|1870|3|16}} \n|birth_place         = Belfast, Ireland\n|death_date          = {{death date|df=yes|1946|5|19}}\n|death_place         = Toronto, Canada\n|position            = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n|years1              = 1887\u20131888 \n|clubs1              = [[YMCA F.C. (Belfast)|Belfast YMCA]]\n|caps1               = \n|goals1              = \n|years2              = 1890\u20131894\n|clubs2              = [[Linfield F.C.|Linfield]]\n|caps2               = \n|goals2              = \n| nationalyears1 = 1888-1894\n| nationalteam1 = [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland Amateurs]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 11\n| nationalgoals1 = 4\n}}\n\n'''William Dalton''' was an Irish [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].<ref name=\"EU Football\">{{cite web |last1=Football |first1=EU |title=EU Football |url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=4188 |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref> He made his Ireland debut aged 18 years and eight days, and went on to win eleven caps for [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]], scoring four goals, including two on his international debut against [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] in the [[1887\u201388 British Home Championship|1887-88 British Home Championship]]. He also played once for the Irish League XI against England in 1894, and also played and scored in an unofficial international against a Canadian touring side.<ref name=\"NIFG\">{{cite web |first1=NIFG |last1=NIFG |title=NIFG |url=http://nifootball.blogspot.com/2006/10/william-dalton.html |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDalton and his wife Kathryn later emigrated to Canada, where he died aged 76 in 1946.\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Irish association footballers (before 1923)]]\n[[Category:NIFL Premiership players]]\n[[Category:Linfield F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland amateur international footballers]]\n[[Category:Irish League representative players]]\n[[Category:Pre-1950 IFA international footballers]]\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1946 deaths]]\n\n\n{{Northern-ireland-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish association football player}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name                = William Dalton\n|fullname            = William Boyd Dalton<ref name=\"EU Football\">{{cite web |last1=Football |first1=EU |title=EU Football |url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=4188 |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n|birth_date          = {{birth date|df=yes|1870|3|16}} \n|birth_place         = Belfast, Ireland\n|death_date          = {{death date|df=yes|1946|5|19}}\n|death_place         = Toronto, Canada\n|position            = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n|years1              = 1887\u20131888 \n|clubs1              = [[YMCA_F.C._(Belfast)|Belfast YMCA]]\n|caps1               = \n|goals1              = \n|years2              = 1890\u20131894\n|clubs2              = [[Linfield_F.C.|Linfield]]\n|caps2               = \n|goals2              = \n| nationalyears1 = 1888-1894\n| nationalteam1 = [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland Amateurs]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 11\n| nationalgoals1 = 4\n}}\n\n'''William Dalton''' was an Irish [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].<ref name=\"EU Football\">{{cite web |last1=Football |first1=EU |title=EU Football |url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=4188 |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref> He made his Ireland debut aged 18 years and eight days, and went on to win eleven caps for [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]], scoring four goals, including two on his international debut against [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] in the [[1887\u201388_British_Home_Championship|1887-88 British Home Championship]]. He also played once for the Irish League XI against England in 1894, and also played and scored in an unofficial international against a Canadian touring side.<ref name=\"NIFG\">{{cite web |first1=NIFG |last1=NIFG |title=NIFG |url=http://nifootball.blogspot.com/2006/10/william-dalton.html |accessdate=9 March 2020}}}}</ref>\n\nDalton and his wife Kathryn later emigrated to Canada, where he died aged 76 in 1946.\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Irish association footballers (before 1923)]]\n[[Category:NIFL Premiership players]]\n[[Category:Linfield F.C. players]]\n{{Northern-ireland-footy-bio-stub}}\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland amateur international footballers]]\n[[Category:Irish League representative players]]\n[[Category:Pre-1950 IFA international footballers]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "template fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Boyd_Dalton"}
{"title_page": "1991 Libertarian National Convention", "text_new": "{{Infobox National Political Convention\n| year = 1991\n| party = Libertarian\n| election_year = 1992\n| logo =\n| image = Marrou-1988-Richmond.jpg\n| image_size = 175\n| caption = Nominees <br> Marrou and Lord\n| date = August 29\u201331, 1991\n| venue =\n| city = [[Chicago, Illinois]]\n| presidential_nominee = [[Andre Marrou]]\n| presidential_nominee_state = [[Alaska]]\n| vice_presidential_nominee = [[Nancy Lord]]\n| vice_presidential_nominee_state = [[Nevada]]\n| othercandidates = [[Richard Boddie]] of [[California]]\n| previous_year = 1989\n| next_year = 1993\n}}\nThe '''1991 [[Libertarian National Convention]]''' was held in [[Chicago, Illinois]] from August 29 to August 31, 1991. [[Andre Marrou]] of [[Alaska]] was chosen as the  [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]]'s nominee for [[President of the United States|president]] in the [[1992 United States presidential election|1992 election]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-1082708.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231073348/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-1082708.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=December 31, 2013 | title=Libertarian Party Nominates Real Estate Broker for Run at a Million Votes | work=[[The Washington Post]] via [[HighBeam Research]] {{Subscription required}}| date=September 1, 1991 | accessdate=May 27, 2012 | author=Walsh, Edward}}</ref>\n\nLibertarians hold a [[Libertarian National Convention|National Convention]] every two years to vote on party bylaws, platform and resolutions and elect national party officers and a judicial committee. Every four years it nominates presidential and vice presidential candidates.<ref>[http://www.lp.org/organization/bylaws.shtml Libertarian Party Bylaws] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080605025750/http://www.lp.org/organization/bylaws.shtml |date=2008-06-05 }}</ref>\n\n==Voting for presidential nomination==\n\n===First ballot===\nAndre Marrou was elected on the first ballot, gathering a majority of the voting delegates, securing nomination.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mises.org/journals/liberty/Liberty_Magazine_November_1991.pdf | title=My Kind of Town | work=[[Liberty (libertarian magazine)|Liberty]] |via=[[Ludwig Von Mises Institute]] | page=41 | date=November 1991 | accessdate=May 27, 2012 | author=Arthur, Chester Alan | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801144446/http://mises.org/journals/liberty/Liberty_Magazine_November_1991.pdf | archive-date=2012-08-01 | url-status=dead | df= }}</ref>\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; text-align:center;\"\n|+ '''1991 Libertarian Party National Convention total vote count: Round 1'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"\n| Candidate\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Total votes cast\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Percent of votes cast\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"\n| '''[[Andre Marrou]]''' ||bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| '''257'''|| '''53.32%'''\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Gold\"\n| [[Richard Boddie]] ||bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 187|| 38.80%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Yellow\"\n| [[None of the Above]] ||bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 20|| 4.15%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"FFFF66\"\n| [[Hans Schroeder (politician)|Hans Schroeder]] ||bgcolor=\"#FFFF66\"| 7|| 1.45%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFFCC\"\n| [[David Raaflaub]] ||bgcolor=\"#FFFFCC\"| 6|| 1.24%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"LightYellow\"\n| Others (scattered) ||bgcolor=\"LightYellow\"| 5|| 1.04%\n|-\n|-bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n|\n|colspan=\"5\"|\n{| align=\"left\"\n|'''Color key:'''\n|\n|bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| '''1st place'''\n|bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 2nd place\n|bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 3rd place\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFF66\"| 4th place\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFFCC\"| 5th place\n|bgcolor=\"LightYellow\"| 6th place\n|}\n|-\n|-\n|}\n\n==Voting for vice presidential nomination==\nA separate vote was held for the vice presidential nomination.  [[Nancy Lord]] was nominated on the third ballot.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mises.org/journals/liberty/Liberty_Magazine_November_1991.pdf | title=My Kind of Town | work=[[Liberty (libertarian magazine)|Liberty]] |via=[[Ludwig Von Mises Institute]] | pages=41\u201342 | date=November 1991 | accessdate=May 27, 2012 | author=Arthur, Chester Alan | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801144446/http://mises.org/journals/liberty/Liberty_Magazine_November_1991.pdf | archive-date=2012-08-01 | url-status=dead | df= }}</ref>\n\n===First ballot===\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; text-align:center;\"\n|+ '''1991 Libertarian Party National Convention total vote count: Round 1'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"\n| Candidate\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Total votes cast\n|bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"| Percent of votes cast\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"\n| '''[[Richard Boddie]]''' ||bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| '''179'''|| '''40.59%'''\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Gold\"\n| [[Mary Ruwart]] ||bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 129|| 29.25%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"Yellow\"\n| [[Nancy Lord]] ||bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 98|| 22.22%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFF66\"\n| [[Calvin Warburton]] ||bgcolor=\"#FFFF66\"| 19|| 4.31%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"White\"\n| [[Craig Franklin]] ||bgcolor=\"White\"| 10|| 2.27%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"White\"\n| Others (scattered) || 6|| 1.36%\n|-\n|-bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"\n|\n|colspan=\"5\"|\n{| align=\"left\"\n|'''Color key:'''\n|\n|bgcolor=\"Goldenrod\"| '''1st place'''\n|bgcolor=\"Gold\"| 2nd place\n|bgcolor=\"Yellow\"| 3rd place\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFF66\"| 4th place\n|bgcolor=\"white\"| 5th place\n|bg color=\"white\"| 6th place\n|}\n|-\n|-\n|}\n\n===Second ballot===\nAfter the second ballot, Ruwart dropped out of the race.\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; text-align:center;\"\n|+ '''1991 Libertarian Party National Convention total vote count: Round 2'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"\n| Candidate\n|bgcolor=