{"title_page": "Hoba meteorite", "text_new": "{{Infobox meteorite\n|Name= Hoba\n|Image = File:Hoba meteorite (15682150765).jpg\n|Image_caption=The meteorite in 2014 after becoming a tourist attraction\n|Lat_Long={{coord|19|35|32|S|17|56|01|E|display=inline,title}}\n|Type= Iron\n|Class=12\n|Country=Namibia\n|Fall_date=Less than 80,000 years ago\n|Found_date=1920\n}}\nThe '''Hoba'''<ref name=database>{{metbull|11890|Hoba}}</ref> ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|o\u028a|b|\u0259}} {{respell|HOH|b\u0259}}) [[meteorite]], short for '''Hoba West''', is a meteorite that lies on the farm of the same name, not far from [[Grootfontein]], in the [[Otjozondjupa Region]] of [[Namibia]]. It has been uncovered but, because of its large mass, has never been moved from where it fell. The main mass is estimated at more than 60 tonnes.<ref name=database/> It is the largest known intact [[meteorite]] (as a single piece)<ref>{{Cite book |title=Meteorites and their parent planets |last=McSween |first= Harry |date=1999 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=0521583039 |edition=2nd |location=Cambridge |oclc=39210190}}</ref> and about twice as massive as the largest fragment of either the [[Cape York meteorite]] (the 34-tonne Ahnighito) or the [[Campo del Cielo]] (the 30-tonne [[Gancedo (meteorite)|Gancedo]]). It is also the most massive naturally occurring piece of [[iron]] (actually [[ferronickel]]) known on Earth's surface. The name \"Hoba\" comes from [[Khoekhoegowab]] word meaning \"gift\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Place Names of Namibia A Historical Dictionary|last=Cassidy|first=Joseph|publisher=Macmillan Education Namibia Publishers (Pty) Ltd|year=2009|isbn=978-99916-0-654-5|location=Windhoek|pages=37}}</ref> It has now became a attractive tourist destination.\n\n==Impact==\nThe Hoba meteorite impact is thought to have occurred more recently than 80,000 years ago. It is inferred<ref>Field Guide to Meteors and Meteorites - O. Richard Norton and Lawrence Chitwood.  Springer Science + Business Media 2008, {{ISBN|978-1-84800-156-5}}</ref> that the [[Earth's atmosphere]] slowed the object to the point that it impacted the surface at [[terminal velocity]], thereby remaining intact and causing little excavation. Assuming a drag coefficient of about 1.3, the meteor would have been slowed to about {{convert|720|mph|km/s|sigfig=2}} from its speed on entering the Earth's atmosphere, typically in excess of 10&nbsp;km/s for similar objects. The meteorite is unusual in that it is flat on both major surfaces.\n\n==Discovery==\nThe Hoba meteorite left no preserved [[Impact crater|crater]] and its discovery was a chance event. In 1920,<ref name=database/> the owner of the land, Jacobus Hermanus Brits, encountered the object while ploughing one of his fields with an [[cattle|ox]]. During this task, he heard a loud metallic scratching sound and the plough came to an abrupt halt. The obstruction was excavated, identified as a meteorite and described by Mr. Brits, whose report was published in 1920 and can be viewed at the [[Grootfontein]] Museum in Namibia.\n\n[[Friedrich Wilhelm Kegel]] took the first published photograph of the Hoba meteorite.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Spencer |first1=L. J. |last2=Hey |first2=M. H. |title=Hoba (South-West Africa), the largest known meteorite |journal=Mineralogical Magazine and Journal of the Mineralogical Society |url=https://rruff.info/doclib/MinMag/Volume_23/23-136-1.pdf |date=March 1932 |volume=XXIII<!--23--> |number=136 |page=4 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161215172158/http://rruff.info/doclib/MinMag/Volume_23/23-136-1.pdf |archivedate=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n\n==Description and composition==\nHoba is a tabloid body of metal, measuring {{convert|2.7|*|2.7|*|0.9|m|ft}}. In 1920 its mass was estimated at 66 tonnes. Erosion, scientific sampling and vandalism reduced its bulk over the years. The remaining mass is estimated at just over 60 tonnes. The meteorite is composed of about 84% iron and 16% [[nickel]], with traces of [[cobalt]]. It is classified as an [[ataxite]] [[iron meteorite]] belonging to the nickel-rich chemical class [[IVB meteorites|IVB]]. A crust of iron [[hydroxide]]s is locally present on the surface, owing to weathering.\n\n==Modern history==\nIn an attempt to control vandalism and with permission from Mrs. O. Scheel, the owner of the farm at the time, the government of [[South West Africa]] (now Namibia) on March 15, 1955, declared the Hoba meteorite to be a national monument.<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta |volume=31 |issue=9 |date=September 1967 |page=1470 |first=M.F. |last=Comerford |title=Comparative erosion rates of stone and iron meteorites under small-particle bombardment |doi=10.1016/0016-7037(67)90021-X |publisher=Elsevier Science, New York |issn=0016-7037|bibcode=1967GeCoA..31.1457C}}</ref> In 1979 the proclamation was changed to include not only the meteorite but also 25 m x 25 m land on which it is situated.<ref name=Voigt>{{Cite book | title=National Monuments in Namibia: An Inventory of Proclaimed National Monuments in the Republic of Namibia | last=Voigt | first=Andreas | publisher=Gamsberg Macmillan | year=2004 | pages=4\u20135 | isbn= 9991605932 | url=https://books.google.com.na/books?id=h0h0AAAAMAAJ}}</ref> In 1985 [[R\u00f6ssing]] Uranium Ltd. made resources and funds available to the Namibian government to provide additional protection against vandalism. In 1987 Mr. J. Engelbrecht, the owner of Hoba West farm, donated the meteorite and the site where it lies to the state for educational purposes. Later that year, the government opened a tourist centre at the site.<ref name=Voigt/> As a result of these developments, vandalism of the Hoba meteorite has ceased and it is now visited by thousands of tourists every year.  It can be seen from satellite imaging, as per this link.<ref>https://www.google.com/maps/@-19.5925701,17.9336854,51m/data=!3m1!1e3</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=packed height=150px>\nFile:Hoba Meteorite.jpg|The Hoba meteorite before the construction of the circular steps.\nFile:Hoba meteorite00.jpg|A person sitting on the meteorite in 1967\nFile:Tatton Park 2016 205 (4x3).jpg|Part of the Hoba meteorite at [[Tatton Park]] in England.\n</gallery> From: my little pony: GET OFF ROLLADERS BOLLDER! \n\nMy Little Pony - Wikipediaen.wikipedia.org \u203a wiki \u203a My_Little_Pony\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Hoba meteorite}}\n* [[Glossary of meteoritics]]\n* [[List of largest meteorites on Earth]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''[[Universe: The Definitive Visual Guide|Universe: The Definitive Visual Dictionary]]'', Robert Dinwiddie, DK Adult Publishing, (2005), pg. 223.\n* {{cite journal |first=P. E. |last=Spargo |title=The History of the Hoba Meteorite Part I: Nature and Discovery |journal=Monthly Notes of the Astronomical Society of Southern Africa |volume=67 |issue=5/6 |year=2008 |pages=85\u201394 |url=http://www.mnassa.org.za/html/Jun2008/2008MNASSA..67..Jun..85.pdf |access-date=2018-07-24|bibcode=2008MNSSA..67...85S }}\n* {{cite journal |first=P. E. |last=Spargo |title=The History of the Hoba Meteorite Part II: The News Spreads |journal=Monthly Notes of the Astronomical Society of Southern Africa |volume=67 |issue=9/10 |year=2008 |pages=166\u2013177 |url=http://www.mnassa.org.za/html/Oct2008/2008MNASSA..67..Oct..166.pdf |access-date=2018-07-24|bibcode=2008MNSSA..67..166S }}\n* {{cite journal |first=P. E. |last=Spargo |title=The History of the Hoba Meteorite Part III: Known and Loved by All |journal=Monthly Notes of the Astronomical Society of Southern Africa |volume=67 |issue=11/12 |year=2008 |pages=202\u2013211 |url=http://www.mnassa.org.za/html/Dec2008/2008MNASSA..67..Dec..202.pdf |access-date=2018-07-24|bibcode=2008MNSSA..67..202S }}\n\n{{Meteorites}}\n{{Meteorites by name}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hoba Meteorite}}\n[[Category:Meteorites found in Namibia]]\n[[Category:Otjozondjupa Region]]\n[[Category:Geography of Namibia]]\n[[Category:Geology of Namibia]]\n[[Category:National Monuments of Namibia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox meteorite\n|Name= Hoba\n|Image = File:Hoba meteorite (15682150765).jpg\n|Image_caption=The meteorite in 2014 after becoming a tourist attraction\n|Lat_Long={{coord|19|35|32|S|17|56|01|E|display=inline,title}}\n|Type= Iron\n|Class=12\n|Country=Namibia\n|Fall_date=Less than 80,000 years ago\n|Found_date=1920\n}}\nThe '''Hoba'''<ref name=database>{{metbull|11890|Hoba}}</ref> ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|o\u028a|b|\u0259}} {{respell|HOH|b\u0259}}) [[meteorite]], short for '''Hoba West''', is a meteorite that lies on the farm of the same name, not far from [[Grootfontein]], in the [[Otjozondjupa Region]] of [[Namibia]]. It has been uncovered but, because of its large mass, has never been moved from where it fell. The main mass is estimated at more than 60 tonnes.<ref name=database/> It is the largest known intact [[meteorite]] (as a single piece)<ref>{{Cite book |title=Meteorites and their parent planets |last=McSween |first= Harry |date=1999 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=0521583039 |edition=2nd |location=Cambridge |oclc=39210190}}</ref> and about twice as massive as the largest fragment of either the [[Cape York meteorite]] (the 34-tonne Ahnighito) or the [[Campo del Cielo]] (the 30-tonne [[Gancedo (meteorite)|Gancedo]]). It is also the most massive naturally occurring piece of [[iron]] (actually [[ferronickel]]) known on Earth's surface. The name \"Hoba\" comes from [[Khoekhoegowab]] word meaning \"gift\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Place Names of Namibia A Historical Dictionary|last=Cassidy|first=Joseph|publisher=Macmillan Education Namibia Publishers (Pty) Ltd|year=2009|isbn=978-99916-0-654-5|location=Windhoek|pages=37}}</ref> It has now became a attractive tourist destination.\n\n==Impact==\nThe Hoba meteorite impact is thought to have occurred more recently than 80,000 years ago. It is inferred<ref>Field Guide to Meteors and Meteorites - O. Richard Norton and Lawrence Chitwood.  Springer Science + Business Media 2008, {{ISBN|978-1-84800-156-5}}</ref> that the [[Earth's atmosphere]] slowed the object to the point that it impacted the surface at [[terminal velocity]], thereby remaining intact and causing little excavation. Assuming a drag coefficient of about 1.3, the meteor would have been slowed to about {{convert|720|mph|km/s|sigfig=2}} from its speed on entering the Earth's atmosphere, typically in excess of 10&nbsp;km/s for similar objects. The meteorite is unusual in that it is flat on both major surfaces.\n\n==Discovery==\nThe Hoba meteorite left no preserved [[Impact crater|crater]] and its discovery was a chance event. In 1920,<ref name=database/> the owner of the land, Jacobus Hermanus Brits, encountered the object while ploughing one of his fields with an [[cattle|ox]]. During this task, he heard a loud metallic scratching sound and the plough came to an abrupt halt. The obstruction was excavated, identified as a meteorite and described by Mr. Brits, whose report was published in 1920 and can be viewed at the [[Grootfontein]] Museum in Namibia.\n\n[[Friedrich Wilhelm Kegel]] took the first published photograph of the Hoba meteorite.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Spencer |first1=L. J. |last2=Hey |first2=M. H. |title=Hoba (South-West Africa), the largest known meteorite |journal=Mineralogical Magazine and Journal of the Mineralogical Society |url=https://rruff.info/doclib/MinMag/Volume_23/23-136-1.pdf |date=March 1932 |volume=XXIII<!--23--> |number=136 |page=4 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161215172158/http://rruff.info/doclib/MinMag/Volume_23/23-136-1.pdf |archivedate=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n\n==Description and composition==\nHoba is a tabloid body of metal, measuring {{convert|2.7|*|2.7|*|0.9|m|ft}}. In 1920 its mass was estimated at 66 tonnes. Erosion, scientific sampling and vandalism reduced its bulk over the years. The remaining mass is estimated at just over 60 tonnes. The meteorite is composed of about 84% iron and 16% [[nickel]], with traces of [[cobalt]]. It is classified as an [[ataxite]] [[iron meteorite]] belonging to the nickel-rich chemical class [[IVB meteorites|IVB]]. A crust of iron [[hydroxide]]s is locally present on the surface, owing to weathering.\n\n==Modern history==\nIn an attempt to control vandalism and with permission from Mrs. O. Scheel, the owner of the farm at the time, the government of [[South West Africa]] (now Namibia) on March 15, 1955, declared the Hoba meteorite to be a national monument.<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta |volume=31 |issue=9 |date=September 1967 |page=1470 |first=M.F. |last=Comerford |title=Comparative erosion rates of stone and iron meteorites under small-particle bombardment |doi=10.1016/0016-7037(67)90021-X |publisher=Elsevier Science, New York |issn=0016-7037|bibcode=1967GeCoA..31.1457C}}</ref> In 1979 the proclamation was changed to include not only the meteorite but also 25 m x 25 m land on which it is situated.<ref name=Voigt>{{Cite book | title=National Monuments in Namibia: An Inventory of Proclaimed National Monuments in the Republic of Namibia | last=Voigt | first=Andreas | publisher=Gamsberg Macmillan | year=2004 | pages=4\u20135 | isbn= 9991605932 | url=https://books.google.com.na/books?id=h0h0AAAAMAAJ}}</ref> In 1985 [[R\u00f6ssing]] Uranium Ltd. made resources and funds available to the Namibian government to provide additional protection against vandalism. In 1987 Mr. J. Engelbrecht, the owner of Hoba West farm, donated the meteorite and the site where it lies to the state for educational purposes. Later that year, the government opened a tourist centre at the site.<ref name=Voigt/> As a result of these developments, vandalism of the Hoba meteorite has ceased and it is now visited by thousands of tourists every year.  It can be seen from satellite imaging, as per this link.<ref>https://www.google.com/maps/@-19.5925701,17.9336854,51m/data=!3m1!1e3</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=packed height=150px>\nFile:Hoba Meteorite.jpg|The Hoba meteorite before the construction of the circular steps.\nFile:Hoba meteorite00.jpg|A person sitting on the meteorite in 1967\nFile:Tatton Park 2016 205 (4x3).jpg|Part of the Hoba meteorite at [[Tatton Park]] in England.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Hoba meteorite}}\n* [[Glossary of meteoritics]]\n* [[List of largest meteorites on Earth]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''[[Universe: The Definitive Visual Guide|Universe: The Definitive Visual Dictionary]]'', Robert Dinwiddie, DK Adult Publishing, (2005), pg. 223.\n* {{cite journal |first=P. E. |last=Spargo |title=The History of the Hoba Meteorite Part I: Nature and Discovery |journal=Monthly Notes of the Astronomical Society of Southern Africa |volume=67 |issue=5/6 |year=2008 |pages=85\u201394 |url=http://www.mnassa.org.za/html/Jun2008/2008MNASSA..67..Jun..85.pdf |access-date=2018-07-24|bibcode=2008MNSSA..67...85S }}\n* {{cite journal |first=P. E. |last=Spargo |title=The History of the Hoba Meteorite Part II: The News Spreads |journal=Monthly Notes of the Astronomical Society of Southern Africa |volume=67 |issue=9/10 |year=2008 |pages=166\u2013177 |url=http://www.mnassa.org.za/html/Oct2008/2008MNASSA..67..Oct..166.pdf |access-date=2018-07-24|bibcode=2008MNSSA..67..166S }}\n* {{cite journal |first=P. E. |last=Spargo |title=The History of the Hoba Meteorite Part III: Known and Loved by All |journal=Monthly Notes of the Astronomical Society of Southern Africa |volume=67 |issue=11/12 |year=2008 |pages=202\u2013211 |url=http://www.mnassa.org.za/html/Dec2008/2008MNASSA..67..Dec..202.pdf |access-date=2018-07-24|bibcode=2008MNSSA..67..202S }}\n\n{{Meteorites}}\n{{Meteorites by name}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hoba Meteorite}}\n[[Category:Meteorites found in Namibia]]\n[[Category:Otjozondjupa Region]]\n[[Category:Geography of Namibia]]\n[[Category:Geology of Namibia]]\n[[Category:National Monuments of Namibia]]\n", "name