{"title_page": "Nattatreeswarar Temple", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox Hindu temple\n| name               = Natadreeswarar Temple\n| image              =\n| alt          = \n| caption            = Plan of Temple island\n| map_type           = <!-- India Tamil Nadu -->\n| map_caption        = Location in Tamil Nadu\n| coordinates        = {{coord|11.2741784|77.8005477|type:landmark_region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| country            = [[India]]\n| state              = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| district           = [[Erode district|Erode]]\n| location           = Between [[Kangeyampalayam]] and [[Patlur]]\n| elevation_m        = \n| deity      = Agastyiswarar, Shiva\n| festivals          = \n| architecture       = South Indian, Temple\n| temple_quantity    = \n| monument_quantity = \n| inscriptions       = \n| established        = <!-- Need an actual date here: 3000 years ago -->\n| creator            = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Natadreeswarar Temple''' is one of the devoted [[Hindu]] temples dedicated to [[Shiva]], located on hillock island inside the [[Cauvery|River Kaveri]], near the city of [[Erode]], on [[Erode]]-[[Karur]] Highways.\n\n==History==\nTo get rid of any kind of [[Dhosam]]', Agasthiar made a Lingam out of sand, placed it on the hillock in the middle of the river Cauvery, garlanded the Lingam with his ''Rudhratcha Malai'' and sat in deep meditation.\n\nIt was believed that meditation would be disturbed at the dawn of the new year. On the first day of \"Chithirai\" \u2013 Tamil New year day \u2013 Agasthiar was disturbed from his meditation and he tried to remove his ''Rudhratcha Malai'' from the Lingam. Then he heard the holy voice of [[Shiva]] asking him not to disturb the present setup and telling him that he went there not only to bless him alone but also his devotees and whoever goes there and worships him.\n\nThus Lord Shiva established himself on the hillock situated in the middle of the river Kavery in Kangeyampalayam near [[Erode]], Tamil Nadu, India.\n\nLater Agasthiar went to the south and finished his assigned work. He prepared an herbal tablet. On consuming the tablet he could present himself in any place he wanted to go. Using such power he came again to the hillock where he was welcomed and blessed by none other than [[Lord Muruga]].\n\nAbout 1000 years ago [[Chola]] kings constructed the temple and named the deity as Agastheeswarar. The Athee tree located inside the temple is believed to be 3000 years old. Devotees throng this temple in thousands on Tamil New Year day and offer prayers to Him to get His blessings.\n\n==Architecture==\nThe temple constructed on the hillock island is situated in the middle of the river Cauvery - middle not only breadthwise but also lengthwise (at the center between Kudagu, where the river originates and Bay of Bengal at Kaveripoompattinam).\n\n==Transport==\nThe Temple is well connected with City bus services to Erode. All the city buses running in-between [[Erode Central Bus Terminus|Central Bus Terminus]] and [[Pasur, Erode|Pasur]] will make a stop at Kangeyampalayam.\n\nAnd from the banks of Cauvery, Ferry boat Services are available to the temple, as well as to the other bank of the river from [[Patlur]] village, [[Tiruchengode Taluk]] [[Namakkal District]]\n\n==External links==\n* http://temple.dinamalar.com/en/new_en.php?id=822\n\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Erode district]]\n\n\n{{India-hindu-temple-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox Hindu temple\n| name               = Natadreeswarar Temple\n| image              =\n| alt          = \n| caption            = Plan of Temple island\n| map_type           = <!-- India Tamil Nadu -->\n| map_caption        = Location in Tamil Nadu\n| coordinates        = {{coord|11.2741784|77.8005477|type:landmark_region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| country            = [[India]]\n| state              = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| district           = [[Erode district|Erode]]\n| location           = Between [[Kangeyampalayam]] and [[Patlur]]\n| elevation_m        = \n| deity      = Agastyiswarar, Shiva\n| festivals          = \n| architecture       = South Indian, Temple\n| temple_quantity    = \n| monument_quantity = \n| inscriptions       = \n| established        = <!-- Need an actual date here: 3000 years ago -->\n| creator            = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Natadreeswarar Temple''' is one of the devoted [[Hindu]] temples dedicated to [[Lord Shiva]], located on hillock island inside the [[Cauvery|River Kaveri]], near the city of [[Erode]], on [[Erode]]-[[Karur]] Highways.\n\n==History==\nTo get rid of any kind of [[Dhosam]]', Agasthiar made a Lingam out of sand, placed it on the hillock in the middle of the river Cauvery, garlanded the Lingam with his ''Rudhratcha Malai'' and sat in deep meditation.\n\nIt was believed that meditation would be disturbed at the dawn of the new year. On the first day of \"Chithirai\" \u2013 Tamil New year day \u2013 Agasthiar was disturbed from his meditation and he tried to remove his ''Rudhratcha Malai'' from the Lingam. Then he heard the holy voice of [[Lord Shiva]] asking him not to disturb the present setup and telling him that he went there not only to bless him alone but also his devotees and whoever goes there and worships him.\n\nThus Lord Shiva established himself on the hillock situated in the middle of the river Kavery in Kangeyampalayam near [[Erode]], Tamil Nadu, India.\n\nLater Agasthiar went to the south and finished his assigned work. He prepared an herbal tablet. On consuming the tablet he could present himself in any place he wanted to go. Using such power he came again to the hillock where he was welcomed and blessed by none other than [[Lord Muruga]].\n\nAbout 1000 years ago [[Chola]] kings constructed the temple and named the deity as Agastheeswarar. The Athee tree located inside the temple is believed to be 3000 years old. Devotees throng this temple in thousands on Tamil New Year day and offer prayers to Him to get His blessings.\n\n==Architecture==\nThe temple constructed on the hillock island is situated in the middle of the river Cauvery - middle not only breadthwise but also lengthwise (at the center between Kudagu, where the river originates and Bay of Bengal at Kaveripoompattinam).\n\n==Transport==\nThe Temple is well connected with City bus services to Erode. All the city buses running in-between [[Erode Central Bus Terminus|Central Bus Terminus]] and [[Pasur, Erode|Pasur]] will make a stop at Kangeyampalayam.\n\nAnd from the banks of Cauvery, Ferry boat Services are available to the temple, as well as to the other bank of the river from [[Patlur]] village, [[Tiruchengode Taluk]] [[Namakkal District]]\n\n==External links==\n* http://temple.dinamalar.com/en/new_en.php?id=822\n\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Erode district]]\n\n\n{{India-hindu-temple-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Titodutta", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nattatreeswarar_Temple"}
{"title_page": "Richard N. Fogoros", "text_new": "'''Richard N. Fogoros''' (commonly referred as '''DrRich''') is a former professor of medicine, and a longtime practitioner, researcher and author in the fields of [[cardiology]] and [[cardiac electrophysiology]]. He currently makes his living as a consultant in research and development with biomedical companies, and as a writer.\n\n==Education and experience==\n\nRichard Fogoros received his bachelor's degree from [[Duke University]] (1971), and his doctorate in medicine from [[Ohio State University]] (1975). He did postgraduate medical training at the [[University of Pittsburgh]] and [[Stanford University]], and has received board certification in [[Internal Medicine]], [[Cardiology]], and [[cardiac electrophysiology|electrophysiology]].\n\nRichard Fogoros practised and taught [[cardiology|clinical cardiology]] for 20 years, directing [[cardiac electrophysiology]] at the [[University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine]], and then at [[Allegheny General Hospital]] in [[Pittsburgh]]. He was listed in Best Doctors in America from its inception until he retired from practice. He has authored numerous scientific articles, book chapters, and books. He also directs several internet resources about heart diseases and American healthcare.\n\n==Publications==\n*Antiarrhythmic Drugs: A Practical Guide. 2 ed, 2007\n*Electrophysiologic Testing. 4 ed, 2006  \n*Fixing American Healthcare: Wonkonians, Gekkonians, and the Grand Unification Theory of Healthcare. 2007\n*Open Wide and Say Moo! The Good Citizen's Guide to Right Thoughts and Right Actions under Obamacare.  2012\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://heartdisease.about.com Verywell Heart Disease and Cardiology site]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fogoros, Richard N.}}\n[[Category:Cardiac electrophysiologists]]\n[[Category:American cardiologists]]\n[[Category:Duke University alumni]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh faculty]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{US-med-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Richard N. Fogoros''' (commonly referred as '''DrRich''') is a former professor of medicine, and a longtime practitioner, researcher and author in the fields of [[cardiology]] and [[cardiac electrophysiology]]. He currently makes his living as a consultant in research and development with biomedical companies, and as a writer.\n\n==Education and experience==\n\nRichard Fogoros received his bachelor's degree from [[Duke University]] (1971), and his doctorate in medicine from [[Ohio State University]] (1975). He did postgraduate medical training at the [[University of Pittsburgh]] and [[Stanford University]], and has received board certification in [[Internal Medicine]], [[Cardiology]], and [[cardiac electrophysiology|electrophysiology]].\n\nRichard Fogoros practised and taught [[cardiology|clinical cardiology]] for 20 years, directing [[cardiac electrophysiology]] at the [[University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine]], and then at [[Allegheny General Hospital]] in [[Pittsburgh]]. He was listed in Best Doctors in America from its inception until he retired from practice. He has authored numerous scientific articles, book chapters, and books. He also directs several internet resources about heart diseases and American healthcare.\n\n==Publications==\n*Antiarrhythmic Drugs: A Practical Guide. 2 ed, 2007\n*Electrophysiologic Testing. 4 ed, 2006  \n*Fixing American Healthcare: Wonkonians, Gekkonians, and the Grand Unification Theory of Healthcare. 2007\n*Open Wide and Say Moo! The Good Citizen's Guide to Right Thoughts and Right Actions under Obamacare.  2012\n==References==\n((Reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[http://heartdisease.about.com Verywell Heart Disease and Cardiology site]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fogoros, Richard N.}}\n[[Category:Cardiac electrophysiologists]]\n[[Category:American cardiologists]]\n[[Category:Duke University alumni]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh faculty]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{US-med-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "template fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_N._Fogoros"}
{"title_page": "Nedungadu Tantondresswara temple", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2020}}\n'''Tantondresswara Temple''' is an ancient temple located in [[Nedungadu]], [[Karaikal district]], [[Puducherry]] Union territory. This temple was constructed by the [[Chola dynasty|Chola rulers]] , who dedicated this temple to [[Shiva]]. This temple from 1971 is regarded as protected monument.\n\n==History==\nTantondresswara Temple was constructed by the rulers of Chola. The main deity of the temple is '''Tantondreeswara (Lord Shiva)'''. The area of Nedungadu got its name from '''Nedunthuyar Theertha Nayaki''', the consort of Tantondreeswara. Her name means the one who redressed the long grievances of the people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trawell.in/pondicherry/karaikal/tantondreeswara-temple-nedungadu|title=TANTONDREESWARA TEMPLE - NEDUNGADU - TRAVEL INFO|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Protected Monument==\nIn 1948, architectural excavations were conducted in this temple. The officials excavated about 14 Bronze sculptures belonging to 14th century. The excavated bronze idols were of [[Thirugnanasambandhar]], [[Vinayaga|Lord Vinayaga]], [[Manickavasagar]], [[Lord Murugan]], Goddess Uma and dancing postures of Lord Shiva such as [[Tandava|Aanandha Thandavam]]. This temple from 1971 is regarded as a protected monument.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://karaikal.gov.in/GovtOffices/TOURISM/temp6.htm|title=Karaikal Tantondreeswara Temple|website=karaikal.gov.in}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture==\nThe entire temple is made up of Red sandstone. The sanctum enshrines the tall idol of Shivalinga which is the main deity, Tantondreeswara.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiancolumbus.blogspot.com/2016/04/nedungadu.html|title=Indian Columbus: Nedungadu Tantondreeswarar Temple|first=Krishnakumar|last=T.k|date=1 April 2016|publisher=}}</ref> The temple has many inscriptions in the outer walls of the sanctum.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Puducherry}}\n\n[[Category:Karaikal district]]\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Puducherry]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2020}}\n'''Tantondresswara Temple''' is an ancient temple located in [[Nedungadu]], [[Karaikal district]], [[Puducherry]] Union territory. This temple was constructed by the [[Chola dynasty|Chola rulers]] , who dedicated this temple to [[Lord Shiva]]. This temple from 1971 is regarded as protected monument.\n\n==History==\nTantondresswara Temple was constructed by the rulers of Chola. The main deity of the temple is '''Tantondreeswara (Lord Shiva)'''. The area of Nedungadu got its name from '''Nedunthuyar Theertha Nayaki''', the consort of Tantondreeswara. Her name means the one who redressed the long grievances of the people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trawell.in/pondicherry/karaikal/tantondreeswara-temple-nedungadu|title=TANTONDREESWARA TEMPLE - NEDUNGADU - TRAVEL INFO|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Protected Monument==\nIn 1948, architectural excavations were conducted in this temple. The officials excavated about 14 Bronze sculptures belonging to 14th century. The excavated bronze idols were of [[Thirugnanasambandhar]], [[Vinayaga|Lord Vinayaga]], [[Manickavasagar]], [[Lord Murugan]], Goddess Uma and dancing postures of Lord Shiva such as [[Tandava|Aanandha Thandavam]]. This temple from 1971 is regarded as a protected monument.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://karaikal.gov.in/GovtOffices/TOURISM/temp6.htm|title=Karaikal Tantondreeswara Temple|website=karaikal.gov.in}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture==\nThe entire temple is made up of Red sandstone. The sanctum enshrines the tall idol of Shivalinga which is the main deity, Tantondreeswara.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiancolumbus.blogspot.com/2016/04/nedungadu.html|title=Indian Columbus: Nedungadu Tantondreeswarar Temple|first=Krishnakumar|last=T.k|date=1 April 2016|publisher=}}</ref> The temple has many inscriptions in the outer walls of the sanctum.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Puducherry}}\n\n[[Category:Karaikal district]]\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Puducherry]]\n", "name_user": "Titodutta", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nedungadu_Tantondresswara_temple"}
{"title_page": "Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s Synagogue", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[File:Synagogue._Listed_ID_-1799._(SW)._-_V\u00e1rmegye_Rd.,_Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG|300px|thumb]]\n\nThe '''Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s Synagogue''' is a large Jewish religious structure.\n\n== History ==\nThe large, domed synagogue was built in 1930 according to the plans of [[Lip\u00f3t Baumhorn]] and his son-in-law [[Gy\u00f6rgy Somogyi]] in an eclectic style decorated with medieval European and Eastern elements. The large building was severely dilapidated by the beginning of the 21st century and is currently being renovated. It no longer has a religious function, but is intended to serve as a venue for cultural programs in the future.\n\n== Gallery ==\n\n<gallery>\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. (S). - V\u00e1rmegye Rd., Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s, Hungary.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. Choir level plan (int). - Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. (N). - V\u00e1rmegye Rd., Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s, Hungary.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. Main door. - Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. Cupola. - V\u00e1rmegye Rd., Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. Cupolas. - V\u00e1rmegye Rd., Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. Photo exhibit. - Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. 2nd floor. (int). - Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. Chairs (int). - Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. Cupola (int) 02. - Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. Pillar heads. (int). - Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. Arc by worm s eye (int) . - Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\n</gallery>\n\n== Sources ==\n* https://turizmus.com/desztinaciok/felujitas-utan-turisztikai-latvanyossag-lesz-a-gyongyosi-zsinagoga-1155719\n* (szerk.) Ger\u0151 L\u00e1szl\u00f3: ''Magyarorsz\u00e1gi zsinag\u00f3g\u00e1k'', M\u0171szaki K\u00f6nyvkiad\u00f3, Budapest, 1989, {{ISBN|963-10-8231-8}}\n\n[[Category:Synagogues in Hungary]]\n\n{{improve categories|date=April 2020}}\n[[Category:History Hungary]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[File:Synagogue._Listed_ID_-1799._(SW)._-_V\u00e1rmegye_Rd.,_Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG|300px|thumb]]\n\nThe '''Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s Synagogue''' is a large Jewish religious structure.\n\n== History ==\nThe large, domed synagogue was built in 1930 according to the plans of [[Lip\u00f3t Baumhorn]] and his son-in-law [[Gy\u00f6rgy Somogyi]] in an eclectic style decorated with medieval European and Eastern elements. The large building was severely dilapidated by the beginning of the 21st century and is currently being renovated. It no longer has a religious function, but is intended to serve as a venue for cultural programs in the future.\n\n== Gallery ==\n\n<gallery>\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. (S). - V\u00e1rmegye Rd., Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s, Hungary.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. Choir level plan (int). - Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. (N). - V\u00e1rmegye Rd., Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s, Hungary.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. Main door. - Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. Cupola. - V\u00e1rmegye Rd., Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. Cupolas. - V\u00e1rmegye Rd., Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. Photo exhibit. - Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. 2nd floor. (int). - Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. Chairs (int). - Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. Cupola (int) 02. - Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. Pillar heads. (int). - Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\nSynagogue. Listed ID -1799. Arc by worm s eye (int) . - Gy\u00f6ngy\u00f6s.JPG\n</gallery>\n\n== Sources ==\n* https://turizmus.com/desztinaciok/felujitas-utan-turisztikai-latvanyossag-lesz-a-gyongyosi-zsinagoga-1155719\n* (szerk.) Ger\u0151 L\u00e1szl\u00f3: ''Magyarorsz\u00e1gi zsinag\u00f3g\u00e1k'', M\u0171szaki K\u00f6nyvkiad\u00f3, Budapest, 1989, {{ISBN|963-10-8231-8}}\n\n[[Category:Synagogues in Hungary]]\n\n{{improve categories|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Jarchdance", "label": "safe", "comment": "Categorization Update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gy%C3%B6ngy%C3%B6s_Synagogue"}
